<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Influx of Kazakhs Changes Kazakhstan's Ethnic Makeup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA ATA, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Influx of Kazakhs and exodus of
other ethnic groups would change Kazakhstan's population makeup in
the near future, a newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A report in the newspaper Ecological Messenger projected that
Kazakhs would account for 57 percent of the country's population
by 2015, 11 percent up from their current level.
</P>
<P>
Population experts attributed the change to immigration. More
Kazakhs would pour into Kazakhstan from neighboring countries and
other ethnic groups would begin an exodus out of the country.
</P>
<P>
Statistics showed that Kazakhstan received some 2 million
immigrants during the 1991-1996 period, and a total of 721,000
people left for other countries during this time.
</P>
<P>
A January 1995 census showed there were 7.6 million Kazakhs and
5.8 million Russians in the country's population of 16.6
million. The number of Kazakhs would shoot up to 10 million and
that of Russians would drop to 3.6 million. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
