<DOCNO> XIE19980108.0003 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq to Start Exporting Oil Next Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Oil Minister Amir Mohammed
Rashid announced today that Iraq will start exporting crude oil
within the third phase of the oil-for-food deal early next week
from the Iraqi port of Al-Bakr and the Turkish port of Ceyhan.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference here, Rashid said that Iraq this
morning began pumping out oil to the oil tanks in both Al-Bakr and
Ceyhan for export
</P>
<P>
Rashid said that Iraq will give priority to the nations and
companies that support lifting the seven-year-old U.N. sanctions
on Iraq, and that there are no restrictions on Iraq's dealing with
any nation or company.
</P>
<P>
Iraq's oil pricing mechanism has been submitted to the
U.N. Sanctions Committee for approval, he said, adding the pricing
plan is expected to be approved within 48 hours.
</P>
<P>
Iraq stopped exporting oil early last month, claiming that it
will not sell oil under the third phase of the oil-for-food deal
between Iraq and the United Nations until the U.N. agrees to its
new plan for distribution of food, medicine and other necessities.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan Tuesday approved the
distribution plan.
</P>
<P>
The oil-for-food deal, which came into effect in December,
1996, allows Iraq to export 2 billion U.S. dollars of oil over six
months to buy food and other humanitarian goods. The third phase
of the deal was approved by the U.N. Security Council on December
4, 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
