<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Urges Algeria to Discuss Steps Ending Killings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Britain, the current rotating
European Union (EU) Presidency state, urged here today the
Algerian government to hold talks with the EU in a bid to put an
end to the massive massacres in Algeria.
</P>
<P>
During a BBC television interview, British Foreign Secretary
Robin Cook said that the Algerian massacres will be a priority of
the British EU presidency and the 15-nation bloc may also be
prepared to help provide aid to communities shattered by the
massacres.
</P>
<P>
Cook, who had earlier proposed to send a high-level EU
delegation to Algeria, stressed that the urgent objective must be
to contain the terrorists.
</P>
<P>
"We need to make it clear to the Algerian government that the
deep concern that exists in Algeria is shared in the wider
community and to explore with them how they might be able to
perform more successfully against the terrorists," he said.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that hundreds of Algerian civilians have been
killed in the first few days of the holy Moslem month of Ramandan
and the Armed Islamic Group was likely to be blamed for most
killings.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Secretary said that the Algerian situation would be
put on the agenda of the EU Foreign Affairs Council meeting due to
be held on January 26. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
