<DOCNO> XIE19980108.0005 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: China's Relief Efforts for Snowstorm Victims in Tibet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, January 7 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government has, over
the past few months, exhibited extraordinarily great concern over
the snowstorm-hit people in the Tibet Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Large amounts of financial and material assistance have been
sent to the affected areas, mainly in north Tibet's Nagqu
Prefecture, where many people have suffered from devastation
by the accumulation of heavy snow since last September.
</P>
<P>
A number of senior government officials, including Vice-Premier
Jiang Chunyun and State Councillor Li Guixian, have helped direct
relief activities and called on the local government and the
armed forces to provide full support for the victims.
</P>
<P>
The People's Liberation Army has sent vehicles and personnel to
assist the victims, with military aircraft airlifting large
quantities of relief materials to the affected areas.
</P>
<P>
The regional government has played an extremely important role
by dispatching eight rescue teams to join in the relief efforts.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the regional government has provided 27.25
million yuan in relief funds, 350 tons of food and 500 tons of
coal to the affected counties.
</P>
<P>
Local governments from throughout the nation have also donated
relief materials to Tibet.
</P>
<P>
Command centers have been set up in all the devastated areas in
order to ensure the smooth shipment and distribution of relief
supplies and funds to the victims.
</P>
<P>
"The snowstorm in 1927 killed tens of thousands of Tibetans,"
said Losang, an 84-year-old Tibetan herdsman. "No one
has died of starvation or exposure when snowstorms hit Tibet last
September, although it was much heavier than that in 1927.
</P>
<P>
"We will never forget the love and kindness exhibited by the
government." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
