<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-07 16:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian Bank Denies Ties with Israeli Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, January 7 (Xinhua) -- The National Bank of Iran has
denied reports that it is cooperating with the Bank Hapoalim of
Israel, the Iranian newspaper Salam reported today.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, the Iranian bank said that it cut off relations
with the Israeli bank in 1980 and has no communication with it
since then, according to the paper.
</P>
<P>
It described the report about its cooperation with the Israeli
bank as "mere lie".
</P>
<P>
Israel radio recently reported that Bank Hapoalim, one of the
three leading banks in Israel, retains ties with the Iranian bank
during the past five years despite the severance of relations
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The radio also said that representatives from the two banks
signed an agreement in Cairo in 1992 on direct exchange of credit
documents.
</P>
<P>
Last month, the Iranian Foreign Ministry denied reports about
cooperation between Iran and Israel, saying that the reports of
the Israeli media are aimed at distorting the image of the Islamic
Republic. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
