<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Starts Geological Prospecting in Caspian Sea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Iran announced today that it has
started geological prospecting operations in the Caspian Sea in
order to confirm its oil and gas reserves, Tehran radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Iran's Deputy Oil Minister for Oil and Gas in the Caspian Sea
Ali Majedi was quoted as saying that it was the first time for
Iran to carry out geological prospecting works in the Caspian sea.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the prospecting operation was an essential step
for the country to estimate the oil and gas reserves in the area.
</P>
<P>
Although the Caspian littoral states and some international
institutions have announced their estimates about the oil and gas
reserves in the Caspian Sea, he said, the estimates could not be
confirmed because prospecting works have not been carried out
in the area.
</P>
<P>
The Caspian Sea, with an estimated reserve of 15.5 billion
barrels of crude oil and some 8.3 trillion cubic meters of natural
gas, is reported to be another oil and gas production center like
the Gulf.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the legal status of the sea, Majedi said that it
comprises the rights of sea navigation, exploitation of natural
resources over and under the seabed and environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
However, the five Caspian littoral countries, namely Iran,
Russia, Khazakhstan, Turkmenistan and Azerbaijan, have not reached
an agreement over the issue, he said, adding that the most
serious difference among the littoral states was how to explore
the natural resources in the sea.
</P>
<P>
Iran has repeatedly announced opposition to any unilateral
exploitation of the natural resources in the Caspian Sea, urging
the littoral states to speed up their negotiations to determine
the legal status of the sea.
</P>
<P>
Last November, Iran lodged a strong protest against Azerbaijan
after Baku started its oil exploitation from the Cheragh
reservoir of the Caspian Sea. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
