<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 12 Kilograms of Pure Heroin Seized in Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Turkish police have seized 12
kilograms of pure heroin in operations against drug trafficking
in Anatolia, central Turkey, semi-official Anatolia News Agency
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The agency quoted Eskisehir Security Director Aydin Genc as
saying that the Turkish police stopped a car from Gaziantep
province bordering Syria to Eskisehir province on Friday and
seized the pure heroin hidden in the vehicle.
</P>
<P>
The police also detained five people in connection with the
drug trafficking, said the police officer.
</P>
<P>
Turkey is a key transit route of drugs to Europe from the area
bordering Afghanistan and Pakistan. In 1996, Turkish police seized
4.4 tonnes of heroin, or 40 percent of the world's total haul,
12.3 tonnes of hashish, 233 kilograms of opium, 13 kilograms of
cocaine and 1,157 kilograms of base morphine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
