<DOCNO> XIE19980108.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU: FIFA'S Agents' Licence System Clumsy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, January 7 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission (EU)
said it would warn world soccer's ruling body FIFA that its
licensing system for the agents of professional players was too
heavy-handed on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Willy Helin, spokesman for EU's Competition Commissioner Karel
Van Miert, said the Commissioner had asked for a rapid warning
letter regarding the licence system for professional player agents
be sent to FIFA.
</P>
<P>
The Commission particularly took aim at a requirement that
prospective agents make a deposit of 200,000 Swiss francs (about
135,593 U.S. Dollars) to obtain a licence.
</P>
<P>
Helin said the process for agents must get approval by both
their national federations and FIFA was rather heavy-handed.
</P>
<P>
The Commission was reacting to complaints, saying that FIFA
rules may infringe EU regulations banning abuse of dominant
position and other restrictive practices.
</P>
<P>
The agents' licensing system was introduced to prevent the
abuse of unqualified agents acting as go-betweens who were accused
of racking up transfer fees artificially.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, the European Court of Justice banned transfer fees for
out-of-contract players and removed limits on the number of
foreign players playing in clubs throughout the 15-nation bloc.
</P>
<P>
The Commission reiterated on Wednesday that it would not allow
such transfer fees despite allegations that the new system was
threatening small clubs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
