<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. New Home Sales Climb Up in November to 11-year High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 7 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. new home sales went
up in November to the highest level in more than 11 years, the
Commerce Department reported here today.
</P>
<P>
Stimulated by strong consumer confidence and low mortgage
rates, new single-family homes were sold at a seasonally adjusted
annual rate of 830,000, the highest since April 1986, the
department said. The figure represented a 5.1 percent gain from
October, the sharpest in a year.
</P>
<P>
New home sales surged 23.4 percent to a rate of 79,000 in the
East, highest in six months. They jumped 14.9 percent in the
Midwest to a rate of 162,000, the most since December 1993, and
4.9 percent in the South to a rate of 382,000, the most since
February.
</P>
<P>
Strong sales pushed the inventory of unsold homes down by 1
percent to 285,000 in November. That's a 4.2-months supply at the
current sales rate, the lowest backlog since July 1971.
</P>
<P>
The median price of a new home was 140,000 U.S. dollars in
November, a 2.4 percent drop from a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
with unemployment at a 24-year low of 4.6 percent in November,
consumer confidence has soared to the highest level since 1969.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
