<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Polish Population Increased Slowly in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Poland was a nation of 38.66
million people at the end of 1997, or 20,000 more than the total
in 1996, with the lowest growth since World War II.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the Polish Central Statistics Bureau showed the
country's population increased only 0.1 percent three years in a
row, due to a low natural population growth rate in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
The migration trend, now gaining momentum, also contributes to
the slow growth, as each year about 20,000 Poles move outside and
only 8,000 foreigners immigrate into the country.
</P>
<P>
The number of city dwellers are 23,000 more than those in the
countryside, resulting in the minimum gap since 1945.
</P>
<P>
The trend of moving from rural to urban areas has been
stagnated, while more urban dwellers are moving into small cities.
</P>
<P>
Polish women count for 51 percent of the population with
average life expectancy of 76.6 years, compared to men's 68.1
years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980108.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> DHA Reports on the Flooding Situation In Somalia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
UNITED NATIONS, January 7 (Xinhua) -- More than 1,800 people
have died in Somalia as a result of the floods, a
latest report from the United Nations Department of Humanitarian
Affairs (DHA) said here today.
</P>
<P>
In the report, DHA says the United Nations Coordinator for
Somalia has confirmed that as of December 31, 1997, 1,855 people
had died and approximately one million are still at risk. More
than 33,360 livestock had also been killed in the floods.
</P>
<P>
Severe diarrhoea, malaria and respiratory infections are
reported to be widespread and have already taken a heavy toll.
Cholera outbreaks have been confirmed in Mogadishu and Merca,
and there are sporadic cholera cases in Kismayo, says DHA.
</P>
<P>
United Nations agencies and nongovernmental organizations
have appealed for 12.8 million U.S. dollars to move their joint
operation from the first phase of emergency rescue and relief
into a new phase of continued relief and rehabilitation. The
phase is expected to last until at least June 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
