<DOCNO> XIE19980108.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-07 16:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli-Turkish-US Naval Exercise Ends </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 7 (Xinhua) -- The navies of Israel, Turkey
and the United States ended today their one-day joint maneuver in
eastern Mediterranean Sea.
</P>
<P>
Two Israeli corvettes, two Turkish frigates and one
U.S. destroyer took part in the exercise, code-named Reliant
Mermaid, which was held some 30 to 150 kilometers off the Israeli
coast.
</P>
<P>
The ships set off from the Haifa Port in northern Israel early
this morning to begin the exercise, which involved over 1,000
sailors from the three countries.
</P>
<P>
Several U.S. and Israeli helicopters and an Israeli
reconnaissance plane also joined the small fleet in conducting
drills on searching for and rescuing ships and sailors in distress
on the sea.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai flew to the Israeli
Saar 5 corvette to inspect the drills. Rony Ben Yehuda, Israeli
Liaison officer aboard the U.S. destroyer, described the
search-and-rescue exercise as successful, saying that Israeli
navy would hold more exercises with Turkish and Jordanian navies
in the future.
</P>
<P>
The three-way naval exercise has been widely condemned by the
Arab world despite the assurances of the three countries that the
exercise was not targeting any other country.
</P>
<P>
The Arab world has become increasingly critical of Turkey,
accusing it of forging a strategic relationship with Israel mainly
aimed at deterring Syria.
</P>
<P>
Israeli fighter plane pilots have been conducting long-range
flight drills over Turkish air space under a military cooperation
deal signed with Turkey in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Arab countries such as Syria, Lebanon and Iran blasted the
Israeli-Turkish alliance and the three-way naval exercise for
destabilizing the region.
</P>
<P>
Jordan, the only Arab country that maintains close ties with
Israel, sent its Naval Commander Hussein Khassawneh to observe the
drill. But Egypt has refused the invitation to send observers to
the drill. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
