<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Ex-President to Be Prosecuted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 7 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's former
state president P W Botha would have to appear in a court since
he refused to appear before the Truth and Reconciliation
Commission (TRC).
</P>
<P>
Botha would be summoned to the George Regional Court in the
Western Cape Province on January 23, South African Press
Association quoted Western Cape Attorney-General Frank Kahn as
saying today.
</P>
<P>
Botha will face a two-year imprisonment or a fine of 20,000
Rand (4,080 U.S. dollars) if convicted on the main charge of
failing to appear before the TRC.
</P>
<P>
The alternative charge against Botha is hindering the
commission in the execution of its duties.
</P>
<P>
Kahn told a news conference that the decision was hard to make
considering Botha's age and health.
</P>
<P>
"He is almost 82 years of age and no attorney-general in any
civilized country lightly decides to prosecute a person of his
age, especially given Mr. Botha's medical history."
</P>
<P>
Kahn said he had considered all the circumstances and decided
that a prosecution was warranted in law and in the public
interest.
</P>
<P>
He added that the TRC had decided not to press charges in
relation to media references to its standing, and there would be
no further charges.
</P>
<P>
Botha has called the truth commission "a circus" and a "witch
hunt" against apartheid leaders, and said repeatedly that he
would not testify before it.
</P>
<P>
Botha had defied three subpoenas of the TRC for hearings of
the role of the former State Security Council, which he chaired
in height of the apartheid conflict.
</P>
<P>
TRC Chairman Desmond Tutu laid formal criminal charges against
him on December 19 when he failed to turn up at the hearing for a
third time in Cape Town.
</P>
<P>
Tension between Botha and the TRC flared up in mid-November
last year when Botha told a Sunday Afrikaans newspaper that he
would rather be prosecuted than appear before the TRC.
</P>
<P>
Botha, who was president between 1984 and 1989, refused to
apologize for the activities of his government, which vehemently
implemented apartheid policies. He insisted that he had done
nothing wrong. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
