<HEADLINE> Japan's Six Opposition Parties Agree to Form Diet Bloc </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Six Japanese opposition parties
decided Wednesday to form a joint parliamentary bloc to seek to
bring down Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto's government.
</P>
<P>
The six parties -- the Democratic Party of Japan (DPJ), the
Taiyo Party, From Five, the Democratic Reform Party, the New Party
Fraternity and Voice of the People, as well as some independents,
will form a bloc of 97 members in the 500-seat House of
Representatives or the lower house.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the six parties said the bloc, to be headed by
Former Justice Minister Megumu Sato, was to be named the People's
Confederation of Democrats, Fraternity and Taiyo, or Minyuren.
</P>
<P>
The six parties and the Reform Club will also make a joint
group of 44 members in the 252-seat House of Councillors or the
upper house.
</P>
<P>
The two blocs will be the largest opposition groups in each
house, but will still be far weaker than the ruling Liberal
Democratic Party which has 259 and 118 seats in the lower and
upper houses respectively.
</P>
<P>
In a declaration, the six parties said that the new bloc will
demand that the government give precedence in the short term to
stimulating the economy instead of reducing the country's fiscal
deficits.
</P>
<P>
They also said they were determined to forward their proposals
to improve the economy at the 150-day regular Diet (parliament)
session which convenes on Monday and fight against the Hashimoto
government.
</P>
<P>
The leaders of the six parties reached the accord after two
days of deliberation.
</P>
<P>
The New Party Fraternity, Voice of the People and Reform Club
are three of the six groups formed after the New Frontier Party
(NFP) was dissolved in late December, while Taiyo and From Five
were formed by politicians who previously defected from the NFP.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
