<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Car Sales Surge In UK With Imports Taking bigger share </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 7 (Xinhua) -- More than 2.17 million cars were
sold last year, the third best on record in Britain, according to
the figures released here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Society of Motor Manufacturers and Traders (SMMT) announced
that 1997 sales were up 7 per cent from the 2.025 million recorded
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Registrations in December reached 84,000 cars, up from 78,141
recorded during the same month in 1996, SMMT said.
</P>
<P>
But the market still remains below its peak of 2.3 million
sales recorded in the boom year of 1989.
</P>
<P>
The SMMT figures also show that imports took a rising share of
the market, accounting for more than 65 per cent of total sales.
</P>
<P>
The Retail Motor Industry Federation (RMIF) said building
society windfalls and booming consumer confidence had boosted the
market, offsetting the rises in interest rates.
</P>
<P>
But Christopher Macgowan, the RMIF's chief executive, predicted
sales would drop back slightly to 2.15 million this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
