<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Overhaul of Canada's Immigration System Urged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, January 7 (Xinhua) -- A massive overhaul of Canada's
immigration policy is needed to restore public confidence in the
system, according to a government-appointed panel.
</P>
<P>
The panel stressed the need for simpler immigration rules and
more stringent controls on people who claim refugee status in
Canada.
</P>
<P>
In a report released Tuesday, the panel recommended a yearly
cap on the number of newcomers and places greater emphasis on
English and French proficiency among all immigrants, including big
investors.
</P>
<P>
Immigrants who enter Canada without a basic knowledge of either
language should pay a tuition fee to offset the cost of language
training, it said.
</P>
<P>
The report also recommended the creation of two separate pieces
of legislation, one that deals with immigration and citizenship,
and another that covers refugees.
</P>
<P>
The report will open to public consultations next month. After
that, government bureaucrats will set to work on crafting changes
to the existing immigrant and refugee guidelines.
</P>
<P>
The new legislation could be ready by the end of this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
