<DOCNO> XIE19980108.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bonn Buries Hope for Early Tax Reform in Germany </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, January 7 (Xinhua) -- The German government Wednesday
decided to drop its attempt to seek a compromise this year with
the main opposition Social Democratic Party (SPD) on a major tax
reform in the country, saying that it is now up to the voters to
make the final decision.
</P>
<P>
German Chancellory Minister Friedrich Bohl said in a statement
Wednesday that because the SPD was not ready for major
compromises, further tax negotiations this year would not "make
any sense".
</P>
<P>
He also announced that German Chancellor Helmut Kohl's ruling
coalition would hold on to its original tax reform package which
incorporates a net tax cut of 30 billion German marks (16.8
billion U.S. dollars) and would seek voters' support for the plan
during the next general elections scheduled for September 27, this
year.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made Wednesday by leaders of the German ruling
coalition consisting of Kohl's Christian Democratic Union (CDU),
its Bavarian sister party Christian Social Union (CSU) and the
junior partner Free Democratic Party (FDP).
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that the government's decision on Wednesday had
made it technically impossible to implement any major tax reform
in Germany by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Tax reform is one of the major initiatives launched by Kohl's
government last year to boost the country's competitiveness as an
investment site and to attack the country's record high
unemployment.
</P>
<P>
The SPD has used its majority in the upper house of the German
parliament to block the government plan, saying that it is too
costly and socially unfair.
</P>
<P>
In reaction to the government's refusal to conduct further
negotiations, the SPD said Wednesday that it would consider
whether it is now necessary to draft its own tax reform plan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
