<DOCNO> XIE19980108.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-07 17:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian Museum to Be Under Tighter Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 7 (Xinhua) -- The Egyptian Antiquities Museum in
downtown Cairo will soon be well protected under a security plan,
Egypt's Culture Minister Farouk Hosni said today.
</P>
<P>
The security plan that was implemented almost 14 months
ago in the Egyptian treasure house will be "fully effective" as
early as next month, Hosni, also Chairman of the Higher
Antiquities Council, told the Middle East News Agency.
</P>
<P>
"The new plan includes using high-tech to secure all parts of
the museum and its surrounding areas against theft, fire or
terrorist attacks," he said.
</P>
<P>
Up to 190 surveillance cameras have already been fixed on all
the doors, entrances and exits inside the museum and its
storehouse to provide the museum with a 24-hour protection, he
added.
</P>
<P>
The cost of the new security plan is estimated at 10 million
Egyptian pounds (2.94 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The protection of the museum, which houses some of the world's
most fascinating antiquities such as the mummies of many pharaonic
kings, is part of a comprehensive one-billion-pound drive to
enhance security in all Egyptian museums.
</P>
<P>
Security around the museum has been tightened since two
Egyptian brothers bombed a tourist bus parked in front of it last
September, killing nine German tourists and injuring 24 others.
</P>
<P>
The improvement of security coupled with the renovation program
of the museum since last summer to provide a new layout for some
chambers, as well as to install new lighting, ventilation and
air-conditioning systems, and specially designed showcases.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian Museum houses a collection of antiquities on the
complete history of Egypt from the Pharaonic, Greco-Roman, Coptic
and Islamic periods to the present. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
