<HEADLINE> Canada's Vehicle Sales Up 18 Percent in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Canada's vehicle sales hit their
highest level last year since 1989, reports said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Sales of cars, trucks and minivans jumped 18.2 percent for the
year to 1.39 million vehicles from 1.17 million in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Trucks led the way with an increase of 26 percent while car
sales climbed nearly 12 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
December sales finished the year strongly, aided by rebates and
reduced interest rates offered by some manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
And recent interest rate increases in the country actually
helped sales because people wanted to lock in financing before
interest rates jumped further, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
Two of the Big Three Canadian automakers recorded double digit
percentage increases in sales.
</P>
<P>
Ford Motor Co. of Canada Ltd. reported 36,085 vehicle sales in
December, up 53.4 percent over 23,531 in December 1996. Total
vehicles sales for 1997 were 315,842, up 14.7 percent from 1996.
</P>
<P>
General Motors of Canada Ltd. reported 42,237 vehicle sales in
December, up 43.5 percent over December 1996. Total vehicle sales
for 1997 were 450,739, up 18.5 percent from that in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Chrysler Canada Ltd. reported 23,243 vehicle sales in December,
up 9.9 percent over December 1996. Total vehicle sales for 1997
were 256,162, up 7 percent over 1996.
</P>
<P>
Foreign car makers also did well. Their December sales hit
32,336, up 59 percent over December 1996. Total sales for 1997 hit
361,250, up 30 percent from 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980108.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Government Handbook Reveals Slice of Life in UK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 7 (Xinhua) -- A Slice of life in Britain is
revealed in Britain 1998, an Official Handbook, published Tuesday
by the government's Office for National Statistics.
</P>
<P>
The handbook forecast that Britain's population will reach a
peak of 61.2 million by the 2020s and will start to fall from
about 2025.
</P>
<P>
Between 1991 and 1995, 1.06 million people emigrated from
Britain, and 1.19 million moved here from abroad.
</P>
<P>
The average age at which women give birth increased to 28.6
years in 1996 from 26.8 15 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, it was revealed that while the number of households
rose by seven million between 1961 and 1996, to 23.5 million,
average household size fell during that period from 3.1 to 2.4 and
has nearly halved during the course of the century.
</P>
<P>
The number of married couples has fallen by four percent during
the 1990s as many more people are choosing to live alone. In 1996,
12 percent of adults, comprising 28 percent of households, lived
on their own.
</P>
<P>
The number of overseas tourists has doubled in the past 20
years to 25.3 million by 1996.
</P>
<P>
The number of foreign companies operating in Britain now stands
at 8,000, including 4,500 from the United States, more than 1,000
from Germany and 250 from Japan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
