<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Mixed Reactions in S. Africa to Botha's Prosecution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 7 (Xinhua) -- There are mixed reactions
in South Africa to former state president P W Botha's prosecution
for defying a subpoena of the Truth and Reconciliation Commission
(TRC).
</P>
<P>
Western Cape Attorney-General Frank Kahn announced today that
Botha would have to appear in court for failing to testify before
the TRC in hearings for the former State Security Council (SSC).
</P>
<P>
Botha would accordingly be charged in the George Regional
Court in the Western Cape Province and would be summoned to
appear on January 23.
</P>
<P>
If convicted, he faces a two-year imprisonment or a fine of
20,000 Rand (4,080 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The ruling African National Congress immediately issued a
statement welcoming the move, saying it "underlines the principle
that no one is above the law irrespective of status in society."
</P>
<P>
The decision would "send a clear message that those who show
contempt for the feelings of victims of gross human rights
violations and the TRC processes will bear the consequences of
their own actions," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"The decision will reinforce the confidence of the majority of
people in the TRC process," it said.
</P>
<P>
The TRC was installed after the 1994 democratic general
elections to investigate atrocities in the apartheid era.
</P>
<P>
Justice Minister Dullah Omar also expressed his approval of
the prosecution move. He called on South Africans to respect and
accept the decision.
</P>
<P>
"It is vital that we establish the rule of law in South
Africa."
</P>
<P>
"The rule of law requires that all law must apply equally to
all persons irrespective of status," he added.
</P>
<P>
"It is my wish that justice should take its course and that
the South African public will see it in the same light."
</P>
<P>
The National Party, which Botha once led, however, complained
that the TRC had double standard in handling the cases of Botha
and ANC leaders.
</P>
<P>
The TRC's actions against Botha were in sharp contrast to the
accommodating attitude to ANC leaders who were granted blanket
amnesty, NP spokesman Daryl Swanepoel said.
</P>
<P>
"The different ways in which the role-players of the past are
handled by the TRC, and the lack of a uniform standard for all,
substantially undermines the remaining integrity of the TRC,"
said Swanepoel.
</P>
<P>
While conceding that "the law now has to take its course" and
appealing to Botha to respect the law, the spokesman said the TRC
had acted wrongly in forcing the issue to the current point.
</P>
<P>
The white-based Conservative Party also attacked the TRC. It
repeated earlier statements that the TRC was bent on undermining
Botha and belittling the Afrikaner, who had made the largest
contribution to South Africa's development.
</P>
<P>
Leader of the Freedom Front, Constand Viljoen, said the issue
was not against Botha alone, but had impact on the entire
Afrikaner community. He appealed to all Afrikaners for moral
support to Botha.
</P>
<P>
"It (the prosecution) is not morally correct and will
definitely not contribute anything to making South Africa more
acceptable."
</P>
<P>
The TRC said it regretted the current situation, but added
that it had given Botha every opportunity to cooperate.
</P>
<P>
"We had hoped that matters would not have reached this
eventuality. We would have preferred that the current impasse
between Mr. Botha and the commission did not end up in a court of
law," TRC deputy chairman Alex Boraine said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"It should have been possible to resolve differences, even
serious differences, through dialogue and discussion, as has been
the case in so many hearings of the TRC."
</P>
<P>
Boraine even appealed to Botha to change his mind at the last
minute to cooperate with his commission.
</P>
<P>
"Even in this 11th hour I would appeal to Mr. Botha to change
his mind and agree to appear before the TRC.
</P>
<P>
"If he refused to do this, then the law must take its course.
No one is above the law -- neither the lowliest nor the highest
in the land."
</P>
<P>
Botha, 81, was president between 1984 and 1989. The TRC laid
criminal charges against him last month immediately after he
defied a third subpoena to testify for the hearings of the SSC, a
powerful "inner cabinet" which Botha chaired in height of the
apartheid conflict.
</P>
<P>
Tension between Botha and the TRC flared up in mid-November
1997 when Botha told an Afrikaans newspaper, Rapport, that he
would rather be charged than appear before the TRC.
</P>
<P>
Botha refused to apologize for the activities of his
government which vehemently implemented apartheid policies and
called the TRC a "circus" and a "revenge camp against the
Afrikaner."
</P>
<P>
However, he said last month that he would respect the law and
appear in court. His lawyer, Ernst Penzhorn, today confirmed that
his client would accept the summons and answer charges in court
on January 23. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
