<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Identification Process Goes Smoothly in Western </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The spokesman said the United Nations Mission for the
Referendum in Western Sahara (MINURSO) is helping the people of
the territory to prepare for a referendum to decide between
independence and incorporation into Morocco.
</P>
<P>
According to the spokesman, between December 3 last year and
January 5 this year, a total of 16,350 person were convoked and
10,036 were identified.
</P>
<P>
Western Sahara was a Spanish colony until 1976 when Spain
withdrew and released itself from international responsibility
over the territory. The territory was subsequently occupied by
Morocco, a move which was opposed by the Popular Front for the
Liberation of Saguia el-Hamra and Rio de Oro (POLISARIO Front)
which took arms against Morocco forces.
</P>
<P>
Following diplomatic initiatives by the Organization of
African Unity and the United Nations, Security Council approved
a settlement plan for Western Sahara in 1990. Under the plan,
there would be a ceasefire, and a transitional period during
which the Special Representative of the Secretary-General of the
United Nations would be in charge of matters relating to the
referendum, assisted by the MINURSO.
</P>
<P>
The Plan was eventually bogged down by the two parties'
difference on certain groups of people to be included in the
referendum.
</P>
<P>
A breakthrough was achieved last year when a new Special
Envoy of the Secretary-General brought the two parties together
and they agreed to resume the identification process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980108.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Firm on Conditions over Zimbabwe's Land </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Britain said today it is
prepared to help finance Zimbabwe's land resettlement program
provided designed schemes are transparent, beneficial to the
poorest in the country and that the government fulfills its
international obligation regarding protection of investment.
</P>
<P>
Tony Lloyd, British Minister of State at the Foreign and
Commonwealth Office responsible for African affairs, told
journalists at the end of his two-day visit to Zimbabwe, his
country however had no direct obligation to fund land reform.
</P>
<P>
He said Britain's commitment was in the spirit of good
relations and as part of its moral obligation towards poverty
alleviation worldwide.
</P>
<P>
Lloyd said he had spelt out to Zimbabwe's acting President
Simon Muzenda the three parameters that Zimbabwe has to meet if
its request for further funding for land resettlement from
Britain was to be heard.
</P>
<P>
The resettlement scheme had to be done to benefit the poorest
people.
</P>
<P>
"We are prepared to help further on the basis that land
distribution should begin with poverty eradication. The
information we have is that significant land has not been
distributed to the poor landless people," Lloyd said.
</P>
<P>
The other important factor was that the designed schemes
should be transparent in terms of guarding against corruption and
misuse of land.
</P>
<P>
The scheme also had to be done according to Zimbabwean law and
in compliance with the international obligations Zimbabwe has
already signed.
</P>
<P>
"Zimbabwe has signed an investment protection agreement with
Britain although this has not yet been ratified. It says that
there cannot be arbitrary expropriation of investment," Lloyd
said.
</P>
<P>
"It is clear that the present land resettlement plans have not
conformed with these parameters. Our commitment is to help on
that basis but this has not yet been met," he noted.
</P>
<P>
At the end of last year the Zimbabwean government released a
list of over 1,500 farms earmarked for compulsory acquisition for
which compensation would be made for developments and not for
land.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe said that if Britain wanted
"its children" to be full compensated it should provide the
money.
</P>
<P>
But Lloyd said his country had no direct obligation to do
that, adding his generation was not the generation which
benefited from the colonialism.
</P>
<P>
He argued that the current move by Zimbabwe had damaged the
country's international credibility as an investment destination
and this was a matter of concern.
</P>
<P>
Britain has provided the money for Zimbabwe's land
resettlement since 1980. However, it stopped land reform
assistance in 1989 following reports of failed resettlement
schemes.
</P>
<P>
Consultations have been going on for the resumption of further
assistance, but Britain has been against Zimbabwe's policy of
compulsory land acquisition, saying it has to be done on a
willing seller and willing buyer basis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
