<HEADLINE> Iraq's KDP Releases 61 Rival PUK Captives </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Iraq's Kurdish Democratic Party
(KDP) has released 61 prisoners of war (POW) of its rival Iraq's
Patriotic Union of Kurdistan (PUK) under the instruction of KDP
leader Massoud Barzani, Turkey's Anatolia News Agency reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The agency quoted a KDP radio report as saying that due to the
Ramadan (Islamic holy month of fasting), the KDP released the PUK
captives who were captured during the armed clashes between the
two rival groups in northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the KDP released the PUK POWs in Erbil
region under the KDP control and they were taken to their homes in
the region under the PUK control.
</P>
<P>
PUK Chairman Jalal Talabani last Thursday sent a letter to
Barzani, seeking a broad reconciliation in a bid to set up a
permanent peace in northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Talabani expressed his hope that Barzani would give a
"positive reply" for the future and freedom of the Kurdish people
in the region, proposing a high-level meeting between the two
factions to resolve their disputes.
</P>
<P>
The two groups agreed on their latest ceasefire last November
after Talabani's forces attacked KDP's positions in the region.
</P>
<P>
The two rivals have been fighting for the control of northern
Iraq since the 1991 Gulf War when the Iraqi government was
rendered ineffective by the U.S.-led allied forces to exert
influence there. 
</P>
</TEXT>
