<HEADLINE> Foreign Envoys to Visit Cyprus for Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Several top foreign envoys will
come to Cyprus at the end of March to prepare for the new round of
U.N.-sponsored direct talks between the two communities' leaders
on the island, Cyprus News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The agency quoted Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides as saying
that he was officially informed that U.N. Secretary-General's
Special Advisor for Cyprus, Diego Cordovez would be in Cyprus at
the end of March.
</P>
<P>
Cordovez, who visited Cyprus last November, had assured that he
would return to the island after next month's presidential
elections in the Greek Cypriot-controlled southern areas to
organize the peace talks between the two communities.
</P>
<P>
After Cordovez, Britain's special representative for Cyprus
Sir David Hannay would visit the island, followed by
U.S. Presidential Emissary, Richard Holbrooke, according to the
president.
</P>
<P>
Two rounds of direct talks between Clerides and Turkish Cypriot
leader Rauf Denktash last summer failed to produce any results
after Denktash refused to negotiate in the wake of the EU
decision to start accession negotiations with Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third of the island in the wake
of a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has been trying for decades to reunite the divided
island in a bizonal, bicommunal federation through peace talks,
but so far no tangible progress has been achieved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
