<HEADLINE> Global Consulting Market to Continue Booming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Global management consulting
revenues are forecast to grow at an annual rate of nearly 16
percent to reach 113 billion U.S. dollars in 2000, according to a
U.S. research group.
</P>
<P>
Consulting revenues are expected to soar to 85 billion dollars
in 1998 from 73 billion dollars in 1997 and 62 billion dollars in
1996, with 98 billion dollars projected for 1999, the Kennedy
Research Group said in a press release today.
</P>
<P>
The Group, a leading information source on the management
consulting and executive search professions in the U.S., said the
business boom stems from growing demand on the part of new
business entrants and clients' pursuit of "one stop shopping".
</P>
<P>
As a result, consultants are forced into new service lines,
moving downstream from pure advisory work to implementation.
</P>
<P>
The involvement of information technology also helps boost the
consulting industry.
</P>
<P>
According to the Group, the information technology share of the
consulting market is expected to rise to nearly 70 percent by 2000
from the current 64 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
