<HEADLINE> Israel Denounced for Violating Hebron Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 7 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian Council today
denounced Israel for continuous violation of the Hebron agreement.
</P>
<P>
In a press release issued in the West Bank city of Ramallah,
the Palestinian Council said that Israel is still reluctant to
implement the Hebron agreement by refusing to carry out its troop
redeployment in the West Bank and to open the Shuhada Street in
Hebron city.
</P>
<P>
Israel also refused to close the vegetable market opened by the
Jewish settlers in Hebron without the approval of the Palestinian
National Authority (PNA), the council said.
</P>
<P>
The Hebron agreement, signed a year ago between Israel and the
PNA, stipulates that Israel implement its troop redeployment in
the West Bank in three stages, with the second stage to be
completed by last September.
</P>
<P>
However, the Israeli cabinet so far still can not agree on the
scope and timing of the second troop redeployment in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The Shuhada Street has been closed by Israel for long due to
the conflicts between the Arab citizens and the Jewish settlers in
the city.
</P>
<P>
"The Israeli actions would destroy the peace process and there
are dangers of possible explosions in the West Bank if Israel
continues violating the Hebron agreement," the council said.
</P>
<P>
It called on the sponsors of the peace process -- the United
States and Russia -- to put pressure on Israel to respect the
agreement.
</P>
<P>
In order to bring the peace process back on track, U.S. peace
envoy Dennis Ross returned to the region Tuesday to have talks
with Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and PNA President
Yasser Arafat on the redeployment issue, but no progress was made
till now. 
</P>
</TEXT>
