<HEADLINE> UN Chief condemns Recent Attacks on Humanitarian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, January 7 (Xinhua) -- UN Secretary-General Kofi
Annan today deplored the recent aerial attacks on Bamiyan airfield
in central Afghanistan while world Food Programme aircraft were
delivering emergency humanitarian relief supplies.
</P>
<P>
In a statement released by the spokesman's office, Annan said
the attacks were carried out despite clearances received in
advance from the Taliban authorities. They not only prevented the
delivery of urgently needed food to 160,000 vulnerable people who
rely on the United Nations assistance, but also jeopardized the
safety of humanitarian workers.
</P>
<P>
The Secretary-General called on the Taliban authorities to
allow the unimpeded delivery of humanitarian assistance and to
cease any action which endangers the safety of humanitarian
personnel.
</P>
<P>
The UN chief stressed it is unacceptable that the United
Nations personnel should be deliberately targeted while carrying
out their humanitarian mission.
</P>
<P>
He has instructed UN representative in Afghanistan to continue
to press the Taliban to give an assurance that the airlift of
food supplies to central Afghanistan can be safely resumed, the
statement added.  
