<HEADLINE> German Phone Fees Row Urged to be Solved Quickly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Deutsche Telekom and its
competitors Wednesday were urged to meet next Monday in order to
negotiate a quick end to their dispute over telephone fees.
</P>
<P>
The dispute was triggered off when former monopoly of Germany's
telecoms market, Deutsche Telekom, last week announced it would
charge customers 95 marks (52 U.S. dollars) for changing
long-distance service providers and 53 marks for those who took
their phone number with them when they left Telekom.
</P>
<P>
Private competitors to Deutsche Telekom, which is still mostly
state-owned, complained such a move would harm a market that only
became fully open on January 1.
</P>
<P>
Telekom suspended its plan Tuesday to wait for a yes or no from
government regulators. It holds the extra charges to be necessary
for covering additional high costs of the open market.
</P>
<P>
It said it would spend 500 million marks over the next five
years on computers and software to handle customers who switch to
new carriers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
