<HEADLINE> Swine Fever Breaks out in Mozambique </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Over 2,000 pigs had died of
African swine fever since the disease broke out last December in
Beira city, in central Mozambque's Sofala Province, the
Mozambique News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The report said the disease has spread to Caia and Gorongosa
regions in the province.
</P>
<P>
Swine fever first broke out in Sofala province in 1995, when
almost all pigs raised in the port city were affected.
</P>
<P>
Reports said swine fever is incurable. Local veterinarians had
advised regions which have not yet been hit by the epidemic to
kill all pigs and sell their meat.
</P>
<P>
They have also warned people to kill all pigs affected by the
fever and burn them before further damage is done.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government reportedly promised to compensate
pig raisers for their losses despite financial difficulties.
</P>
