<HEADLINE> Lebanon Bans Satellite News Broadcast by Private </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon today decided to ban
private television stations from airing news and political
programs via satellite, claiming some of them are harmful to the
country's image and its relations with other Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made at a cabinet session Wednesday morning
and then declared by Lebanese Information Minister Bassem Al Sabaa
through the radio Voice of People.
</P>
<P>
Al Sabaa announced that the government has decided to withdraw
satellite newscast licenses from the privately owned Lebanese
Broadcasting Corporation (LBC) and Future Television station owned
by Prime Minister Rafik Hariri.
</P>
<P>
They are the only two stations which are allowed to air news
and political programs on satellite among the six functioning
stations in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Tele-Liban, the only state-run station, will be authorized to
operate satellite political and news programs service and other
stations may relay them, he added.
</P>
<P>
Apart from that, he said, the government has ordered to form an
11-minister-committee to submit an assessment report of the
country's media to the cabinet within two months.
</P>
<P>
The government made the decision because some political and
news programs on satellite broadcast only focus on Lebanon's
negative issues and never show anything positive, he explained.
</P>
<P>
These programs have tarnished Lebanon's image and threatened its
relations with other Arab countries, he added.
</P>
<P>
Some Gulf Arab countries have complained that Lebanese TV
programs contain the social values and traditions that are
unacceptable to them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
