<DOCNO> XIE19980108.0058 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asia Crisis Having No Impact on Euro: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, January 7 (Xinhua) -- The European Union's executive
body, the European Commission, today ruled out the possibility
that the financial crisis in Asia would have any impact on the
bloc's single currency plan.
</P>
<P>
"The crisis is likely to have a very limited impact, almost
negligible impact, on growth in Europe, and will have no impact on
achieving the euro within the foreseen timetable," Yves-Thibault
de Silguy, EU commissioner for monetary affairs, told a press
conference following a Commission discussion of the Asia crisis.
</P>
<P>
The commissioner told reporters that the EU's economic growth
prospects remained good, adding that there was no reason to alter
the Commission's growth forecast of three percent for 1998.
</P>
<P>
The International Monetary Fund (IMF) and Organization for
Economic Cooperation and Development put their forecast for the EU
growth at 2.8 percent for the year of 1998.
</P>
<P>
De Silguy also brushed aside suggestions that a deflationary
spiral could arise from Asia's crisis, saying that it was too soon
to start talking about the issue.
</P>
<P>
However, Asian financial crisis continued Wednesday in the wake
of disappointment at Indonesia's 1998 budget and a weak Wall
Street performance on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The commissioner explained that since trade with Asia only
accounted for 2.2 percent of the bloc's gross domestic product and
nine percent of exports, there should be little risk that the
crisis would spread to EU countries due to trade links.
</P>
<P>
But de Silguy said the EU should remain alert to the situation,
adding there was also no reason to be totally complacent.
</P>
<P>
"The crisis in Asia has complex causes and the mechanisms of
contagion are also complex," he told the press conference.
</P>
<P>
The commissioner said Asia's poorly supervised financial system
and the former ties between many Asian currencies and the U.S.
dollar were the main causes of the crisis.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that the crisis had resulted in a global
reallocation of capital, particularly in favor of U.S. and
European markets.
</P>
<P>
"This has boosted the dollar and driven down long-term interest
rates," he said.
</P>
<P>
De Silguy believed that the Asian countries had to find a
solution by themselves to the ongoing crisis. But he also
expressed his support for the assistance advocated by the IMF in
this regard.
</P>
<P>
He said that the EU should not substitute international
financial institutions, adding that it was the IMF's job to play a
key role in resolving the Asia crisis.
</P>
<P>
He encouraged the Asian countries to reform their financial
systems and to reinforce their regional economic cooperation on
the EU model.
</P>
<P>
The commissioner also reiterated the EU's support for China's
full integration with the global economy through future membership
of the World Trade Organization (WTO). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980108.0059 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
