<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 7 (Xinhua) -- U.N. High Commissioner for
Refugees (UNHCR) Sadako Ogata today condemned the escalating
violence in Burundi where an armed attack forced some 8,000
civilians to flee the tiny central African state Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The attack took place in Maramvya village in Bujumbura
Province and among the fled are around 3,000 survivors of last
week's massacre at the nearby village of Rukaramu, which left
more than 150 people dead, said a UNHCR report reaching here.
</P>
<P>
"Innocent civilians are clearly the targets. As in the attacks
on Congolese refugees in Rwanda, most of the victims are women
and children who are being chased further and further from their
homes," the commissioner was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Aid workers, including UNHCR staff, said they were unable to
reach Maramvya Tuesday to check for casualties, but met several
wounded villagers on the road leading to the area, a few
kilometers from the captial's airport.
</P>
<P>
UNHCR had already been providing aid, including blankets,
jerrycans and high protein biscuits, for the survivors of the
Rukaramu massacre which also caused 2,000 returnees to flee from
UNHCR's Gatumba transit center a few kilometers away. 
</P>
