<HEADLINE> Year-Ender: Turkish-Israeli Military Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Turkey's growing military and
defense cooperation with Israel has drawn harsh criticism from
the Muslim world and Arab countries who fear it would change the
region's balance of power.
</P>
<P>
As the latest proof to such a cooperation, Turkey and Israel,
together with the United States, held naval and air joint
exercises in the international waters near Israeli coast today.
</P>
<P>
The two countries have signed a series of military and defense
accords under which they share airspace and bases for training
purposes.
</P>
<P>
They have undertaken to jointly produce 500-kilometer-range
Arrow missiles and hundreds of 150 kilometer-range Popeye II
missiles.
</P>
<P>
Israel will upgrade Turkish F-4 warplanes in a contract worth
630 million U.S. dollars, and will compete to win another
100-million-dollar deal of upgrading 48 Turkish F-5 fighters.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and the Jewish state are discussing several
defense-related projects under which Israel will supply the
Turkish Air Force with helicopter Airborne Rescue System and
modernize Turkey's aged M-60 tanks.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, Israel is offering its Phalcon model to Turkey
which plans to buy a number of early-warning aircraft (AWACS) with
a total value of 800 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Israel have defended their tightened military
ties. Turkish President Suleyman Demirel has said the relationship
"does not pose a danger for any third country."
</P>
<P>
Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai, who paid a visit to
Turkey recently, described the relationship as a strategic one,
adding "it is not targeted against anyone."
</P>
<P>
Both countries reportedly regard Iran, Syria and Iraq as
sources of potential threats.
</P>
<P>
Ankara is locked in a range of disputes with the three Muslim
neighbors. It accuses Syria of backing its outlawed Kurdish
Workers' Party (PKK) and it is also in hot disputes with Damascus
over water resources and territory.
</P>
<P>
It accuses Iran of trying to export the Islamic revolution and
is deeply concerned about the ballistic missile potentials in Iran
and Syria.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
