<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Year-Ender: Turkish-Israeli Military Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
There are about 2,500 to 3,000 PKK rebels who often cross into
Turkey from northern Iraq to attack civilian and military targets
in the country.
</P>
<P>
The honeymoon between Turkey and Israel has worried the Muslim
world which believes the relationship is aimed at increasing
Israel's military superiority over its Arab neighbors.
</P>
<P>
In its eighth summit held in the Iranian capital of Tehran last
month, the 55-member Organization of the Islamic Conference passed
a resolution indirectly denouncing Turkey for its growing military
ties with Israel. Demirel had to withdraw from the meeting early
to shun criticism.
</P>
<P>
Some Arab countries in the Middle East, especially Syria, Iran
and Egypt, have criticized Turkey for its closer links with
Israel, saying that it threatens peace and stability in the region.
Syria has accused the two countries for forging a "covert
alliance."
</P>
<P>
The al-Baath newspaper, the organ of Syria's ruling Baath
party, said recently in an editorial that "this unannounced
alliance aims not only to bury the (Middle East) peace process,
but also to achieve new gains at the expense of the Arabs and
their legitimate rights...and consequently, to impose a 'fait
accompli' policy."
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa has said that "these
policies will lead to an arms race and the return of tension to
the region."
</P>
<P>
Iran has complained about the expanding military ties between
Turkey and Israel, and accused Turkey of sheltering Iran's
opposition groups.
</P>
<P>
Observers here hold that Turkey will continue to further ties
with Israel in the fields of military and defense industries
despite increasing pressure from some Arab countries in the
region. 
</P>
