<HEADLINE> Turkey Not Recognize Greek 10-Mile Air Space </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Greece's implementation of
10-mile air space will not be recognized by any country, including
Turkey, as it is against international law, Turkish Foreign
Ministry Spokesman Necati Utkan said today.
</P>
<P>
Utkan made the remarks at a weekly press conference here after
Greece Tuesday criticized Turkey for violation of its airspace.
</P>
<P>
He said that the implementation of the 10-mile national air
space "is an absolute violation of international law."
</P>
<P>
Greek Defense Ministry sources said Tuesday that when Greece
celebrated Epiphany, Turkish F-16 warplanes infringed air control
regulations in the Athens flight information region (FIR) north
and south of Lesvos island in the eastern Aegean Sea.
</P>
<P>
On 14 occasions, Turkish warplanes violated Greek national
airspace in the region over the islands of Psara, Chios and
Oenousses, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
"This is the second time (in one month) that the Turkish air
force is carrying out provocations during a religious holiday in
violation of an agreement to refrain from such actions during
religious holidays and anniversaries," the sources said.
</P>
<P>
In 1988, Greece and Turkey reached a "memorandum agreement" to
promote confidence-building measures between the two countries on
the principle of good-neighborliness. The agreement calls for
respect of each other's major religious holidays.
</P>
<P>
On Christmas Day, Athens also condemned Ankara for violation of
its airspace by Turkish jet fighters. 
</P>
