<HEADLINE> 9 Percent of German Population are Foreigners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Foreigners living in Germany
totaled 7.31 million by the end of 1996, amounting to about 9
percent of the country's total population, the latest available
government data released today said.
</P>
<P>
According to a German government report, the largest group of
foreigners, 2.05 million, are ethnic Turks, who account for about
28 percent of Germany's total foreign population.
</P>
<P>
They are followed by 754,000 Yugoslavs, nearly 600,000
Italians, 363,000 Greeks, 342,000 Bosnians, 283,000 Poles, 202,000
Croats and 185,000 Austrians.
</P>
<P>
About 1.43 million, or 20.5 percent, of all the foreigners were
born in Germany.
</P>
<P>
Almost two thirds of all Turks and Greeks, and 71 percent of
Italians have already lived in Germany for 10 or more years. A
large number of them are so-called guest workers who began
migrating to Germany nearly four decades ago to help ease the
country labor shortage after World War II.
</P>
<P>
However, despite their long-time residency, most of the
immigrants had not been fully integrated into the German society
so far, the report admitted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
