<HEADLINE> Nemtsov on Main Task in Russia in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Main tasks for Russia in this
year is to keep the improving economic situation under control,
and to have "major structural transformations in the country",
Russian First Deputy Prime Minister Boris Nemtsov said on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview with the Interfax news agency Nemtsov
said such structural transformations are economic growth, slashed
taxes, and timely pay.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the country should finally abandon "the common stock"
principle of making social benefits available to all but actually
to no one and adopt a social security system, by which benefits
are addressed to those who really need them, Nemtsov said.
</P>
<P>
Another major restructuring task, in Nemtsov's opinion, is "to
establish an elementary state order: secure customs borders so
that there would be no contraband and fight against the illegal
production of vodka and alcohol."
</P>
<P>
Nemtsov stated that the main task in 1998 is to achieve an
economic growth, "above all an industrial growth of up to four
percent a year." He believed this can be achieved by changing the
system of taxation.
</P>
<P>
As for privatization, the First Deputy Prime Minister holds it
is not a goal in itself, nor is it the main means to attain an
economic growth. He stressed that "competition is more important
than privatization. Creating competitive conditions is more
important and healthier for society than privatization". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
