<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ross: No Information on Further Redeployment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 7 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Middle East peace envoy
Dennis Ross said here today that he has not yet received any
information on the further redeployment in the West Bank during
his talks with Israeli officials.
</P>
<P>
After meeting with Israeli President Ezer Weizman at the
president's residence today, Ross told reporters that no statement
from the Israeli side concerning the extent of the second
withdrawal has been given to him since he began a new round of
efforts to advance the peace process Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Ross, who met Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and
Palestinian National Authority President Yasser Arafat Tuesday
night, said that in today's meeting Weizman and he discussed ways
to get the peace process back on track.
</P>
<P>
Weizman said that it is very important for Israel to continue
the peace talks, but he did not express his opinion on the further
pullback.
</P>
<P>
The president asked Ross and his advisers to give backing to
Netanyahu, who is mired in a domestic political crisis generated
by the resignation of moderate Foreign Minister David Levy.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu Tuesday also refused to discuss with Ross the
exact scope of the second withdrawal, saying that no decision on
the issue has been taken by the cabinet.
</P>
<P>
But local media reported that Netanyahu intends to reduce the
scope of further redeployment from over 10 percent to 8 percent so
that his proposal on the issue can be passed by the cabinet, which
is dominated by the right-wingers after Levy's departure.
</P>
<P>
However, Ross Tuesday night informed Arafat that the United
States is sticking to its position that Israel must hand over at
least 10 percent of the territories to the Palestinians in the
second redeployment.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian senior negotiator Saeb Erekat, who attended
Tuesday's meeting between Arafat and Ross, today confirmed that
Ross believed internal political crisis in Israel should not
change Israel's stand to push forward the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Ross will meet Netanyahu and Arafat again before he concludes
his mission Friday. 
