<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-07 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Cypriot Leader Rejects UN Peace Proposals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf
Denktash said today that he will not consider any peace proposals
by the Untied Nations at the moment, the semi-official Anatolia
News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Denktash made the announcement following his meeting with
U.N. Cyprus envoy Gustave Feissel in Nicosia, the capital of
Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Earlier press reports said that U.N. special adviser on
Cyprus, Diego Cordovez would visit Cyprus in March with a set of
peace documents.
</P>
<P>
"If Cordovez comes here, we will talk with him, but we will not
discuss any documents," Denktash was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriot leader declared as "dead" the
U.N.-sponsored peace talks concerning Cyprus last month when the
European Union (EU) officially invited Greek Cypriots for the
accession talks, while excluding Turkey from the enlargement
process.
</P>
<P>
He claimed that the Cypriot government had no legal right to
apply for EU membership on behalf of the whole island, whose
northern third was controlled by Turkish Cypriots and Turkish
army.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus was divided into the Greek Cypriot-controlled south and
Turkish Cypriot-dominated north since 1974 when Turkish troops
intervened in the wake of an abortive pro-Greece coup.
</P>
<P>
"Now we have to find new common ground for starting the
talks. The common ground is the reality on the ground," Denktash
said, adding that the international community should recognize
the legitimation of the Turkish Cypriot authorities.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Cypriots unilaterally declared the "Turkish Republic of
Northern Cyprus" in 1983, which was only recognized by Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Denktash, however, said that Turkish Cypriots did not want to
kill the peace process, adding that they would be as flexible as
possible.
</P>
<P>
Local observers believe that the U.N. is adopting a
"wait-and-see" approach and will make concrete decisions after the
Cypriot presidential elections scheduled for February.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. and international community have been sparing no
efforts to strive for a settlement of the protracted Cyprus
issue, but so far no substantial results have been achieved.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
