<HEADLINE> Jordan Denies Seeking Alliance with Non-Arab </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, January 7 (Xinhua) -- A senior Jordanian official today
denied that his government is bending the country's pan-Arab
policies to seek alliance with non-Arab nations.
</P>
<P>
While delivering a speech to the Parliament today, Jordan's
Deputy Prime Minister for Services and Administrative Development
Abdullah Ensour said that Jordan is not seeking any military or
political alliance through its participation as an observer in the
U.S.-Turkish-Israeli navy exercise in the Mediterranean.
</P>
<P>
Joint military exercises have been taking place in the region
for some 20 years and some of them even involved the countries
that are now criticizing Jordan's participation in the three-way
one-day exercise, said Ensour.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Foreign Affairs Fayez Tarawneh, in another speech
to the Parliament, echoed Ensour's views, saying that Jordan's
participation is only a sovereign issue and the exercise is just
for search and rescue work.
</P>
<P>
The current exercise is dramatized by the media in a way that
goes beyond military and political significance, Tarawneh told the
lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
Some legislators attacked the Jordanian government for sending
Navy Commander Hussein Khassawneh as an observer to the
exercise.
</P>
<P>
Jordan is the only country in the Arab world that responded to
Turkey's invitation for the exercise and sent an observer there.
</P>
<P>
The joint exercise, code-named Reliant Mermaid, was held
today. It lasted only four hours. Five U.S., Israeli and Turkish
warships and some aircraft and helicopters took part in the
exercise which is widely thought to target Syria and Iraq and has
been drawing harsh criticism from the Arab world.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, Syria and Iraq are spearheading an Arab campaign
against the growing military cooperation between Turkey and
Israel.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Israel signed two military cooperation agreements
in 1996 and are discussing several defense-related projects.
</P>
</TEXT>
