<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shortlist of Arms Suppliers to S. Africa Approved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 7 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's military
equipment overhaul moved into the decisive phase as the Defense
Ministry has approved a shortlist of products and suppliers for a
proposed 10-billion-Rand (2.04-billion-U.S. dollar) arms deal, South
African Press Association reported.
</P>
<P>
"A shortlist of products and suppliers has been approved and
countries are in the process of being informed accordingly," Defense
Ministry spokesman Puso Tladi said today.
</P>
<P>
However, he declined to elaborate which countries made the list
until the relevant countries had been formally informed of the
decision.
</P>
<P>
There were reports that Germany, Britain, Canada, Italy, Spain and
France had made the cut, while arms manufacturers from Russia, Brazil
and Denmark had been excluded.
</P>
<P>
The six countries were expected to receive a formal request for
proposals within the next few weeks. The document would call for
detailed offers on counter-trade and financing for the weapons.
</P>
<P>
The process has been slow mainly because no detailed plans for
counter-trade measures were made.
</P>
<P>
The program requires the suppliers to invest a portion of the value
of the contracts in civilian and military production in South Africa
to create jobs.
</P>
<P>
The offers would be processed and presented to Defense Minister Joe
Modise and then the cabinet, probably in the second quarter of the
year.
</P>
<P>
The proposed deal includes corvettes, submarines, fighter aircraft
and tank.
</P>
<P>
It is understood that five corvettes were shortlisted, including
the German Meko 200 and 200A, the French Lafayette, and ships offered
by Spain's Bazan and Britain's Yarrow yards, the Business Day
newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
Italy's offer, which included a proposal to build two of the four
warships in South Africa, was rejected on technical grounds. The ship
offered by the state-owned Fincantieri yard was judged unsuitable for
South Africa's rough waters.
</P>
<P>
Germany's Daimler-Benz, France's Mirage and Sweden's Saab Gripen
are understood still to be in the running as the South African Air
Force's next generation of fighter-trainer jets. Neither Britain's
Hawk nor Russia's Mig-29 are understood to have made the cut, said the
paper.
</P>
<P>
Three manufacturers -- Canada's Bell, Italy's Agusta and the
French-German firm, Eurocopter -- are still in the race to supply the
successor to the South African Air Force's Alouette light utility
helicopter.
</P>
<P>
Britain's Westland and France's Cougar were shortlisted as
potential maritime helicopters which would become part of the
corvette's equipment.
</P>
<P>
Among the battle tanks shortlisted are the French Leclerc and the
British Challenger. Russia's T-80U tank was excluded as Russia's
counter-trade offer did not meet minimum requirements, the paper said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
