<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1.2 Million People Affected by Drought in PNG: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 8 (Xinhua) -- At least 400,000 Papua New
Guineans were experiencing critical shortages of drinking water,
and 1.2 million people overall were affected by the punishing
drought there, an official report released here Thursday said.
</P>
<P>
Conducted by Australia's official aid agency AusAID on behalf
of the Papua New Guinea (PNG) government, the report warned that
the situation in PNG would worsen before improving around May.
</P>
<P>
"Even with reasonable amounts of rain from now onwards, the
number of people without adequate food will continue to increase
with the worst period to occur, around February and March 1998,"
it said.
</P>
<P>
"From April 1998 onwards conditions will improve reasonably
quickly, so that by May 1998, probably only those people who live
in the high altitude areas will remain with no local means of
support."
</P>
<P>
The report also warned of continued problems with the nation's
water supply, saying 47,000 people had only extremely limited
amounts of contaminated water for drinking, and 363,000 others had
to carry water of variable quality for excessive distances.
</P>
<P>
"Despite rain during November and December, most local sources
of water remained inadequate," the report said.
</P>
<P>
Water is expensive for aid agencies to transport and difficult
to distribute.
</P>
<P>
But the report said it expected the water supply to improve
over the next two months, as long as rainfall continued.
</P>
<P>
And it said an epidemic of dysenteric disease, which may have
been expected from the drinking of polluted water, had not
occurred.
</P>
<P>
"Around 1.2 million people or 40 percent of an estimated 3.15
million rural dwellers in PNG are suffering a severe, and to some
a life threatening food shortage," the report said.
</P>
<P>
The number of people who found themselves without food other
than what they could collect from the bush had grown to 260,000,
while those who had only small, inadequate amounts of food had
expanded three times to an estimated 980,000.
</P>
<P>
The report stressed that replanting was vital, saying in parts
of PNG, there was a critical lack of planting material.
</P>
<P>
It also said there were many reports of people dying from what
appeared to be the complications of eating bush foods, in
particular bush leaves.
</P>
<P>
Australian Defense Minister Ian McLachlan Thursday said that
Australia's relief efforts to distribute food to remote areas in
PNG by air would be stretched to the limit by the end of the
month.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that by the end of this month we will be putting
out around about 1,000 tonnes a month which is just about as much
as we can handle militarily," McLachlan said.
</P>
<P>
The Australian relief operation had distributed 1.3 million
kilograms of aid materials, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980108.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
