<HEADLINE> China's Gold Output Reaches 166.3 Tons in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 8 (Xinhua) -- China produced 166.3 tons of
gold in 1997, up 37.9 percent on 1996.
</P>
<P>
Wang Dexue, director of the Gold Administration under the
Ministry of Metallurgical Industry, made the announcement today at
a news conference here.
</P>
<P>
The country's gold industry earned profits during 1997,
despite the world's sluggish gold market.
</P>
<P>
Wang attributed the achievements to the gold industry's ongoing
market-oriented restructuring which has strengthened management
and the viability of local gold producers.
</P>
<P>
However, he noted that China's gold industry faces difficulties
and challenges centered on the fact that the gold prices are
declining on both international and domestic markets.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that the country is short of gold
resources. 
</P>
