<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Service Industry Important for Hong Kong: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 8 (Xinhua) -- A senior Hong Kong official
said here Thursday that Hong Kong must take action to preserve and
enhance its position as a premier services center in Asia through
the next century.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening session of a tripartite forum on Hong
Kong's service industry attended by government officials,
businessmen and academics, Donald Tsang, financial secretary of
the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region, said Hong Kong's
economy is now firmly rooted in services.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's economy has been transformed from the manufacturing
industry to the service industry in the past two decades, Tsang
noted. "We must build on our strengths in order to sustain our
economic growth. Services will continue to provide our competitive
edge in the days to come."
</P>
<P>
"This contributes to my confidence that Hong Kong will be the
first among others in rising up from the financial turmoil
troubling Asia," he added.
</P>
<P>
Tsang asked the participants of the forum to express their
views on how Hong Kong can best take advantage of the reform of
the state-owned enterprises in China's interior areas and how Hong
Kong can make the most of global trade and investment
liberalization.
</P>
<P>
He also urged them to identify the challenges and opportunities
that lay ahead as the world enters the Information Age and think
about how Hong Kong should prepare itself for the next phase of
the services era and what Hong Kong should do to increase its
services productivity in order to enhance its competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
"There may not be ready answers to these questions but I look
to you for views so that we can make a start in identifying the
way forward. Identify the obstacles and problems so that we can
together tackle them, and eventually overcome them," Tsang said.
 
</P>
