<HEADLINE> Consumer Complaints Rise Sharply in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The year 1997 saw a
substantial rise in the number of consumer complaints, totaling
11,535 cases and making it the highest on record, the Hong Kong
Consumer Council announced here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The number of complaints went up 31 percent from 8,805 cases in
1996.
</P>
<P>
The categories that recorded most complaints included
electrical and telecom appliances, with 1,763 cases; furniture,
with 976 cases; and properties, with 777 cases.
</P>
<P>
Modeling agencies registered 638 cases in 1997, representing a
steep rise of 215 percent over the previous year. Dried seafood
and ginseng shops and beauty saloons also saw a notable rise in
complaints.
</P>
<P>
The jump was probably due to the current economic downturn as
the bulk of the increase occurred in the latter half of the year,
said the council's chairperson, Anna Wu, who predicted that the
rising trend is likely to continue into 1998.
</P>
<P>
Research on consumer policy issues, trade practices and legal
protection will be the main focus of work for the council in the
new year, she said.
</P>
<P>
The research will provide much needed crucial information for
improving consumer protection as the marketplace becomes
increasingly globalized and complex.
</P>
<P>
Consumer education will also be a priority, to enable consumers
themselves to safeguard their own rights and interests in the
purchase of goods and use of services, she added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
