<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Port of First Asylum Policy to Be Scrapped: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Secretary for Security Peter
Lai announced Thursday that the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region (SAR) government has decided to abolish the port of first
asylum policy for Vietnamese people arriving here illegally in the
future.
</P>
<P>
The decision has been made with regards to "changed
circumstances in Vietnam, the nature of recent illegal arrivals
and widespread calls in the community for scrapping the port of
first asylum policy," the official told a press conference here.
</P>
<P>
The Provisional Legislative Council (PLC), the legislature of
the SAR, carried a motion on August 20 last year urging the
government to end the policy imposed by the British government in
1979.
</P>
<P>
"What the abolition would mean in practical terms is that there
would be no more special treatment for Vietnamese illegal arrivals
in Hong Kong in future. They would be treated in the same way as
are illegal arrivals from any other country," Lai said.
</P>
<P>
The change of policy would involve amending the Immigration
Ordinance, which contains special provisions for screening for
refugee status and review procedures for Vietnamese people
arriving in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
In order to prevent a possible influx of Vietnamese into Hong
Kong between now and the passage of the amendment bill by the PLC,
it is proposed that the special provisions of the ordinance should
cease to apply to new arrivals with effect from Friday when the
amendment bill is gazetted, Lai said.
</P>
<P>
The scrapping of the port of first asylum policy is part and
parcel of a package of measures to deal with the remaining
Vietnamese problems in Hong Kong, following the completion of a
comprehensive review conducted by the government of its policy on
Vietnamese refugees (VRs), Vietnamese migrants (VMs) and
Vietnamese illegal immigrants (VIIs).
</P>
<P>
The SAR government has for the past several months won full
support from the Central People's Government, either at
international conferences related to the issue or in negotiations
with the Vietnamese side, Lai said.
</P>
<P>
Since the emergence of the Vietnamese boat people in 1975, Hong
Kong has received more than 200,000 people from Vietnam. Of these,
some 143,000 have been resettled in third countries and about
69,000 VMs and VIIs have been returned to Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
In terms of numbers, this represents a successful resolution of
98.5 percent of the problem, Lai told an earlier briefing to
members of a PLC panel on security.
</P>
<P>
But there still remain about 1,200 VRs, 700 VMs and 1,100 VIIs
in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The government will press the U.N. High Commissioner for
Refugees to continue its best efforts to resettle the VRs and it
will also work together with the Vietnamese government to
repatriate the others, Lai said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980108.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia to Spend More on Science </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The Russian government Thursday
decided to spend more to help the development of science, the
Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin told a cabinet session that
more than four percent of the 1998 state budget would go to the
country's research institutions.
</P>
<P>
At the same session, the cabinet approved guidelines for
reforming the research system in years 1998-2000, and Chernomyrdin
urged the implementation of the program.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Prime Minister Vladimir Bulgak said economic reforms in
the country were impossible without the development of science and
the speedy implementation of these guidelines.
</P>
<P>
Budget funds, Bulgak said, should be spent primarily on state
scientific research institutions and priority research projects.
</P>
<P>
The science budget was estimated at 14.2 billion redenominated
rubles (about 2.4 billion U.S. dollars) in 1998, rising from the
10 trillion old rubles (1.7 billion dollars) last year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the cabinet decided to use private funds for
science, which currently account for 25-50 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
Bulgak warned of a "brain drain," saying Russia had only 1
million scientists in 1997, compared with the 2 million in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Some 15,200 Russian scientists have so far settled down outside
the country permanently and 30 percent changed their occupations
mainly due to the lack of project funding. 
</P>
</TEXT>
