<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Somali Shilling Appreciates Against Dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Amid the anarchy in the
country, the super decentralized economy of Somalia is
strengthening with the Somali Shilling increasing in value
against foreign currencies in Mogadishu's main business centers.
</P>
<P>
Today, the U.S. dollar took a new low in its history in
Mogadishu's main Bakara market.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. dollar which was sold 8,700 against the Somali
Shilling six months ago, today is exchanged with only 6,300 in
the Somali capital.
</P>
<P>
Business and money dealers agreed that the new depreciation of
the dollar is related to the new political trend and optimism
following the Cairo agreement signed by the Somali factions
including the two main warlords, Ali Mahdi and Hussein Aidid.
</P>
<P>
Abdi Mohamed Ali, manager of a local business company in
Bakara market, told Xinhua that despite the hope for a political
settlement in the near future, many Somalis are receiving hard
currencies from their relatives abroad for the Holy month of
Ramadan and the Eid festivals that follows.
</P>
<P>
Another clue devaluating the dollar is the wish of the
businessmen to sell out all their stock before air and seaports
in Mogadishu are opened. Goods from the new seaport will of
course be much cheaper than those imported through the natural
seaports outside the capital.
</P>
<P>
"Everybody is trying to get rid of the old stock," said Ali.
</P>
<P>
Business movement within the country is also contributing to
the devaluation of the hard currencies.
</P>
<P>
Muhidin Trabune, another prominent import and export dealer,
said traffic restrictions as a result of the recent heavy rains
in southern Somalia are playing a major role in creating a
business stagnation.
</P>
<P>
"No one can import more goods when his store is still full of
the old goods," he noted, adding "all roads to the southern
regions are cut and Mogadishu can't consume all we have, so what
to do with the dollars."
</P>
<P>
The devaluation of hard currencies are not confined to the
U.S. dollar alone, but the Saudi Riyals, the Ethiopian Bir and
the Kenyan Shillings as well.
</P>
<P>
As the essential food items such as the sugar, flour and rice
are getting more expensive in the southern regions of the
country, Mogadishu is moving smoothly with the benefits of the
dollar depreciation. Each 50 kg bag of sugar which was sold US
$22.50 is today sold less than US$20.50 in Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
However, local food products of maize and sorghum still remain
unaffected by the money exchange rates.
</P>
<P>
The money exchange business employs many Somali in the
different markets throughout the capital. Dozens of young Somalis
go to the markets before dawn to make their living from the
exchange benefits. Sometimes, these youngsters loose their money
especially when the dollar makes a quick loss of value.
</P>
<P>
There has been no central bank or government to deal with the
values of the currencies or fight the fake money which might be
injected into the market-oriented economy of the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
