<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan to Increase Trade With ASEAN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan plans to increase its
trade with the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) by
about 10 percent during the 1997-98 fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
Annual trade between the two sides now is estimated at around
45.8 billion rupees (about 1.04 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The Commerce Ministry believes that by the end of the 1997-98
fiscal year (ending on June 30, 1998), the trade volume between
Pakistan and ASEAN will cross the 50 billion rupee (1.14 billion
dollars) mark.
</P>
<P>
Sources from the Commerce Ministry said Thursday that the
Pakistani government has finalized an elaborate strategy to
further trade ties with especially Malaysia, Singapore, Indonesia
and Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif has instructed the
Commerce Ministry to find ways and means to boost economic and
trade relations with ASEAN, they said.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan's exports to ASEAN during 1991-92 were worth 9.7
billion rupees (220 million dollars) while imports from that
region amounted to 16.9 billion rupees (384 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
Pakistan's exports to ASEAN increased to 10.2 billion rupees
(232 million dollars) in 1994-95 while its imports from the region
snowballed to 40.4 billion rupees (918 million dollars) in the
same period.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan is now planning to find markets for its steel,
electrical and farm products and manpower in the ASEAN region.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, Pakistan is expecting investments from ASEAN
countries, especially Malaysia, for setting up a range of
medium-sized and large hi-tech industries in the industrial zones
to be set up along the Lahore-Islamabad motorway, the sources
said.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia has already agreed to set up a huge mechanical complex
to manufacture machinery for the engineering industry in the
proposed industrial area near Chiniot, Punjab Province.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN comprises Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines,
Singapore, Thailand, Vietnam, Myanmar and Laos.  
</P>
</TEXT>
