<HEADLINE> Nepali PM Requests Mid-Term Polls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Nepali Prime Minister Surya
Bahadur Thapa Thursday asked King Birendra to dissolve parliament
and hold mid-term polls, as the opposition has planned a
no-confidence motion against his coalition government, the King's
Principal Press Secretariat said.
</P>
<P>
Sources here said a cabinet meeting held on Thursday morning
made the decision, and the prime minister flew to Pokhara, 120
kilometers west of Kathmandu, in the afternoon to see King
Birendra, who was inaugurating the Janapriya Multiple Campus
building there.
</P>
<P>
The main opposition the Communist Party of Nepal (United
Marxism-Leninism, CPN-UML) on Wednesday evening decided to table a
no-confidence motion against the present government, the sources
said.
</P>
<P>
A total of 96 MPs from the CPN-UML and the Chand faction of the
National Democratic Party (RPP) have formally requested the King
to convene a special session of the parliament to discuss their
no-confidence motion, said a notice issued by the King's Principal
Press Secretariat.
</P>
<P>
The King has not made a decision yet on the two requests, a
Royal Palace source said.
</P>
<P>
The coalition government led by Surya Bahadur Thapa came to
power on October 7, 1997 after the coalition government headed by
Lokendra Bahadur Chand was brought down by a no-confidence motion
moved by the Nepali Congress (NC).
</P>
<P>
The present government, the sixth since 1990, is a coalition of
the NC, the RPP and the Nepal Sadbhavana Party.  
</P>
</TEXT>
