<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study Identifies New Clue to Cause of Diabetes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Scientists announced Thursday the
identification of a new clue to the cause of the diabetes, opening
a possible new way for treating the disease.
</P>
<P>
American researchers wrote in the journal Nature that the
progression of diabetes may be linked to the failure, by a set of
T-cells, to produce the substance interleukin 4 (IL-4).
</P>
<P>
Diabetes would be caused when cells in pancreas are destroyed
by the body's immune system, said the researchers at Harvard
University in Boston, Massachusetts, of the United States.
</P>
<P>
The pancreas produce insulin, the hormone that in turn controls
sugar metabolism.
</P>
<P>
Experiments on mice have shown that IL-4, a hormone that has
anti-inflammatory properties and can suppress the immune system,
appears to hinder the development of diabetes.
</P>
<P>
If IL-4 is no longer made, the last obstacle to diabetes is
removed and the T-cells can destroy cells in the pancreas.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, stimulating the production of IL-4 may help prevent
the development of diabetes, which affects 135 million people
worldwide and kills 2.8 million every year.
</P>
<P>
Researchers said their next step would be to find out what
triggers the production of IL-4. At the same time, more work needs
to be done to bring the experiments to clinical trials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980108.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Port Achieves 14 Million TEUs in Container </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The Singapore Port has
achieved a container throughput of 14.12 million TEUs (twenty-foot
equivalent units) for the year ending December 31, 1997, a 9.1
percent increase over 1996's 12.94 million TEUs, the PSA
Corporation said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Describing the achievement as "very satisfactory" given the
prevailing economic and currency crises in the region, PSA
Corporation Chairman Yeo Ning Hong said this year's result is
testimony that the customers continue to find value in using the
services at the Singapore Port.
</P>
<P>
He said the port had worked hard to reduce customers' cost by
providing highly reliable service in berthing their ships on time,
delivering fast handling rates and providing faster connections
for transshipment containers.
</P>
<P>
High productivity played an important role in the achievement
of 14 million TEUs, Yeo said.
</P>
<P>
For the third generation container vessels of PSA Corporation's
major customers, the average number of containers handled per
vessel call was more than 2,000 TEUs. They were serviced at an
average rate of 88 containers per hour, the fastest in the world,
he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
