<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interest Rates Plunge in Sweden </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Interest rates in Sweden
dipped low Wednesday as hopes were high about ongoing wage talks,
and the U.S. Federal Reserves delivered optimistic tones.
</P>
<P>
The yield on ten-year Swedish government bonds fell by 11 basis
points to an all-time-low of 5.72 percent, while short-term paper
fell by about 4 basis points.
</P>
<P>
While Swedish yields plummeted, the interest rate gap between
Sweden and Germany shrank to only 53 points.
</P>
<P>
A domestic factor affecting the rates is Sunday's agreement by
the paper and forest workers' union to accept wage increases of
2.5 percent this year and 2.4 percent for the following two years.
</P>
<P>
This has led to expectations that negotiations by the metal
workers' union, retail clerks' union and others will also lead to
only moderate wage increases, thus unlikely to spur inflation.
</P>
<P>
The Swedish rates were also affected by U.S. Federal Reserves
Chairman Alan Greenspan's speech on Saturday, in which he warned
about the negative effects of deflation.
</P>
<P>
The speech was seen as a sign that the Federal Reserves,
functioning as the central bank of the United States, will not
raise interest rates on February 3-4. 
</P>
</TEXT>
