<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian Minister Calls for Joining WTO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Minister of Agriculture
Issa Kalantari has urged the government to apply for the
membership of the World Trade Organization (WTO), the Iran Daily
newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
Iran can not long afford to stay away from the WTO and should
make efforts to win entry into the organization in the near
future, Kalantari said at a meeting of managers of the Rural
Cooperatives Organization.
</P>
<P>
Experts, however, have cautioned that by joining the WTO,
Iran's industries would face serious challenges.
</P>
<P>
The agriculture minister argued that setting the goal to join
the WTO will give Iran the momentum to develop the agricultural
sector by canceling government subsidies and encouraging
competition, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Farmers can set up organizations to help upgrade the quality
of their goods, and make better use of technical facilities to
compete in international markets," he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister noted that if Iran becomes a WTO member, the
government is able to levy taxes on farmers rather than subsidize
them.
</P>
<P>
He complained that the government gives too much subsidies to
bread consumption, saying that 6,000 billion rials (about 2
billion U.S. dollars) are earmarked annually for subsidizing wheat
and bread.
</P>
<P>
He called on Iranian farmers to invest in agriculture. He
suggested that if each of 1.5 million farmers invests 1 million
rials (about 333 dollars), a body with a capital of at least 150
billion rials (about 50 million dollars) will be formed to help
develop the agriculture. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
