<HEADLINE> Senior Official in S. Leone Condemns Kamajors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, January 8 (Xinhua) -- State radio in Sierra Leone
today quoted Major Alimmamy Mansaray, the Secretary of State as
describing the action of Kamajor militiamen in blocking roads in
the country as "undemocratic and inhuman."
</P>
<P>
"They are also killing innocent civilians and impeding the
free movement of people and goods with the support of Nigerian
troops in ECOMOG," Mansaray told a meeting of executive members
of the Amalgamated Transport Union in Kenema.
</P>
<P>
The Executive members had paid a call on the minister to
appeal for "increased security" for their inter-city vehicles
transporting essential goods.
</P>
<P>
Mansaray warned that his administration "will not hesitate to
take drastic action against Kamajor supporters" including
paramount chiefs suspected of covertly aiding the Kamajors.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, in the ongoing war itself, reports from Zimmi near
the Liberian border in the south said government troops continue
to battle with a well armed Kamajor band for the second straight
day after an initial lull in the fighting on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"The area is now unsafe so I decided to pull out my family,"
said Brima Kebbie, a farmer, in a telephone interview in Kenema.
According to him, hundreds of mud-houses have been torched and
rice plantations destroyed.
</P>
<P>
Another civilian spoke of hundreds of civilians killed as
rocket propelled grenades missed their targets and landed on
civilian settlements.
</P>
<P>
"The kamajors are bringing reinforcement continuously across
the Mano River Bridge accompanied by a number of white men whose
identity is unknown," he added.
</P>
<P>
The military high command in Kenema confirmed the heavy
fighting but said casualty figures are being compiled.
</P>
<P>
Sporadic fighting has also continued in the eastern diamond
mining town of Tongo, said the High Command.
</P>
<P>
"We are consistently beating them back," said a military
communique which is being disputed by the Kamajors who said they
killed over 20 government soldiers and surrounded the government
forces.
</P>
<P>
There has not been any independent confirmation of both
claims. The military forces in Bo said they have killed 35
Kamajors while it lost five soldiers in the fighting on the
outskirts of Bo, Sierra Leone's second largest city. Fighting
died down on Tuesday but the area remained tense, residents said.
</P>
</TEXT>
