<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-08 13:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Refutes Statements by US Ambassador to UN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, January 8 (Xinhua)-- Iraq today refuted the
statements of the U.S. ambassador to the U.N. claiming that 95
percent of the contracts of food and medicine within the second
phase of Iraq-U.N. oil-for-food program has been approved.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi News Agency INA quoted a spokesman for the Iraqi Trade
Ministry as saying that the real percentage was not more than 77
percent.
</P>
<P>
Seven months had passed since the implementation of the
second phase of the oil-for-food deal, but Iraq had only
received foodstuff worth of 295 million dollars out of 1212
million dollars allocated for the procurement plan, said the
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
He said if the U.S. Ambassador checked well records of the
Security Council Sanctions Committee, he would discover that the
percentage of the contracts which had been ratified was not 95
percent, but it does not exceed 77 percent.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that baby milk and other materials under
contracts of the second phase have not reached Iraq yet, adding
that under the U.S. pressure, food contracts worth of 90 million
dollars have not been recorded by the Sanctions Committee.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman called on the international community to put
pressure on the U.S. and the Sanctions Committee to record
these contracts and not to delay the food contracts concluded
within the third phase of the oil-for-food program.
</P>
<P>
Under the oil-for-food deal, Iraq is allowed to export 2
billion dollars worth of oil every six months to buy food,
medicine and other humanitarian supplies for its people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
