<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Disappointed at Canada's Beef Quota Decision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Australian Acting Prime
Minister Tim Fischer Thursday accused Canada of reneging on an
agreement to restore Australian beef imports, which were cut by
7,000 tons a year ago.
</P>
<P>
Fischer said his country would keep pushing Canada for full
restoration of beef quota arrangements as negotiated during the
long-running Uruguay round of trade talks, which led to the
creation of the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
"Australian beef exporters met their quota last year and could
this year have supplied at least the agreed level of 42,000 tons,"
he said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
At Fischer's request, senior officials from the Department of
Foreign Affairs and Trade called in Canada's High Commissioner
William Schumacher to inform him of Australia's disappointment
after his country allocated Australian beef exporters only 35,000
tons as its annual import quota.
</P>
<P>
After a year of intense lobbying by trade officials and the
cattle industry, Australia had expected Canada to allow it to
restore beef exports to the previous annual quota of 42,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
Canada's decision prompted the Australian cattle industry to
call on the Australian and Canadian governments to hold urgent
talks to resolve outstanding trade issues, such as beef quotas.
</P>
<P>
Cattle Council of Australia President John Wyld said the local
beef industry has been working collectively for the past year in
an effort to have the original quota restored.
</P>
<P>
Australian access to the Canadian market was slashed a year ago
for purely political reasons, Wyld said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"The Australian cattle industry will not take this decision
lightly," he said.
</P>
<P>
Canada announced last February that Australia's 1997 beef quota
had been slashed as it had not used the full 42,000-ton quota in
1996.
</P>
<P>
The decision was expected to cause Australian beef exporters to
lose nearly 9 million U.S. dollars in income from its fourth
largest export market.
</P>
<P>
Beef exports are just one area of contention between the two
Commonwealth nations. Australia was accused last year of hiding
behind a threat of unacceptable disease risk to block imports of
fresh Canadian salmon.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
