<DOCNO> XIE19980108.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Urges Rightwing Coalition Members to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu today urged hardliners within the coalition to
support the planned second phase of further troops redeployment in
the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to a conference of Jewish parliamentaries here,
Netanyahu stressed he would advance the Israeli-Palestinian peace
process by carrying out the necessary troop pullback in the West
Bank.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu warned that if there is no progress in the peace
process, the leftists would stage a comeback to seize power. In
earlier remarks, he described the election victory in 1992 by the
Labor Party as a disaster for the country because it resulted in
the Oslo peace accords and Israeli handover of occupied land to
the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli leader added bluntly that if those who support
"the careful and responsible move" will remain in the government,
while those do not can quit.
</P>
<P>
After the conference, Netanyahu convened a meeting of heads of
coalition parties to discuss the latest political turmoil caused
by the resignation of Foreign Minister David Levy this week and
to lobby for their support to the proposed redeployment. Rafael
Eitan of Tsomet, Aryeh Deri of Shas Party, Natan Sharansky of
Israeli Baaliya and Avigdor Khahalani of The Third Way were
invited to the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu made the remarks ahead of his third round of talks
with visiting U.S. special peace envoy Dennis Ross, who is
pushing for progress in the peace process. Ross' mediation here
is aimed at preparing for President Bill Clinton's pending
meetings with Netanyahu and Palestinian National Authority (PNA)
leader Yasser Arafat later this month.
</P>
<P>
Due to the resignation of Levy, a leading moderate within the
rightist coalition, Netanyahu's maneuvering room has been
dramatically reduced. A group of rightist lawmakers have
threatened to topple Netanyahu if he goes ahead with the
redeployment.
</P>
<P>
Many now doubt how Netanyahu could carry out the second
redeployment since his government has in fact become hostage of
the hardliners. The Defense Minister Yithzak Mordechai, Another
dove within the government, threatened Wednesday night to resign
if the government could not implement the pullback within three
months.
</P>
<P>
Under heightened U.S. pressure to carry out the redeployment,
Netanyahu repeatedly assured Washington that he would honor the
promise he made. But he is reportedly scaling down the
proposed percentage of pullback from over 10 percent to 8
percent in order to appease the hardliners.
</P>
<P>
The PNA has made it clear that it would firmly reject anything
that is less than 10 percent. For its part, the PNA has been
demanding for a 30 percent withdrawal at every stage of the
three-phase pullbacks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
