<HEADLINE> Rebel Head in S. Leone Denies Split between Govt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Solomon Rogers, chairman of
the war council of the Sierra Leonean rebel Revolutionary United
Front (RUF), today dismissed reports of a possible split between
the military government and the RUF following the former's
disciplinary actions in the alleged looting of the Iranian
Embassy on New Year's Day.
</P>
<P>
Out of the eight men implicated, six were members of the
Sierra Leone Army while two were from the People's Army made up
of the former RUF combatants.
</P>
<P>
RUF captain Browne was dismissed from the People's Army while
the RUF's Battle Group Commander, Lt. Colonel Issa Sesay was to
lose three months' salary.
</P>
<P>
"There is no split because of the decision," Rogers said.
Rogers, who is Secretary of State for Agriculture and Forestry,
said, "this action will not in any way bring cracks in the
alliance since the Anti-looting Decree was agreed by all in the
alliance."
</P>
<P>
"It is unfortunate that Sesay was inadvertently implicated in
the mess by his personal assistant (Captain Browne)," he added.
</P>
<P>
Browne, together with five soldiers in the Sierra Leone army
including the man who first announced the May 25, 1997 coup, are
now detained at the maximum security prison in the capital.
</P>
<P>
The government said their detention is necessary as they had
tried to influence the People's Army to mutiny against the
decision to punish them for their alleged crimes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
