<DOCNO> XIE19980108.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Dominance over Women's Diving Shaken </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PERTH, January 8 (Xinhua) -- China's winning streak in the
women's 3-meter springboard diving snapped on Thursday as Russian
Yulia Pakhalina scored 544.62 points to win the event at the world
swimming championships.
</P>
<P>
Pakhalina, 20, led all the way to beat Chinese Guo Jingjing
into second place by 25.96 points.
</P>
<P>
China had never lost in the women's springboard events in the
previous three world championships. Gao Min won the event in both
the 1986 and 1991 championships and Tan Shuping triumphed in the
1994 Worlds.
</P>
<P>
The 16-year-old Guo Jingjing was philosophical at her
defeat. "This is as it should be, the Russian diver was very good
tonight and was better than me," she said.
</P>
<P>
"The judging was also very good," Guo added.
</P>
<P>
Chantelle Michell, who placed 10th after the semi-finals,
clawed back to win a bronze medal for Australia.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Chinese duo Sun Shuwei and Tian Liang garnered 326.34
points in the men's synchronized platform diving to win China's
first gold medal in the championships.
</P>
<P>
Sun and Tian highlighted the 10-meter event with their best
dive of the night - a back three and a half somersault - to beat
Germany's Michael Kuehne and Jan Hempel into second place with
Russia's Alexandr Varlamov and Igor Loukashin narrowly behind on
third.
</P>
<P>
The Russian pair made a spectacular start, scoring 99.60 after
the first two rounds, to establish a lead over the Chinese and
Germans going into the third round.
</P>
<P>
But the Chinese, who throughout the competition matched
execution with brilliant synchronization, performed a superb
forward three and a half somersault in their third dive to go into
a lead they never relinquished.
</P>
<P>
Kuehne and Hempel were delighted with their silver medal.
"Despite being the European champions last year we have had a
terrible run up to the world championships because I have started
studying and Jan has been ill," Kuehne said.
</P>
<P>
"So it is only in the last eight weeks or so when we have
really started performing well again," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
