<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Makes progress in Privatizing SOEs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government has
made some progress in privatizing state-owned enterprises (SOEs)
since coming to power 18 months ago, the Bangladesh Observer
newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
During the period, the government has finalized the process for
disinvestment of 32 SOEs, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
To transfer loss-making SOEs to private entrepreneurs is part
of the government policy.
</P>
<P>
SOEs in this South Asian country incur a total loss of 434
billion taka (9.6 billion U.S. dollars) every year, and the
government sustains a loss of 25 billion taka (552 million
dollars) in the state-owned sector.
</P>
<P>
The government has already enlisted 54 SOEs for disinvestment
in the current fiscal year starting July 1, 1997, while the
Privatization Board, which is in charge of the work for
privatizing the loss-making industries, has enlisted 87 SOEs for
disinvestment, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The industrial units now awaiting disinvestment include 21 jute
mills, 19 textile mills, 21 steel and engineering units, 10 sugar
and food businesses and eight chemical units, it said.
</P>
<P>
Despite the progress that has been made, a number of problems
remain such as delay in implementation of the decision for
disinvestment because of the absence of concrete directives and
commitment by political leaders and resistance from the trade
unions, it said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980108.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
