<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading French newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- Prime Minister Lionel Jospin Thursday will meet
representatives of unions and associations of jobless people to
discuss "concrete and immediate improvement" of the emergency
situation of jobless people, after demonstrations were held in
Paris and other French cities Wednesday in protest of unemployment.
</P>
<P>
-- The general directors of police forces of Turkey and seven
European countries concerned with the recent exodus of 1,000 Kurds
toward Europe will meet Thursday in Rome to discuss ways to
contain the immigration of Kurds. Germany is very critical of
Italy over the issue and wants a "concrete result", while Italy
wants Turkey and Greece to stop networks of illegal immigration
and seek a common action by European police forces.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- The French city of Strasbourg Wednesday decides to mark out
the areas considered to be "difficult" and to reinforce the police
force there. City officials and deputies are considering imposing
a curfew on teenagers to restrict them at home after certain hours
in the night. Moreover, girls become more and more involved in the
juvenile delinquency in France, as many of them are using violent
methods identical to those used by boys.
</P>
<P>
-- While the Asian currencies continued to collapse, the creditor
banks of Western countries, especially France and Germany, are
looking for a solution to short-term debts owed by South Korea. The
center of gravity of the unprecedented Asian financial collapse has
shifted to Indonesia, where the currency rupiah is yielding ground
after the government announced a budget plan which is little
convincing. 
</P>
