<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Refuses to Apologize to Aborigines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The Australian government
Thursday refused to follow Canada's example to make a formal
apology to indigenous people for its white assimilation policy
during 1910-1970 that forcibly removed aboriginal children from
their families.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on Canada's formal apology for decades of
discrimination against aboriginal people, Australian Acting Prime
Minister Tim Fischer said: "Australia's constitution is not
Canada's, Australia is not Canada, there are differences."
</P>
<P>
Canada formally apologized overnight for decades of
discrimination, including the widespread abuse of Indian children
at federally-funded boarding schools, following a report into
treatment of indigenous people.
</P>
<P>
Fischer said the Canadian experience had no link to Australia.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian government had set up the boarding schools for
Indian children, whereas in Australia, the practice of removing
Aboriginal children was largely in the hands of state governments
and the church, he said.
</P>
<P>
Fischer expressed personal deep regret for past wrongs but told
Australian Broadcasting Corporation (ABC) radio that no
comparisons could be drawn between Australia's situation and that
of Canada.
</P>
<P>
"(Prime Minister) John Howard gave a strong personal apology,
expressed his full regret, as I do, for so much which has happened
in the past, but it did happen in the past," Fischer said.
</P>
<P>
He said a government apology would not be forthcoming.
</P>
<P>
"Let's get on with the task of building a better life for the
Aboriginal people in practical ways, that's what we are doing, and
I am proud of the efforts that we will continue to do in that
regard," he said.
</P>
<P>
Up to 100,000 aboriginal children were forcibly separated from
their families during 1910-1970 under Australia's white
assimilation policy.
</P>
<P>
Aboriginal leaders have called on the government to follow
Canada's lead and apologize for the past treatment of indigenous
people.
</P>
<P>
Some indigenous leaders have condemned Fischer's response,
saying Australia was increasingly isolated for its stance.
</P>
<P>
Ray Robinson, government-appointed acting chairman of a
commission in charge of aboriginal affairs, accused the government
of being unable to face up to history.
</P>
<P>
"Our present-day government may not be responsible for
implementing past policies but it is responsible for dealing with
the history we inherited," Robinson said.
</P>
<P>
Federal opposition leader Kim Beazley said Canada's apology
offered Australia another chance to deal with the issue.  
</P>
</TEXT>
