<HEADLINE> Li Peng Meets Vice President of Texaco (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Black said that Texaco cherishes its long-standing cooperation
with China and expressed hope that the project will signal a good
beginning for bilateral cooperation in the production of coalbed
methane.
</P>
<P>
He said the U.S. side will do its best to ensure the success of
the project.
</P>
<P>
Vice-Premier Zou Jiahua and a number of other senior Chinese
officials attended today's meeting and signing ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The two firms will reportedly jointly explore over 60 billion
cu.m. of prospective coalbed methane resources. Some 300 wells
will be drilled during the exploration and production period, with
each well expected to produce 5,000 cu.m. of methane daily, and
500 million cu.m. annually.
</P>
<P>
The China CBM was founded in May 1996. Chinese President Jiang
Zemin and Premier Li Peng penned the following respective
inscriptions marking the founding of the company: "Rely on
scientific and technological progress, and develop the the coalbed
methane industry for the benefit of the people"; and "Develop
coalbed methane and explore new energy resources".
</P>
<P>
China has designated a number of coal mines in Liaoning, Anhui,
Hebei and Shanxi provinces to pilot for coalbed methane
exploration. Two coalbed methane bases in Shanxi Province are
expected to engage in industrial exploration.
</P>
<P>
Related coal mines and bases will reach an annual production
capacity of one billion cu.m. of coalbed methane by the end of
this century, with the figure expected to rise to 10 billion
cum. by the year 2010. This will in turn form a complete
production scope for the exploration and use of coalbed methane,
and will lay a solid foundation for China's use of new energy
resources.  
</P>
