<HEADLINE> Cyprus Unhappy with U.S.-Israel-Turkey Exercise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus is not happy about the
naval exercise jointly staged by Israel, Turkey and the United
States in eastern Mediterranean, Cypriot Foreign Minister Ioannis
Kasoulides said here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters before a cabinet meeting, Kasoulides
said the Cypriot government considers military cooperation
between Israel and Turkey "a development which we do not favor."
</P>
<P>
He said Cyprus was not passive over the issue and had made
"friendly representations" to the government of Israel last
month.
</P>
<P>
"We got the assurances we wanted," he said, adding "this does
not stop us from stating that we are not happy about the
three-nation military exercise."
</P>
<P>
Kasoulides noted that relations between Cyprus and Israel are
very good, just as relations with Arab countries in the region.
</P>
<P>
However there was no need for military cooperation between
Turkey and Israel, he said, because that creates concern to
neighboring Arab states and upset balances with friendly
countries such as Cyprus, Syria and Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Government spokesman Manolis Christofides said Wednesday that
Cyprus was not affected by the exercise, but pointed out the aim
of the exercise, which was described as humanitarian, was "not
compatible with the human rights violations in Turkey and the
genocides this state has carried out".
</P>
<P>
The one-day exercise Wednesday described as a "success" by
U.S. and Israeli military officers, was condemned by neighboring
Arab states.
</P>
<P>
Greece, a strong supporter of Cyprus, also criticized the
exercise, saying it does not contribute to peace and stability in
the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
