<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Analysis: China's Energy Development Enters New Stage (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 8 (Xinhua) -- China United Coal-bed Methane
Co. Ltd. (CUBM) and Texaco Inc. signed a contract here today to
jointly explore 2,663 sq km of methane resources in east China's
Anhui Province.
</P>
<P>
The region where the two investment partners will cooperate on
exploration is believed to have more than 60 billion cubic meters
of coal-bed methane resources.
</P>
<P>
During the exploration period, 300 wells will be sunk at an
investment of 500 million U.S. dollars. When completed, the wells
should produce 500 million cubic meters a year.
</P>
<P>
This is China's first large coal-bed methane development
project with overseas cooperation. The contract with the
U.S. energy giant marks the beginning of easing energy shortages
and improving energy structure in China in the next century. The
agreement is considered to also mark a new period in the country's
energy development.
</P>
<P>
Coal-bed methane is commonly known as coal-mine gas and is
basically the same thing as conventional natural gas. Each 1,000
cubic meters of coal-bed methane can produce heat equivalent to
one metric ton of petroleum. The gas can be used either as fuel
for cooking, power generation or as high-quality raw material for
producing fertilizer, carbon black and formaldehyde.
</P>
<P>
As is known to all that China is relatively deficient in
resources, with the per-capita figure only 47 percent of the
world's volume. Energy experts predict that by the year 2000 the
gap between supply and demand in China will be 21 million to 25
million tons.
</P>
<P>
Coupled with energy shortages, China has an irrational energy
structure compared to that of developed countries. With the
proportion of coal as high as 75 percent, petroleum and natural
gas make up one-third and one-tenth of the world's averages,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
China's abundant coal-bed methane long has been wasted despite
energy shortages. To prevent gas explosions, 600 million cubic
meters of coal-bed methane are annually drawn from mines. The coal
mines are not only a polluted environment, but also contribute to
a serious loss of natural resources.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980108.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Analysis: China's Energy Development Enters New Stage (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Exploration and utilization of coal-bed methane, considered a
strategic energy of the 21st century, has drawn the attention of
all countries in the world.
</P>
<P>
China's total coal-bed methane resources are listed at 35,000
billion cubic meters, equivalent to 45 billion tons of standard
coal and equal to the country's conventional natural gas
resources, and three times the reserves in the United States.
</P>
<P>
The CUBM was founded in 1996 jointly by the Ministry of Coal,
the Ministry of Geology and Natural Resources, and the China
National Petroleum and Natural Gas Corp, with an aim to advance
the exploration of coal-bed methane in China.
</P>
<P>
CUBM is responsible for the prospecting, exploration of
coal-bed methane resources, related production, pipeline
installation, transmission and processing of coal-bed methane.
</P>
<P>
The company has been given an independent budget status and the
autonomy of cooperation with overseas partners, as well as a
series of other corporate preferential policies.
</P>
<P>
Chen Minghe, chairman of CUBM, held that the exploration and
utilization of coal-bed methane has bright prospects even though
China started late.
</P>
<P>
"But exploration of coal-bed methane demands high investment
and has great risks, so China will practice strategies including
increasing overseas cooperation to introduce more technology and
funds so as to advance development of the coal-bed methane
industry," he said.
</P>
<P>
So far, international companies from the United States and
Australia have invested in the exploration of coal-bed methane in
China. In addition to today's contract-signing, CUBM has completed
negotiations over cooperation with overseas investors in six
coal-bed methane exploration projects.
</P>
<P>
China has designated coal mines in Liaoning, Anhui, Hebei and
Shanxi provinces as pilot projects for coal-bed methane
development. It will is considering setting up two coal-bed
methane bases in north China's Shanxi Province to undertake
industrial exploration.
</P>
<P>
By the end of this century, these coal mines and projects
should be able to produce one billion cubic meters of coal-bed
methane annually, and 10 billion cubic meters by the year 2010.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980108.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
