<HEADLINE> China to Introduce New Curriculum in Senior Middle Schools </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 8 (Xinhua) -- China will soon introduce a new
curriculum into senior middle schools nationwide to encourage
students to learn more, the State Education Commission announced
today.
</P>
<P>
The current curriculum was written in 1990 and is considered
outmoded. Many people have criticized the courses as dull and
eroding students' creativity. They say the curriculum is not good
for teaching students how to solve practical problems.
</P>
<P>
The new curriculum will incorporate class meetings, scientific
inventions, sports, artistic performances and social activities
into the formal courses. Also, a morality course will be
emphasized.
</P>
<P>
An obligatory course will be added to improve students'
artistic sense.
</P>
<P>
"The curriculum places importance on basic knowledge, skills
and capability, and is aimed at developing the student's
personality," said Ji Baocheng, a commission official in charge of
the reform.
</P>
<P>
The curriculum will also allow students to choose some courses
in which they are interested and which might be helpful for
their employment if they cannot enter university after graduation.
</P>
<P>
The curriculum has been used by 210,000 students on a trial
basis in Shanxi and Jiangxi provinces and Tianjin Municipality
selected by the commission. The commission's goal is for every
senior middle school in China to use the curriculum by 2000.
</P>
<P>
Education experts said that the reform will directly affect 10
million students on campuses.
</P>
<P>
They say only when the education sector in China takes into
consideration the moderization drive, the world and the future,
can it cultivate people who are able to cope with challenges in
the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
The term of China's senior middle school is three years, and
the students' age ranges between 16 and 19. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
