<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Two U.S. Air Force pilots
survived Tuesday when their F-16 fighters collided over the Utah
Test and Training Range west of the Great Salt Lake.
</P>
<P>
The collision occurred in the afternoon during a training
mission, said Capt. Dennis Mehring of Hill Air Force Base, some
105 miles (170 kilometers) east of the test and training range.
</P>
<P>
One of the pilots, Capt. Scott Hufford, managed to land his
fighter at a nearby airfield while the other, Capt. Paul
Hertzberg, ejected safely, said reports reaching here.
</P>
<P>
Hertzberg's fighter, however, crashed on the training range.
</P>
<P>
Since last September 13, when an Air Force C-141 transport
collided with a German military plane off the coast of Africa and
killed 33 people, Air Force B-1B, B-52, T-38 and F-16 have
experienced crashing, missing target, colliding in a number of
disasters and incidents.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's collision has been under investigation. 
