<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, U.K. Step up Actuarial Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 8 (Xinhua) -- A workshop on international
actuarial systems and the development of actuarial science in
China was hosted by the Insurance Institute of China and United
Kingdom-based Eagle Star Insurance Company here today.
</P>
<P>
This was the first workshop of its kind held in
China. Officials from Chinese government agencies such as the
People's Bank of China and the State Commission for Restructuring
Economic Systems, professionals from nine countries and regions
including the United Kingdom and the United States, and executives
from China's top insurance companies attended the discussion.
</P>
<P>
The delegates held that the growth of an actuarial system and
intensive training of actuaries are crucial to the building of a
sophisticated insurance industry in China.
</P>
<P>
Duncan Ferguson, president of the British Institute of
Actuaries, said: "The Institute of Actuaries would like to see a
Chinese actuarial institute qualify as a full member of the
International Actuarial Association in time and will be pleased to
help the Chinese actuaries achieve that objective."
</P>
<P>
As an attempt toward this end, the London-based institute,
together with Eagle Star and China's Central University of Finance
and Economies held an award ceremony here Wednesday for Chinese
actuarial students who had excellent performances in the master's
program co-sponsored by the three parties.
</P>
<P>
This was the third award ceremony held since the program was
launched in 1993.
</P>
<P>
According to Ferguson, the success rate for the Chinese
students who were enrolled in the program is 70 percent on the
examinations, while that of British students is 50 percent. The
achievement was especially hard won because the exams are
conducted in English, he said.
</P>
<P>
In the last four years, Eagle Star has spent 10 million yuan
(1.2 million US dollars) on the program. It plans to inject
another 5 million yuan in the next two years.
</P>
<P>
Eagle Star, the first European insurer to have a presence in
China, set up a representative office in Beijing in 1992, and has
two more representatives in Shanghai and Guangzhou.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
