<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mao's Hometown Becomes Revolution Museum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Shaoshan, hometown of late
Chinese leader Mao Zedong, has become a giant outdoor museum
dedicated to the country's revolutionary history.
</P>
<P>
In the last 10 years 40 Chinese leaders visited Shaoshan in
Xiangtan County, central China's Hunan Province, and wrote
inscriptions, while nearly 20 universities and colleges made the
place a center for moral education.
</P>
<P>
Statistics also show that Shaoshan has been visited by 14
million people from other parts of China since 1986.
</P>
<P>
Since the Hunan provincial government designated Shaoshan as a
revolution memorial center and tourism resort in 1986, local
residents have restored historic relics and built additional
tributes to the revolution.
</P>
<P>
A bronze statue of Mao, a forest of stone tablets with
inscriptions of Mao's poetry and Mao's library have been
constructed in addition to Mao Zedong's former residence and
memorial hall.
</P>
<P>
The local government also collected 10,000 pieces of documents
with historic value and precious articles left by Mao, and has
initiated a publicity campaign to promote the exhibition of this
material.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980108.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Economy Grows in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Russia's gross domestic product
(GDP), industrial output and retail trade grew by 1.2 percent, 3.2
percent and 3.9 percent respectively in 1997, Prime Minister
Viktor Chernomyrdin said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The country also saw an 11 percent inflation, lower than half
of the 1996 level, a 2.5 percent increase in incomes and a 5.7
percent decrease in unemployment, Chernomyrdin told the first
cabinet session of the year.
</P>
<P>
He was quoted by the Interfax News Agency as saying the country
entered the New Year without wage arrears, with over 15 trillion
rubles having been channeled from the federal budget to provinces
to pay off the arrears.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank of Russia, together with the government,
managed to guarantee the stability of the ruble in 1997, despite
the international financial crisis, the prime minister said.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin indicated that tax collection would be the main
task of the cabinet in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The low tax collection led to the poor implementation of the
budget, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
