<HEADLINE> Shanghai Police Send New Year's Greetings To Taxi Drivers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, January 8 (Xinhua) -- On the first day of the new
year, some 80,000 taxi drivers in Shanghai received New Year's
cards from Liu Yungeng, director of the municipal public security
bureau.
</P>
<P>
The cards, wishing the city's drivers a happy new year,
suggested that the drivers should take certain precautions to
avoid possible incidents and stay in contact with police via the
emergency line.
</P>
<P>
With over 38,000 taxis using the city's streets each day, it is
witness to sporadic incidents of taxi-hijacking, even though steps
have been taken to halt the crime, and the police were sending
more suggestions.
</P>
<P>
Local police sources say that the Qiangsheng Taxi Company,
which has constant contact with the police emergency line, has
provided information 98 times for the police and has helped solve
a dozen major crimes in the past two months.
</P>
<P>
Other major taxi companies are also said to be looking for ways
to co-operate with the police to help maintain social order in the
city. 
</P>
