<HEADLINE> Guangdong Province Ranks First in Tourism for 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, January 8 (Xinhua) -- South China's Guangdong
Province earned 2.8 billion U.S. dollars in foreign exchange from
tourism in 1997, ranking first in the country for five consecutive
years.
</P>
<P>
The earnings represent a 6.1 percent increase over 1996, and
accounts for one-fourth of the country's total.
</P>
<P>
Local statistics show that 43.5 million tourists visited the
province in 1997, up 8.7 percent over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The province is rich in tourism resources and has a close
cultural relationship with nearby Hong Kong and Macao.
</P>
<P>
The provincial cities received 7.25 million overseas tourists
in 1997 -- including 5.91 million from Hong Kong, Taiwan and Macao
-- up 4.9 percent from 1996. About 1.34 million of the urban
visitors were from foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
The number of overseas tourists visiting the provincial capital
of Guangzhou, the Zhuhai special economic zone, Dongguan and
Zhongshan (the former home of Dr. Sun Yat-sen) all showed notable
increases in 1997.
</P>
<P>
To attract more overseas tourists, the provincial government
has invested in tourism facilities, expedited construction of key
sites
 and provided a wide range of services.
</P>
<P>
Efforts have been made to organize overseas travel services on
a promotional tour of the province. Provincial travel services
also directly went abroad to organize overseas tourists.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the province is linked to the Internet to tap
computer-savvy international tourists. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
