<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Up in Light Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The Australian stock market
closed in positive territory after a day marked by light trading
Thursday, with investors keeping a weather eye on the mercurial
Asian markets.
</P>
<P>
Henderson Charlton Jones dealer Scott Emms said the local
bourse was still keeping a close eye on what was happening in
Japanese and Hong Kong sharemarkets and their potential impact on
the United States.
</P>
<P>
"Obviously Japan has had a bit of a positive influence today,
but overall it was a pretty steady day," Emms said.
</P>
<P>
There were renewed fears of a flow-on effect impacting on the
U.S. economy if the Japanese Government in particular did not take
action to fix the country's economy, he said.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index closed 3.8 points up at 2,650.7, off a
low of 2,633.7, with an improvement in industrial stocks
offsetting continuing weakness in major resource companies.
</P>
<P>
Overnight in New York, stocks finished modestly lower after
rebounding from a steep slide spurred by the mounting uncertainty
over how much U.S. companies are being hurt by the economic crisis
in Asia.
</P>
<P>
Locally, the all industrials index finished the day 11.3 points
stronger at 4,574.5.
</P>
<P>
The banking index shot up 42.3 points to 5,683.4, with the
Commonwealth Bank following on from Wednesday's comparatively good
performance to again be the best of the banks, up 20.4 cents.
Commonwealth shares reached an intra-day high of 18.68 Australian
dollars.
</P>
<P>
ANZ closed steady at 10.31 Australian dollars, National
Australia Bank rose 29 cents and Westpac added six cents.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index fell 2.9 points to 1,111.6, among
resource stocks BHP was down 10.3 cents, amid continuing copper
price weakness, WMC lost 10 cents and MIM gained three cents.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was a light 320.84 million shares worth
930.59 million Australian dollars (595.57 million U.S. dollars),
with rises slightly outnumbering falls by 495 to 492.  
</P>
</TEXT>
