<HEADLINE> Macao Yaohan Group Declared Bankrupt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The Macao Yaohan Department Store,
one of the chain shops of the Yaohan Group, was declared bankrupt
by a Macao court on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The declaration was the latest insolvency of the worldwide
group. The Macao store, which opened in 1992, stopped running last
November following the announcement of liquidation of the Yaohan
Hong Kong store.
</P>
<P>
The Macao Daily News quoted a court notice as saying creditors
should report to the court their creditor's rights within 60 days
from the publication of the notice on the Government Gazette.
</P>
<P>
An independent commissioner will be appointed later by the
court to handle the liquidation affairs, the report said.
</P>
<P>
But the department store resumed its operation just days before
Christmas in the name of "New Yaohan" with the agreement of the
liquidator of the Yaohan Hong Kong store, property owners and
renters of the Macao store.
</P>
<P>
The largest property owner, the Macao Tourism and Amusement
Company, paid a bail of 1.6 million patacas (about 200,000 U.S.
dollars) for a six-month trial operation before the reopening of
the store.
</P>
<P>
The Macao Yaohan owes some 600 creditors a total of more than
200 million patacas (about 25 million dollars), including rents to
property owners and initial investment to its parent company.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980108.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Plunge Sharply on Singapore Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Share prices plunged sharply
on the Singapore market as the benchmark Straits Times Industrials
Index (STII) fell all the way down from 1,368.06 points to 1,270.7
points at the closing of trade on Thursday, losing 97.36 points.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said fears that Indonesia's financial turmoil will hurt
Singapore banks' earnings fueled a sell-off in banking stocks.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, concerns that the slumping property market in
Singapore will hurt banks' earnings also triggered selling in
banking stocks, they said.
</P>
<P>
The total market volume increased to 243.47 million units,
valued at 502.99 million Singapore dollars (about 282.58 million
U.S. dollars). Declines overwhelmed advances by 338 to 47, while
227 other counters remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
The Singapore Technologies Engineering was the most actively
traded counter as it registered a turnover of 15.56 million units.
It was followed by Asian Food and Property which had 12.3 million
shares traded. DBS (Development Bank of Singapore) Land was next
with 12.01 million units changed hands.
</P>
<P>
Ipco Warrant led the gainers of the day as it rose by 17 cents
to finish at 1.15 U.S. dollars. IPCO increased by 10 cents to end
at 2.4 U.S. dollars, while Liang Huat was up by 8.5 cents to close
at 38 Singapore cents.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, DBS Foreign was the biggest loser as it
declined by 1.9 dollars to end at 11.9 Singapore dollars. OCBC
(Overseas Chinese Banking Corporation) Foreign and the UOB (United
Overseas Bank) Foreign fell by 1.2 dollars each to close at 7.5
and 7.2 Singapore dollars respectively. OUB (Overseas Union Bank)
Foreign lost 95 cents to finish at 5.25 Singapore dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
