<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Legislature Voter Registration Improves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Robin Ip, deputy secretary for
Constitutional Affairs, said here Thursday that the vote
registration in functional constituencies (FCs) for the May
Legislative Council election (FCs) has improved.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of voter registration in FCs at a press conference
here Thursday morning, Ip said the situation in agriculture and
fisheries, transport, and insurance is particularly encouraging.
</P>
<P>
However, he said the situation in a number of FCs is still
worrying, including sports, performing arts, culture and
publication, import and export, textiles and garment, information
technology and wholesale and retail.
</P>
<P>
Ip urged those eligible voters in FCs to get registered as soon
as possible before the deadline of registration on January 16.
</P>
<P>
The first Legislative Council election of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region will be held here on May 24, this year.
</P>
<P>
The 60-member Legislative Council will be made up of 20 to be
returned by geographical constituencies through direct elections,
30 by functional constituencies and 10 by an Election Committee
election.
</P>
<P>
The functional constituencies which are composed of major
organizations' representatives of 30 sectors such as urban and
regional councils, health services, insurance, finance, labor and
social welfare are of importance in the community.
</P>
<P>
Ip said: "we have had a series of briefings for major
organizations to explain the registration process and to urge
their members to get registered."
</P>
<P>
The Registration and Electoral Office (REO) is making thousands
of telephone calls to those eligible voters for registration and a
second round of letters have also been issued by the REO to
eligible voters, he said.
</P>
<P>
Ip said it will not be possible to extend the voter
registration deadline owing to the tight timetable for preparing
the first legislature election, with many key steps governed by
statutory deadlines.
</P>
<P>
The REO has to publish a provisional register before February
15. This means after the close of registration on January 16, the
REO has less than a month to verify the eligibility of the
electors, process the data by computer, and print the register, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Noting some suggestions for compulsory registration, Ip
stressed that this will not be adopted for this coming election.
</P>
<P>
"After the election in May, we will, as usual, review the
various aspects of the election, including the method of voter
registration," he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
