<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Runs Out of Puff </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The embattled Australian dollar
again ran out of puff Thursday as it sank from the highs reached
overnight.
</P>
<P>
The local unit closed the session at 63.68 U.S. cents, up from
63.43 late Wednesday, but nowhere near the 64.55 reached in an
offshore rally.
</P>
<P>
The currency had started trading on a much stronger footing
after the U.S. dollar fell markedly against the Japanese yen
overnight thanks to Bank of Japan intervention.
</P>
<P>
However, the Australian dollar's strength was short-lived as
the greenback again strengthened at the expense of regional
currencies.
</P>
<P>
This followed a meeting early Thursday in Washington between
influential Japanese Vice-Minister for International Affairs
Eisuke Sakakibara and Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan.
</P>
<P>
Speculation about possible joint intervention by the central
banks to halt the U.S. dollar's surge and the Japanese yen's slide
kept the greenback in check early.
</P>
<P>
However, no news of joint action emerged and the U.S. dollar
strengthened against the yen.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian rupiah was again the main regional victim,
crashing past the psychological 10,000 level against the U.S.
dollar.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah's plunge came amid speculation about a debt
moratorium by Indonesia and concerns over a lack of commitment by
Jakarta to International Monetary Fund reforms.
</P>
<P>
Locally, retail sales and building approvals data released
Thursday were largely ignored by both the foreign exchange and
debt markets as they focused on developments offshore.
</P>
<P>
Economists said the Australian dollar will be kept bouncing
between 0.60 and 0.65 U.S. dollars for several months as fears of
an imminent current account deficit blowout gather momentum.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar ended Thursday at 84.39 yen from 84.61
Wednesday and at 1.1621 Deutsche marks, from 1.1634.  
</P>
</TEXT>
