<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambezi Basin Selected for Water Resources </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The Zambezi River basin has been
selected as initial focus for collaboration on improving
availability and management of African water resources, according
to lastest issue of Africa recovery.
</P>
<P>
As the largest of the the African river systems flowing into
the Indian Ocean, the Zambezi River basin has been selected as a
focus by the special initiative's informal water working group to
demonstrate coordination of U.N. efforts and inter-agency
cooperation, the U.N. publication said.
</P>
<P>
The Zambezi basin must be managed effectively to mitigate the
effects on water supply of increased population, industrial and
mining development, and greater irrigated food production, the
U.N. said.
</P>
<P>
Over 250 million people in Africa have no access to safe
drinking water, and almost 300 million lack adequate sanitation,
it said.
</P>
<P>
"If the current situation does not improve, an estimated 500
million Africans are likely to be without safe water and
sanitation by the year 2020 given the rate of population growth,"
said the publication.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Environment Program (UNEP) and the Southern African
Development Community (SADC) have developed a project for the
equitable use of shared water resources which will be tested in a
pilot project and sector studies in the Zambezi basin, and
replicated in the other water basins in the SADC region.
</P>
<P>
The World Meteorological Organization (WMO) and the United
Nations Industrial Development Organization (UNIDO) are working
on a project to rehabilitate and improve the network for
monitoring water quality within the Zambezi basin.
</P>
<P>
The Zambezi Basin, shared by eight countries and covering
about 1.35 million square kilometers, forms a major part of SADC,
where over 70 million people lack access to safe water. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
