<HEADLINE> Motorola to Increase Investment in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Motorola will increase its
investment in China from 1.2 billion U.S. dollars to 2.5 billion
U.S. dollars by the year 2000, said P.Y. Lai, president of
Motorola (China) Electronics Co.
</P>
<P>
The Motorola production center in Tianjin, a port city
neighboring Beijing, has absorbed 1.2 billion U.S. dollars and
turned itself into a powerful manufacturing force with
approximately 10,000 employees, Lai said. A second Motorola
production center will be located in Suzhou City of east China's
Jiangsu Province.
</P>
<P>
The company also will invest 280 million U.S. dollars in Leshan
of northwestern Sichuan Province, to start an export-oriented
semi-conductor industry, Lai said.
</P>
<P>
All investment will come directly from the profits Motorola has
made in China, he said. By 2000, the company's investment will
amount to 2.5 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Lai said Motorola is confident in the potential here because of
China's lasting economic boom and the government's commitment to a
stable currency exchange rate.
</P>
<P>
The country's stable political situation, high economic growth
rate and foreign currency reserves of 140 billion U.S. dollars
were cited by Lai as factors in a sound financial order and smooth
domestic market.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Motorola will launch its North Asia business center
in Beijing this year, and will enhance cooperation with China in
such frontier technologies as satellite and data communications
systems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
