<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Divorce School Opens to Resolve Marital Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 8 (Xinhua) -- China's divorce rate has been
increasing in recent years as a result of overwhelming social
changes brought on by the country's reform and opening-up drive
which started in 1979, according Wenhui Bao a major Chinese
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
To deal with the situation, Beijing has opened a divorce school
providing courses and a counseling service to help estranged
couples mend their endangered marriages.
</P>
<P>
Students of the school are couples who have applied for
divorce. The teachers are volunteers from the district Trade
Union, the Federation of Women and the court system.
</P>
<P>
Among the first eight couples to graduate from the school, one
couple withdrew their divorce application.
</P>
<P>
"The schools' efforts in saving marriages, though weak, are
very worthwhile," said Chen Yijun, a researcher at the Sociology
Institute under the Chinese Academy of Social Science.
</P>
<P>
China's divorce rate has climbed from 3.7 percent to 8.7
percent in the 1981-1991 period, and Beijing's rate has jumped
from 2.5 percent to 16.6 percent in the same period. The rate
climbed to 23.8 percent in 1995, and 25 percent in 1996. And the
divorce rate is expected to increase in the next few years.
</P>
<P>
Chen suggested providing scientific knowledge about marriage
and family to the public, and educating engaged couples to be more
aware of their responsibilities for families and children.
</P>
<P>
"The divorce school is just a beginning, " Chen said. "More
such agencies should be available to provide legal and
psychological counseling to these couples."
</P>
<P>
The rising divorce rate in China, especially in urban areas,
can lead to many social problems in housing, children's education,
custody and division of property, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
More trained sociologists who specialize in marriage and family
sciences are needed to help women and men deal with the
psychological and social problems when divorce is unavoidable.
</P>
<P>
The school was opened by the Marriage Registration Office under
the Civil Affairs Bureau of Chongwen District, one of five urban
districts of Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Some Chinese social organizations plan to open more schools to
try to avoid or save ruptured marriages. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
