<HEADLINE> China to Crack Down on Illegal Cultural Activities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The Ministry of Culture is
planning a nationwide crackdown on misbehavior in karaoke halls,
night clubs, art galleries and VCD shops.
</P>
<P>
Huang Zhengchun, a spokesman for the ministry, said at a news
conference here today that the market is developing quickly and
there is a certain amount of chaos and disorder. Because of that,
he said, steps will be taken this year to cope with the problems.
</P>
<P>
Some of the problems cited by Huang include VCD piracy, illegal
publications, vulgar performances, sexual services, gambling, and
sales of fake artwork.
</P>
<P>
The official said that 1998 has been designated by the ministry
as China's first "Legal Year for the Cultural Market," during
which the market is expected to get on a sounder track.
</P>
<P>
The ministry will try to implement three new regulations on
cultural market management, make the supervision team more
powerful to enforce the new rules, and launch a publicity campaign
to make everyone understand the law.
</P>
<P>
Illegal activities will be policed, and a clean market will be
restored, he vowed.
</P>
<P>
This will be one of the greatest actions China has ever taken
over the past decades to manage the cultural market, Huang said.
</P>
<P>
Liu Zhongde, minister of culture, has signed a regulation on
administrative punishment to guide the crackdown on illegal
activities.
</P>
<P>
China has 4,000 cultural supervision offices with 50,000
workers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
