<HEADLINE> Manila, Leftist Rebels Make Progress in Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The peace talks between the
Philippine government and the leftist rebel National Democratic
Front (NDF) have made progress by reaching an agreement on human
rights issues, a statement from the government negotiation panel
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The accord was reached after two and a half days of intensive
discussions on the Comprehensive Agreement on Human Right and
International Human Law in The Hague, the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
However, the statement said, the panels are encountering
difficulty in resolving some contentious provisions and they
agreed to continue their talks.
</P>
<P>
The NDF wants the inclusion of provisions from the Geneva
Conventions and Protocol I which refer to rules on the conduct of
international conflict between sovereign states, it said.
</P>
<P>
The government panel insists that inclusion of such provisions
impinges on the government's constitutional sovereignty and
integrity.
</P>
<P>
The government accepts the inclusion of humanitarian principles
and standards governing internal conflict as embodied in Common
Article 3 of the Geneva Conventions, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The NDF, the political wing of the Communist Party of the
Philippines, has been engaging in the peace talks with the
government sporadically on human rights issues since 1992 in the
Netherlands, where rebel leaders live.
</P>
<P>
The NDF and its military wing, the New People's Army, have
fought the government for more than three decades and still has a
presence in many hinterland areas, including some rural villages
around metropolitan Manila.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
