<DOCNO> XIE19980108.0196 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-08 10:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Prospects for Forming National Unity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 8 (Xinhua) -- A national unity government
for Israel in order to same the Middle East peace process? This
has become a hot topic here but is unlikely to turn into reality
very soon.
</P>
<P>
The reason: opposition Labor Party Chairman Ehud Barak is
against it.
</P>
<P>
Following David levy's resignation as foreign minister on
Sunday, some politicians of the ruling Likud Group expressed
their worries about the right-wing coalition government's future
political stability. They pointed out that the immediate threat to
the government would be the issue of how to carry out the second
stage troop redeployment in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
In fact, it is the coalition government that has internal
conflicts on Israel's long overdue troop redeployment. The
majority cabinet and Knesset (parliament) members of the coalition
oppose the pullback.
</P>
<P>
At least eight Likud Knesset members (KMs) have expressed their
strong opposition to the redeployment, warning Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu that they would support a no-confidence motion
against him if he agrees to a further pullback.
</P>
<P>
Defense Minister Yitzhak, from Likud, announced Wednesday night
that he would quit the government unless it implements a further
pullback in the West Bank in three months.
</P>
<P>
With the departure of dovish Levy and his Gesher (bridge)
Party, the Likud faction is left with only a one-set majority in
the 120-seat Knesset. This razor-thin parliamentary majority could
easily bring the government down if some coalition KMs vote
against the government along with the opposition.
</P>
<P>
In this circumstances, the coalition partner the Third Way
Party has raised again the proposal of forming a national unity
government with the Labor Party, not only for the purpose of
maintaining the political stability, but for the sake of the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Former Prime Minister Shimon Peres also discussed this proposal
on Wednesday in the Knesset with his Labor colleagues, suggesting
that the Labor reach an agreement with the coalition to join the
Netanyahu government for six months, during which there would be a
substantial West Bank pullback.
</P>
<P>
The agreement would also call for holding elections after six
months, and that after elections, both parties would set up a
national unity government and rotate the premiership.
</P>
<P>
"Netanyahu will kill the peace process to save his government.
His majority is too slim to pass redeployment. I wanted to assure
the necessary majority for redeployment," Peres said.
</P>
<P>
But his proposal was rejected by Barak, the party leader, who
said such an agreement could save Netanyahu and his coalition from
tumbling down.
</P>
<P>
The Third Way Party, in a statement issued Wednesday night,
called Barak and the Labor members to adopt Peres's proposal and
urged Labor to rise above party interests and unite to further the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
Looking at the current political situation and party conflicts
in Israel, however, prospects for forming a national unity
government are really dismal, at least for the time being. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980108.0197 </DOCNO>
