<HEADLINE> Insurance Giant's Income from Premiums up 35.7 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 8 (Xinhua) -- China's largest insurance
company reported a 35.7 percent increase in its premium income
last year while maintaining its market share at above 70 percent,
company statistics show.
</P>
<P>
The People's Insurance Company of China (PICC) received 78.8
billion yuan (9.5 billion U.S. dollars) in premiums in 1997, up
35.7 percent from the previous year, or 117 percent of the
budgeted figure, company chairman Ma Yongwei announced today.
</P>
<P>
A breakdown shows that PICC's annual life insurance premiums
surged more than 80.89 percent to 38.9 billion yuan last year,
while those from property insurance were up 8.3 percent to 38
billion yuan. Premiums from the re-insurance business jumped 32.9
percent to 10.5 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
While the PICC's premium income grew steadily last year, its
payment viability improved markedly.
</P>
<P>
Company statistics indicate that the value of PICC's reserve
funds for insurance responsibilities by the end of 1997 was 11.88
billion yuan, or 20 percent, more than a year ago. Bank deposits
accounted for 45 percent of the insurer's total assets at the end
of last year, up 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese insurance giant paid a total of 36.86 billion yuan
in redemptions in 1997, according to Ma, who attributed the stable
business growth of its company to increased efforts to prevent and
ward off financial risks.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the PICC established a specialized agency for the
management of high-risk business as well as improved financial and
accounting practices among its grass-root subsidiaries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
