<DOCNO> XIE19980108.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-08 09:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Khatami: No Need for Iran to Resume Ties with US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, January 8 (Xinhua) - Iranian President Mohammad
Khatami stated early this morning that there was no need for
Iran to have diplomatic relations with the United States since
Washington was still adopting a hostile policy towards Iran.
</P>
<P>
"We fell no need for ties with the U.S. especially as the
modern world is so diverse and plural that we can reach our
objectives without U.S. assistance," Khatami said in his interview
with the American TV network CNN.
</P>
<P>
Khatami in his first address to the "great American people"
criticized the U.S. Administration for its policies of
domination, saying that the "policies pursued by American
politicians outside the United States over the past half a
century since the World War II was incompatible with the American
civilization which is founded on democracy, freedom and human
dignity."
</P>
<P>
"I fell that American politicians should realize the fact
and adjust themselves with the standards of the Anglo-American
and American civilization and at least apologize to their own
people because of the approach they have adopted," he said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that it was the U.S. politicians that have
adopted a hostile policy against Iran, "they have tried to
inflict economic damage upon us, a clear example of which is
the d'Amato Act which represents a continuation of Cold War
mentality" and the allocation of 20 million dollars to topple
the Iranian government.
</P>
<P>
Khatami believed that there were some mistrust and
misunderstanding between the two nations, which was caused by
the American policies.
</P>
<P>
"There must first be a crack in this wall of mistrust to
prepare for a change and create an opportunity to study a new
situation," he said, adding "unfortunately, the behavior of the
American governments in the past up to this date has always
exacerbated the climate of mistrust and we do not detect any sign
of change of behavior."
</P>
<P>
However, Khatami noted the Iranian nation has no intention to
insult the American nation when they chants "Death with the U.S.A"
and burn the American flag, saying that "these slogans symbolize a
desire to terminate a mode of relations which existed between Iran
and the United States" and was a response to the remark of former
U.S. defense secretary who said the Iranian nation must be rooted
out.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed regret to the occupation of the American
embassy in Tehran by Iranian students in November, 1979, saying
that everything must be analyzed within its own context and the
incident occurred "within the context of revolutionary fervor and
pressures to which the Iranian nation was subjected."
</P>
<P>
"Today we are in the period of stability, and fully adhere to
all norms of conduct regulating relations between nations and
governments," he said.
</P>
<P>
Khatami reiterated his stance for dialogues between the Iranian
and American nations, saying that nothing should prevent dialogue
and understanding between the two nations, especially between
their scholars and thinkers.
</P>
<P>
"I recommend the exchange of professors, writers, scholars,
artists, journalists, and tourists," he said, but adding that
"the dialogue between civilizations and nations is different from
political relations."
</P>
<P>
Last month, Khatami announced his readiness to have a dialogue
with the "great American people," a stance welcomed by top
U.S. officials including President Bill Clinton who said "I expect
nothing but a dialogue with Iran."
</P>
<P>
However, observers here noted that there were still many
hurdles on the way for a direct dialogue between the two
governments, particularly the strong opposition from both
governments to the rapprochement between the two
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980108.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-08 09:43 </DATE_TIME>
