<HEADLINE> French FM to Visit Lebanon on Mideast Tour </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, January 8 (Xinhua) -- French Foreign Minister Hubert
Vedrine will arrive in Lebanon Sunday on a two-day visit seeking a
larger role in the Middle East and pushing the stalled peace
process forward, local newspaper the Daily Star reported today.
</P>
<P>
The official visit is Vedrine's first trip to Lebanon since
taking office in June 1997. After visiting Lebanon, he will go on
to Syria and Jordan, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
During the stay in Lebanon, Vedrine is to hold talks with his
Lebanese counterpart Farez Boueiz on the need for a greater
European role in the deadlocked Middle East peace talks, said a
Lebanese Foreign Ministry source.
</P>
<P>
The source described the trip as an "exploratory" venture in
view of the change in the French government, following the
Socialist Party majority victory in the national elections last
June.
</P>
<P>
The official visit would confirm France's support for peace on
the basis of the U.N. Security Council Resolutions 424, 425 and
338 and for Lebanon's sovereignty and territorial integrity.
</P>
<P>
Vedrine's itinerary includes the opening on Monday of the new
French Consulate here.
</P>
<P>
He is also expected to meet with Lebanon's president, prime
minister and parliament speaker on the final day of his visit, the
source said. 
