<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The following are the business
briefs from Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt had decided to lift the ban on importing
textiles to comply with relevant rules regulated by the World
Trade Organization, the Egyptian Gazette reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Egyptian government imposed a 54 percent tariff
on imported textiles, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The domestic textile producers, however, feared that the
decision of last week would expose them to keen competition of
Turkey and Asian countries despite the tariff.
</P>
<P>
They said high taxes, smuggling and expensive raw materials
would make it hard for them to compete with foreign rivals,
according to the paper.
</P>
<P>
But Egyptian Minister of Industry and Mineral Resources
Suleiman Reda had said the decision was expected to result in a
boom of the Egyptian textile industry after a long period of
isolation and lack of competition.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- A newly built poly-propylene plant of Kuwait had
sold its first batch of product in the domestic market and it was
expected to produce more for export, according to the Kuwaiti News
Agency.
</P>
<P>
Kamal Bahbahani, marketing manager of the plant belonging to
the Petrochemical Industries Company said the plant sold 24.75
tonnes of its product Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He added that it would sent its first shipment of 250 tonnes to
Syria next week and will export its product to other Arab
countries, India, Pakistan, China and countries in Africa and
Europe as international demand for the material was increasing.
</P>
<P>
The plant's annual producing capacity stood at 100,000 tonnes.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- More than 2 million passengers traveled through the
Beirut International Airport last year, set a record after the end
of Lebanon's civil war in 1990, the Lebanese Daily Star newspaper
reported.
</P>
<P>
This indicated a 17 percent rise over 1996.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese Minister of Transportation Omar Miskawi attributed the
growth to increased political stability of the country, according
to the paper.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel's Manufacturers Association had urged the
Industry and Trade Ministry to double this year's Export Promotion
Fund to 260 million shekels (74 million U.S. dollars), the local
daily Jerusalem Post reported.
</P>
<P>
The association said the supplementary funds would be used to
maintain the existing overseas markets and develop new markets in
the light of pessimistic forecast for world economic this year.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The demand for manpower in Israel rose by an
average of 15 percent in 1997, the Jerusalem Post said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The demand for academic and management professionals increased
by 23 percent and 19 percent for engineers, according to the daily.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the demand for construction workers had dropped by
47 percent due to an industry slump, the daily said.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli economists had anticipated that Israel's
gross domestic product would increase by 2.7 percent this year,
the Jerusalem Post newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
And the rate of export expansion was estimated at 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
This implied a stagnation of the Israeli economy, said
economists.
</P>
<P>
But the inflation rate would be down to 7 percent because of
budget cuts, sound monetary policy and a decrease in import prices
resulting from the East Asian economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Industry and Trade Ministry had begun to
study the implications of the Asian economic crisis on Israeli
economy and formulate tackling measures, local media reported.
</P>
<P>
Dov Mishor, director-general of the ministry, said that the
crisis erupted in Southeast Asia last year could adversely affect
Israel's economy because it exports 20 percent of the goods to the
countries in the region.
</P>
<P>
He said the crisis would mainly hit Israel's consumption goods,
as the living standards in the Southeast Asian countries had been
severely reduced. 
</P>
</TEXT>
