<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Khatami Reiterates Iran's Opposition toward </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, January 8 (Xinhua) - Iranian President Mohammad
Khatami today reiterated Tehran's opposition to the Middle East
peace process, but noting that Iran would not stand in the way.
</P>
<P>
In his interview here with the U.S. TV network CNN, Khatami
said that "we have declared our opposition to the Middle East
peace process because we believe it will not succeed. At the same
time, we have clearly said that we do not intend to impose our
views on others or we would stand in their way."
</P>
<P>
"In our view all Palestinians have the right to express their
views about their land, including millions of Palestinians in
diaspora, they too have a right to self-determination," he said,
adding that "only then can there be a lasting peace."
</P>
<P>
Khatami, in his first televised address to the American people,
stated that "we seek a peace through which Jews, Muslims and
Christians, and indeed each and every Palestinians, could freely
determine their own destiny and we are prepared to contribute
toward the realization of that peace."
</P>
<P>
The Middle East peace process is not just and it does not
address the rights of all parties in an equitable manner, he said,
adding that Iran is prepared to contribute to an international
effort to bring a just and lasting peace in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that Iran has "the greatest respect for all
Palestinians who are concerned about the future of Palestine,"
calling on the United States to avoid support for Israel."
</P>
<P>
Iran is not against Jewish people, Khatami said, adding that
the Zionists constitute a small portion of the Jewish people and
have openly declared and proven in practice that they are
expansionists.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli intransigence in the course of the current peace
process, and its failure to honor its own undertakings has
enraged even U.S. allies in the region, he said, "in my view
peace can come to the Middle East when all Palestinians, Jews and
Muslims alike, can determine the future of the land."
</P>
<P>
He criticized the U.S. Administration for accepting the
"Zionist" influence in its policies, saying that "the impression
of the people of the Middle East and Muslims in general is that
certain foreign policy decisions of the U.S. are in fact made in
Tel Aviv and not in Washington."
</P>
<P>
Khatami also denied the accusation that Iran is seeking
weapons of mass destruction, saying that Iran has joined the
Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty and the official representatives
of the International Atomic Energy Agency have inspected Iran's
facilities and confirmed that Iran's nuclear programs are for
peaceful purposes.
</P>
<P>
"It is ironic that those who are so concerned about saving
humanity from nuclear weapons, fully support Israel which is a
nuclear power and is unwilling to join the NPT or accept IAEA
safeguards while leveling allegations against Iran," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian President stated that Iran is not a nuclear
power, and will not intend to become one. 
</P>
</TEXT>
