<HEADLINE> China to Have Registered Auditors on Environment Management </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 8 (Xinhua) -- China will have its first group
of registered auditors in environment management systems (EMS)
this year.
</P>
<P>
"The register of EMS auditors will play a very important role
in ensuring the quality of auditors and the recognition of
international environmental standards to enterprises," said Chen
Chunyu, an official with a national registration committee for
auditors of environment management systems.
</P>
<P>
Chen said the committee has begun accepting applications for
registered auditors.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 people from across the nation have applied to be
registered auditors, including a large number from east coastal
areas. "There are also people from southwest China's Chongqing
Municipality and Sichuan Province," Chen said, adding that the
deadline for applications is January 31.
</P>
<P>
Many of the applicants have experience in environmental
management or have received training. Chen said that all
applicants must pass an examination to be registered auditors.
</P>
<P>
In 1996 China introduced the ISO14000, a set of international
standards for environmental management. China set up a committee
to promote the environmental qualifications of the International
Standards Organization last year. The registration committee is
its subordinate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
