<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists Use Rare Earth to Increase Fish Yield </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The fish yield in ponds is
expected to increase at least 10 percent if the fish takes fodder
with a rare-earth aminoacid additive newly developed by Chinese
scientists.
</P>
<P>
Experts from the Ministry of Agriculture said the additive,
developed by scientists from the Heilongjiang Research Institute
of Aquatic Products, is an encouraging invention and a
breakthrough in the fishery industry.
</P>
<P>
The fish fodder additive is made of rare earth chloride
together with methionine and lysine.
</P>
<P>
Scientists said the newly developed additive is easier to keep
and for fish to digest in comparison with the simple rare-earth
additives such as rare-earth chloride and rare-earth nitrate.
</P>
<P>
Trial fish breeding with the newly developed fodder additives
also proved its effectiveness. 
</P>
</TEXT>
