<HEADLINE> Kibaki Vows Never to Accept election Results </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Opposition Democratic Party of
Kenya (DP) has vowed never to accept the results of the
just-ended 1997 General Election and go to court to challenge the
outcome of the elections.
</P>
<P>
The Daily Nation today quoted DP Chairman Mwai Kibaki as
claiming at a rally here Wednesday that there was massive rigging
during the December 29 General Election.
</P>
<P>
Kibaki, the runner-up in the presidential race, hit out at his
fellow opposition colleagues, religious leaders and
non-governmental organizations who have recognized the outcome of
the polls.
</P>
<P>
"We'll never agree that Moi won fairly. Rigging is rigging,"
he stressed, adding that "we'll go to court, we'll go to
Parliament and to wananchi (people) and demand justice."
</P>
<P>
The opposition National Development Party (NDP) and Social
Democratic Party (SDP) officials did not turn out at the rally
although they were on the list of the speakers.
</P>
<P>
Presidential poll losers like Wamalwa Kijana (Ford-Kenya) and
Raila Odinga (NDP), opposition Safina and religious organizations
have so far accepted the poll results.
</P>
<P>
World leaders including those from the United State, China,
and European Union have recognized the outcome of the elections.
</P>
<P>
Odinga and Kibaki said last week that they had rejected the
election results and demanded a repeat of the polls within 21
days.
</P>
<P>
However, a day after President Daniel arap Moi's swearing in,
Odinga reversed his position, saying that he had accepted the
outcome of the elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
