<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First U.S. Stamp of 1998 Issued to Mark Chinese Tiger Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, January 7 (Xinhua) -- The United States Postal
Service issued the first stamp of this year Monday in celebration
of the Chinese Year of Tiger at a ceremony held in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
The stamp is a symbol of friendship between China and the
United States and a gift to both peoples at the Chinese Lunar New
Year, said Wang Yusheng, Chinese consul general in San Francisco,
at the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Tiger is one of the 12 symbolic animals associated with a
12-year cycle of the Chinese lunar calendar. The rest are rat, ox,
rabbit, dragon, snake, horse, sheep, monkey, rooster, dog and
boar. The Chinese Lunar New Year, which usually starts in January
or February, begins on January 28 this year.
</P>
<P>
The Postal Service began to issue the set of Chinese Lunar New
Year stamps in 1992. Clarence Lee, a Chinese-American from Hawaii,
whose work has a special paper-cut style, is chosen to design the
stamps.
</P>
<P>
The 32-cent new stamp, of which 51 million pieces have been
printed, features a multicolored tiger in the center, with the
Chinese calligraphy "Year of the Tiger" on the left upper corner.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
