<HEADLINE> Coup Plotters Alleged to Relocate Nigerian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The persons arrested in
connection with the alleged coup plot in Nigeria last December
have as one of the plans to return the national capital from
Abuja to Lagos, the government has revealed.
</P>
<P>
"They had already concluded arrangements on relocating the
federal capital back to Lagos," said federal Capital Territory
Minister Lt.-Gen. Jerry Useni, quoted by press reports today.
</P>
<P>
Briefing members of the committee of traditional rulers and
leaders of thought in Abuja Wednesday, Useni said the coup
plotters had intended to bombard the presidential villa,
assassinate the head of state and some other prominent figures.
</P>
<P>
"The coup would no doubt have turned out to be the bloodiest
in the history of this nation," he added.
</P>
<P>
Abuja, located in the middle of Nigeria, was built as national
capital beginning 1970s. but most of the ministries and
parastatals did not move from Lagos to the capital until late
1996 at a sternest warning of the government.
</P>
<P>
Most of foreign embassies and media headquarters are still in
Lagos.
</P>
<P>
In another development, Minister of State for Foreign Affairs
Alhaji Buhari Bala told visiting Guinean Ambassador Alhaji
Abraham Doubkour the coup plotters intended to extend the
transition to civil rule program for another 18 months, in
addition to plans to loot the national treasury.
</P>
<P>
Before the two ministers, Foreign Minister Tom Ikimi had
voiced similar accusations when he briefed the corps of African
envoys in Abuja Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The coup attempt was uncovered by the government on December
21, 1997 and 12 suspects, including Chief of General Staff
Lt.-Gen. Oladipo Diya and two former ministers, were arrested.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary investigations had been completed before a special
panel was set up on December 29 for a month-long further
investigations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
