ROME -- National police chiefs from seven European countries
and Turkey arrived here Wednesday to discuss ways to control the
westward exodus of Kurdish refugees.
</P>
<P>
Top police officials from Italy, Turkey, Germany, France, the
Netherlands, Austria, Belgium and Greece were scheduled to meet
Thursday for one-day talks on illegal immigration, and better
controls of the European borders.
</P>
<P>
More than 1,200 immigrants, mostly Turkish and Iraqi Kurds,
arrived in southern Italy in recent weeks. They sparked a debate
that has since spread to other European Union countries on how to
deal with the exodus. (Italy-Kurds)
</P>
