<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Rupiah Plunges to New Record low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian rupiah plunged to
a new record low of 10,000 against the U.S. dollar at noon trade
Thursday from 8,450 per dollar Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
At 9:30 a.m. local time the rupiah opened with 9,500 against
the greenback.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah has lost about 250 percent of its value against the
U.S. dollar since July last year.
</P>
<P>
Currency dealers said the main causes of the weakness of rupiah
were the strong demand for dollars by the corporate to pay
maturing short-term debts and the worry expressed by the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) over the Indonesian government's
commitments to restructure the nation's economy.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia has 119 billion dollars foreign debts, out of them 65
billion dollars were private sector debts. The private sector has
to pay 9.6 billion maturing debts at the end of 1997, official
sources said early.
</P>
<P>
IMF officials on Tuesday called Indonesia's economic crisis
worrisome, faulting the Jakarta government for failing to follow
through on pledges to restructure the nation's economy.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia, which agreed on an IMF-led bailout of over 30
billion dollars in October last year, has committed to conduct a
series of reforms, including reforms in financial, fiscal and
banking sectors.
</P>
<P>
On January 6, the Indonesian government announced a budget that
failed to meet target set by the IMF under the bailout deal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980108.0217 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-08 09:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt FM: 1998 Decisive for Mideast Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa has said that 1997 is "a bad year for peace" in the Middle
East and that the decisive moment for the peace process is "round
the corner," local newspaper Al Ahram reported today.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the English weekly, Moussa said that the
"first few weeks of 1998 may well determine the fate of the peace
process as a whole."
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, Moussa was not optimistic about the prospects for
the peace process in 1998. "My expectations are not very bright. I
am not very optimistic. I hope there will be room for some
progress," he said.
</P>
<P>
This depends on what is going to happen in the U.S.-Israeli and
U.S.-Palestinian meetings," Moussa said in the interview.
</P>
<P>
In order to break the peace deadlock, U.S. President Bill
Clinton will meet Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu in the
White House on January 20 and Palestinian National Authority
President Yasser Arafat two days later.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said the U.S. role, particularly in the coming few
weeks, will be instrumental, "simply because there remains nothing
within the framework of the peace process but for the U.S. to play
its role as an honest broker."
</P>
<P>
"Now the critical moment has come. Now is the time the
U.S. must play this role with vigor and even-handedness," he said.
</P>
<P>
Moussa blamed Netanyahu's uncompromising policies "putting
everything in terms of black and white" that brought the peace
process to this "either/or" situation.
</P>
<P>
"Netanyahu's policies have brought into sharp focus the real
Israelis policies and demands under the Likud, with no sugar
coating on them, non, whatsoever," said Moussa.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the resignation of Israeli Foreign Minister David
Levy, which has put the Likud-led right-wing coalition government
in Israel on the brink of collapse, was no excuse for
procrastination.
</P>
<P>
Moussa, a veteran of Egyptian-Israeli peace negotiations,
insisted that Washington was fully capable of brokering a balanced
peace, despite Netanyahu's intransigence, citing U.S. mediation
between Israel and Egypt nearly two decades ago.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian minister showed adamance in upholding the
Palestinian rights, saying that "Egypt will never help sell out
the Palestinian cause or facilitate its liquidation."
</P>
<P>
"If it is liquidation that is being discussed, then you can
count us out," said Moussa.
</P>
<P>
Egypt and Israel established diplomatic relations in 1979 but
the ties have never been warm. They further strained over the
deadlock in the Palestinian-Israeli peace talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980108.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Telecom Companies' Joint Sponsorship of HK's New Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Hongkong Telecom and China
Telecom (Hong Kong) Ltd. announced here on Thursday that they had
joined hands to sponsor the annual Lunar New Year fireworks
spectacular.
</P>
<P>
The two leading telecommunications companies of Hong Kong will
provide a total of 6.8 million HK dollars (0.87 million US
dollars) for the 23-minute Fireworks '98, which will light up the
sky of the Victoria Harbor on January 29. This is the 17th annual
New Year Fireworks display in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The display will consist of over 18,000 fireworks shells from
China's inland, Japan, Spain, Germany, Italy and the United
States. The shells will be launched from four barges in a
triangular layout in the harbor waters, which is expected to
provide the best possible views for the usually large Near Year
crowds.
</P>
<P>
A feasibility study is currently underway on the possibility of
placing speakers systems at key locations on both banks of the
harbor, to relay, for the first time in Hong Kong, the soundtrack
accompanying the display.
</P>
<P>
"This year's display is much more meaningful as it is the first
Lunar New Year since Hong Kong's handover when the people of Hong
Kong and the inland areas can celebrate together.
</P>
<P>
"Our joint sponsorship with China Telecom (Hong Kong) Ltd. for
the fireworks display shows the confidence in both the future of
Hong Kong and the continuous cooperation between the SAR and the
Mainland," said Linus Cheung, Chief Executive of Hongkong Telecom.
</P>
<P>
"In jointly sponsoring the traditional New Year fireworks
display with Hongkong Telecom, we aim at bringing happiness to the
celebrations of the Hong Kong citizens," said Chen Zhaobin,
Vice-Chairman and President of China Telecom (Hong Kong) Ltd.
</P>
<P>
The show consists of three sections, namely "New Year Salute",
"A Golden Celebration" and "Fortune Extravaganza".
</P>
<P>
And special low-level fireworks have been arranged between two
sections, which allows time for smoke to disperse.  
</P>
