<HEADLINE> Inscriptions Commemorate Late Chinese Premier Zhou Enlai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 8 (Xinhua) -- People's Daily, China's leading
newspaper, today highlighted inscriptions penned by foreign
statesmen and celebrities in its sixth edition to mark the
centenary of the birth of China's late Premier Zhou Enlai.
</P>
<P>
Zhou Enlai served as China's premier from 1949 when the
People's Republic was founded to 1976.
</P>
<P>
Norodom Sihanouk, king of Cambodia, wrote that the respected
and beloved Premier Zhou Enlai is the great and immortal hero of
the Chinese nation and the Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
Former Japanese Prime Minister Yasuhiro Nakasone said in his
inscription that the people of Japan and China should always
treasure their friendship.
</P>
<P>
Henry Kissinger, former Secretary of State of the United
States, called Zhou "a great statesman and an outstanding human
being."
</P>
<P>
Igoralexeyevich Rogachev, Russian ambassador to China, wrote in
Chinese: "Deeply cherish the memory of Comrade Zhou Enlai."
</P>
<P>
Claude Cheysson, former prime minister of France, said in his
inscription that he met Zhou Enlai in Geneva in 1954 and admired
his talents and capabilities and was deeply overwhelmed by the
style of the great man of the time.
</P>
<P>
Han Suyin -- a Chinese-British writer wrote in Chinese: "Always
cherish your memory, Premier Zhou."
</P>
<P>
The paper published the inscriptions from a photo album in
commemoration of Zhou. 
</P>
</TEXT>
