<HEADLINE> Zambia Bank Aims at 9 Percent Inflation Reduction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of Zambia has targeted
a further reduction in the inflation rate to nine percent by the
end of December 1998 while economic growth has been pegged at
between five and six percent, Zambia Daily Maily reported today.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Felix Kani, Economics Department Director of the central
bank, said Wednesday that he was confident the targeted inflation
reduction and economic growth for 1998 were sustainable going by
last year's reduction of inflation from 35 percent to 18.6
percent.
</P>
<P>
The confidence comes from several sources of growth, among
them mining, tourism and the banking and financial services
sector.
</P>
<P>
Kani pointed out that the on-going privatization of copper
mines, which represent Zambia's first economic pillar, will
improve operations and increase output through advanced
technology and astute management.
</P>
<P>
However, he said that little or no growth is expected in the
country's agricultural sector because of the effects of the El
Nino.
</P>
<P>
But because of the expected growth in the other sectors, the
dampening effects in agriculture would be offset, according to
the bank official. 
</P>
</TEXT>
