<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Defense Minister Threatens to Quit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Defense Minister
Yithzak Mordechai has threatened to resign unless the government
implements the further redeployment in the West Bank within three
months, Israel Radio reported today.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai, touted as the leading dove within the government
after the resignation of Foreign Minister David Levy earlier this
week, sounded the threat on state television Channel 3 Wednesday
night.
</P>
<P>
He did not elaborate, but said the government was capable of
carrying out the long-delayed troop redeployment and must do so.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai met with Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu earlier to
discuss the consequences of Levy's resignation and the current
visit of U.S. peace envoy Dennis Ross. Ross is here to prepare for
President Bill Clinton's meetings with Netanyahu and Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat later this month.
</P>
<P>
He said things have changed since Levy's resignation, adding
"we must seek a way to make an effort and advance with the
process."
</P>
<P>
He also demanded the Palestinian National Authority make
efforts to fight terrorism and fulfill its commitments.
</P>
<P>
The departure of Levy, a leading moderate within the rightwing
coalition, has reduced the government's parliamentary majority to
the minimal 61 seats in the 120-seat Knesset (Parliament).
</P>
<P>
This has drastically limited Netanyahu's maneuvering space in
carrying out the second pullback, over which some hardline
lawmakers threaten to topple the government.
</P>
<P>
Ross held a second meeting with Netanyahu Wednesday night to
brief the Israeli leader on his meeting with Arafat a day
earlier. He told Netanyahu that Arafat would firmly reject the
reported single-digit percentage withdrawal from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Ross also pushed for progress in the Israeli-Palestinian
negotiations on building the Gaza airport, seaport and safe
passage between Gaza Strip and West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Local media reports said Netanyahu has scaled down the
proposed percentage of second pullback from about 10 percent to
eight percent during his talks with Ross. Netanyahu is also
proposing combining the second and third redeployments stipulated
in the Oslo accords and Hebron agreement into a single operation.
</P>
<P>
Top on Ross' agenda is to try to get the two sides to agree on
a security document on improving bilateral security cooperation
and fighting terrorism. Israel has been demanding for some changes
to the draft document.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu's tough position evidently resulted in postponement
of a scheduled meeting between Ross and Arafat in Bethlehem
Wednesday night, and the meeting was rescheduled early Thursday in
Ramallah in the West Bank.

08/01/98 8:9 GMT

