<HEADLINE> Leather Export Low in COMESA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The export of leather and
leather products remains low in the Common Market for Eastern and
Southern Africa (COMESA) region although it has the abundant
resource, Zambia Daily Mail reported today.
</P>
<P>
The local newspaper quoted Robert Arunga, Director of COMESA
Leather and Leather Products Institute, as saying recently that
the institute will promote and develop the leather industry in
the region to achieve its full potential.
</P>
<P>
COMESA's cattle accounts for 60.9 percent of the cattle
population in Africa, 37.4 and 54.2 percent of the continent's
sheep and goats respectively.
</P>
<P>
The few COMESA countries dealing in the leather industry
produce low value products and are not dealing in finished
products. The countries export raw materials, it quoted an
Ethiopian publication, the Entrepreneur, as saying.
</P>
<P>
Only Ethiopia, Kenya, Sudan and Zimbabwe are said to have
sizable leather industries out of the 20 COMESA states.
</P>
<P>
As to Africa it accounts for only 1.1 percent of the annual
world trade in leather despite its estimated 18 percent share of
the global livestock population, according to the newspaper.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
