<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Determined to Go Ahead With Port Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan government is
determined to go ahead with a much delayed port development
project in the Southwestern city of Galle, a senior government
official said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
M.H.M. Ashraff, minister of port development, rehabilitation
and reconstruction, said the cabinet at a meeting Wednesday
reaffirmed its commitment and determination to carry out the
project with the objective of spearheading the overall
socio-economic development of the Southern region.
</P>
<P>
Under the project, a breakwater will be constructed while the
port be dredged to improve the capacity of the port.
</P>
<P>
The project was first discussed during the tenure of the
previous government under the United National Party (UNP) in
September 1992.
</P>
<P>
Ashraff said the selected bidder of the project, the UK-China
Consortium, was almost on the point of finalizing the necessary
financial support in collaboration with a Malaysian company when
the economies in Southeast and East Asian countries suffered a
currency devaluation of unprecedented magnitude.
</P>
<P>
He said it was the international monetary circumstances that
frustrated the government's expectations in mobilizing the
requested financial support and caused the delay.  
</P>
</TEXT>
