<HEADLINE> Vietnam to Build First Oil Refinery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Construction of Vietnam's first
oil refinery starts Thursday with a ground-breaking ceremony at
Dung Quat Bay in the central coastal province of Quang Ngai.
</P>
<P>
The long-awaited refinery is being built by the state oil giant
PetroVietnam after potential foreign investors pulled out of the
project.
</P>
<P>
The refinery will cost about 1.5 billion U.S. dollars and has a
design capacity for refining 6.5 million tons of crude oil a year.
</P>
<P>
"This is a very difficult and complicated project marking a
decisive breakthrough in the development of a petrochemical
industry," PetroVietnam's President Dr. Ho Si Thoang told Vietnam
News on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He said the refinery, called Dung Quat Refinery No.1, is "very
essential" for Vietnam's development.
</P>
<P>
PetroVietnam submitted a feasibility study in march last year,
which was prepared in collaboration with government-employed oil
consultants for the construction of the Dung Quat project.
</P>
<P>
Currently, PetroVietnam plans to get 600 million U.S. dollars
from profits it has accrued through joint venture oil exploitation
over the past decade.
</P>
<P>
Another 400 million U.S. dollars will come from foreign loans,
while the remaining 500 million U.S. dollars is yet to be raised.
</P>
<P>
The complex will include not only the first oil refinery, but
also a number of petrochemical factories.
</P>
<P>
Some refined products will be processed afterwards to produce
aromatic hydrocarbon compounds for use by the petrochemical
industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980108.0230 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Domestic Debt Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's domestic debt is set
to hit a record 4.7 billion U.S. Dollars in the near future,
posing a threat to both the economy and the government's credit,
the weekly Business reported today.
</P>
<P>
The report said the southern African country's debt currently
stands at 60 billion Zimbabwe Dollars (3.5 billion Dollars), but
gratuities to former Zimbabwean Freedom Fighters and the
acquisition of over 1,700 farms for their resettlement would add
about 20 billion Zimbabwe Dollars (1.2 billion Dollars) more to
the debt.
</P>
<P>
The weekly quoted the latest quarterly guide to the economy
from the First Merchant Bank as saying that at this level debt
service and government salaries would equal to the tax collected.
</P>
<P>
''This means that all the funds needed by the government to
provide the actual services expected of it will have to be
borrowed,'' the bank said.
</P>
<P>
It noted that as the government was under pressure to borrow
as little as possible because the money would add further to the
debt and costs of debt services, it would have to scale down its
services to the public.
</P>
<P>
This, said the bank, had already caused the scale and quality
of the services of most ministries to deteriorate and they could
now be expected to decline further.
</P>
<P>
The bank said interest and capital repayments due in the
existing debt in the 18 months ending December 31, 1998, already
came to a total of about 20 billion Zimbabwe Dollars (1.2 billion
Dollars).
</P>
<P>
It added that with the ''intensification of political
pressures and the more vigorous restatement of the government's
land redistribution intentions,'' a severe decline in confidence
had become evident in the business community. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
