<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Satellite Network on Way to Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe will benefit from the
setting up of an advanced satellite telecommunications network
which will enable mobile users and remote villagers to
communicate at affordable prices.
</P>
<P>
Four other southern African countries, Zambia, Botswana,
Mozambique and Namibia, have also been listed as first
beneficiaries of the 50-million-Dollar deal to be implemented in
two phases by African Continental Telecommunications Ltd (Actel),
the weekly ''Business'' reported today.
</P>
<P>
A spokesperson for Actel told the weekly that services will be
marketed in conjunction with telecommunications corporations of
the five African countries and in-country service providers.
</P>
<P>
The first phase of the project is expected to be in place by
late 1999, with the repositioning of a geo-stationary satellite
leased from American Mobile Satellite Corporation (Amsc).
</P>
<P>
Under the first phase, the satellite leased from Amsc will be
repositioned from its current orbital slot at 101 degrees west
(where it serves customers in the U.S.) to 11.5 degrees east.
</P>
<P>
This will enable it to provide mobile and fixed point
telephone services to businesses and individual customers in
rural and urban Africa.
</P>
<P>
Phase two will involve the construction and launch of a
replacement satellite with expanded geographic and service
delivery by 2001. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
