<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Overseas-Funded Businesses Create 17 Million Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Overseas-funded enterprises in
China have provided 17 million jobs for China, 10 percent of the
non-agricultural working people, according to sources from the
Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation (MOFTEC).
</P>
<P>
Since 1980, China has approved the establishment of more than
300,000 overseas-funded enterprises, and the 145,000 of them which
are now operational employ 17.5 million foreign and Chinese
workers with foreigners accounting for only hundreds of thousands.
</P>
<P>
MOFTEC sources also said that from 1992 to 1996, taxes
paid by overseas-funded enterprises added up to more than 200
billion yuan with an annual average increase of 58 percent.
</P>
<P>
That figure was 4.25 percent of China's total industrial and
commercial tax revenue in 1992, and 11.8 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
In the first half of last year, the tax amounted to 45.9
billion yuan, an increase of 53.18 percent over the same period of
1996, and accounted for 12.89 percent of China's industrial and
commercial taxes during the period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980108.0235 </DOCNO>
