<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya's Ruling Party Garners 114 Seats in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The ruling Kenya African
National Union (KANU) has got a total of 114 out of 222
Parliament seats in the just-concluded 1997 General Election, the
East African Standard reported today.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that out of the 210 elected seats, KANU had
collected 108 while all opposition parties in the country
garnered 102.
</P>
<P>
The 102 opposition seats are divided as follows: Democratic
Party of kenya (39), National Development Party (21), Ford-Kenya
(17), Social Democratic Party (15), Safina (4), Ford-People (3),
and Shirikisho, Ford-Asili and Kenya Social Congress one each.
</P>
<P>
Samuel Kivuitu, Chairman of the Electoral Commission of Kenya,
was quoted as saying Wednesday that in accordance with Kenya's
Constitution, KANU will be required to nominate six Members of
Parliament (MP).
</P>
<P>
The Democratic Party of kenya will nominate two MPs while
National Development Party, Ford-Kenya, Social Democratic Party
and Safina will each nominate one MP, he added.
</P>
<P>
Kivuitu noted that the proportion was calculated on the basis
of the parties' strength in parliament.
</P>
<P>
The commission chairman pointed out that all political parties
can nominate election losers as MPs, giving hope of returning
posts to former MPs and cabinet ministers who lost in the
December 29 general election.
</P>
<P>
Out of 24 former cabinet ministers, a total of 12 were
defeated during the nomination and polling of the elections.
</P>
</TEXT>
