<HEADLINE> Southeast Asian Crisis May Hit Bangladesh Exports: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The economic turmoil in Southeast
Asia may affect Bangladesh's long-term exports though the country
has so far managed to protect itself from the crisis, a finance
official said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"The long-term prospect of export may be affected by the
changes in exchange rates in Southeast and East Asian countries as
their competitiveness is increasing as a result of devaluation,"
Finance Minister Shah A.M.S. Kibria was quoted as saying by the
local press on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh's exports for the first five months of the current
fiscal year beginning July 1 rose "vigorously" with a growth of
over 20 percent over the same period of the last fiscal year, said
Kibria.
</P>
<P>
He expected the growth momentum of the country's short-term
exports to continue and remain unaffected by the Southeast Asian
crisis, "since most of our exports go to Europe and North
America."
</P>
<P>
The country's export earnings were recorded at 2.22 billion US
dollars during the July-November period, compared with 1.76
billion dollars in the corresponding period of the previous fiscal
year, according to statistics from the Exports Promotion Bureau.
</P>
<P>
The finance minister cautioned against a possible slowdown in
the country's long-term export due to the massive devaluation
caused by the currency crisis in Southeast Asia. "We have to
remain vigilant in this regard," he said.
</P>
<P>
The foreign exchange reserve of Bangladesh stood at 1.66
billion US dollars at the end of December. "The reserve will be
rising in the coming months," as there was a higher export growth,
said the finance minister.  
</P>
</TEXT>
