<DOCNO> XIE19980108.0239 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa's Botha Unlikely to Be Jailed: Experts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Former state president P.
W. Botha is unlikely to be jailed even if he is found guilty of
failing to appear before the Truth and Reconciliation Commission
(TRC), The Star daily today quoted legal experts as saying.
</P>
<P>
He was served with a summons from Western Cape
Attorney-General Frank Kahn Wednesday to appear in George
Regional Court on January 23.
</P>
<P>
Under the founding bill of the TRC, the 81-year-old Botha
faces a two-year imprisonment and/or a fine if convicted.
</P>
<P>
"I do not see Mr. Botha going to jail under any
circumstances," said Krish Govender, attorney and spokesman for
the National Association of Democratic Lawyers.
</P>
<P>
He said the case against Botha could take one or two years
because of the amount of documentation involved and the technical
and legal battle that would be triggered.
</P>
<P>
Botha has refused to testify before the TRC in person on the
workings of the now defunct State Security Council, which he
chaired during the height of apartheid conflict in the 1980s; on
raids into neighboring countries; the state's chemical warfare
program and the murder of anti-apartheid activists.
</P>
<P>
Govender said Botha could get his lawyers to challenge the TRC
because he had submitted a 1,800-page report to the TRC to answer
its questions.
</P>
<P>
He could also appeal against a court decision to the
Constitutional Court.
</P>
<P>
"I think it would be a long time before Mr. Botha even enters
the box. I also believe that even if he is given a jail sentence,
either Mr. (President Nelson) Mandela or Mr. (Deputy President
Thabo) Mbeki would pardon him as final act of reconciliation,"
Govender said.
</P>
<P>
Another expert, Lionel Reichenberg, said Botha could buy time
by getting doctors' health certificates or appealing to higher
courts.
</P>
<P>
The TRC sued Botha after he defied a third subpoena of it on
December 19.
</P>
<P>
The TRC was trying to accommodate him after he failed to
appear for the first time in November 1997, citing health
reasons. But tension began to build up when Botha told an
Afrikaans newspaper, Rapport, that he would rather be prosecuted
than appear before the TRC.
</P>
<P>
TRC Chairman Desmond Tutu, who was angry with Botha's attitude
toward his commission, had threatened him with legal action ever
since.
</P>
<P>
Tutu failed to lay criminal charges against Botha on December
5 only because of a small legal defection in the second subpoena.
</P>
<P>
Botha, who was president between 1984 and 1989, refused to
apologize for the activities of his apartheid government and
called the TRC "a circus" and "a revenge camp against the
Afrikaner."
</P>
<P>
The TRC was set up after the first all-race general elections
in 1994 to probe human rights violations in the apartheid era.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980108.0240 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Top Thai Exporters Back Shorter Forex Holding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's exporters
associations have expressed support for the government's decision
to allow exporters to hold foreign currency for a maximum seven
days instead of 15 days of receipt, and urged more steps to curb
currency speculation.
</P>
<P>
They agreed that the measures are necessary for curbing
currency speculation but called for easing liquidity to facilitate
exports, according to the Bangkok Post Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Vorapong Pitchpongsa, president of the Rice Exporters'
Association, said that it is unlikely for farm product exporters
to be involved in money speculation as they need fast cashflow in
baht for purchase of export items.
</P>
<P>
Viroj Amatakulchai, president of the Federation of Thai Textile
Industries, said that if exporters should be allowed to hang onto
foreign currency, they would use the money, at this time of tight
liquidity, to fund manufacturing rather than to speculate.
</P>
<P>
He said the high interest rates introduced to prop up the baht
had made borrowing from banks prohibitive for manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
If manufacturing companies stay inactive for lack of funds, the
threat to the economy grows and the stability and the value of the
baht are further affected.
</P>
<P>
Prof. Krirkkiat Phipatseritham of the University of the Thai
Chamber of Commerce, said investors turn to currency speculation
because the stock market is poor, pushing the baht lower than the
level it should be.
</P>
<P>
He urged the government to introduce more comprehensive
measures to tackle speculation in foreign currency.  
</P>
</TEXT>
