<HEADLINE> Shanghai Raises Efficiency in Use of Foreign Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, January 8 (Xinhua) -- East China's Shanghai
municipality, the largest commercial and industrial center in the
country, has worked to use foreign funds in a more efficient way
as the total sum of suck funding drops.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the municipality approved 1,802
foreign-funded projects in 1997, with a contracted foreign
investment of 5.32 billion US dollars, down 14.4 percent and 8.4
percent, respectively, from the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The structure of foreign investment has been improved, said
local officials, noting that more money flew to industrial
projects. The municipality also made the best use of foreign funds
for its agriculture and infrastructure construction.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, more trans-national firms entered the
municipality. In 1997, Shanghai General Motor, the largest
foreign-invested project in the city, was set up.
</P>
<P>
Fifty-five out of the 100 world top industrial transnational
firms listed in "Fortune" have invested in the municipality.
</P>
<P>
The municipal government will continue to encourage foreign
investment in agriculture, high-tech projects, environmental
protection projects and infrastructure construction. It will put
in force detailed rules on foreign-funded projects
recently. 
</P>
