<HEADLINE> Jiangsu Collects 1.5 Billion Yuan in Personal Income Tax </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, January 8 (Xinhua) -- East China's Jiangsu province
collected 1.5 billion yuan in personal income tax in 1997, nearly
double the 1996 figure.
</P>
<P>
1997 was the fourth year running for the province to record a
one hundred percent increase in income tax collection, according
to the local government.
</P>
<P>
The government attributed the achievement to the taxation
authorities' efforts to intensify management and supervision over
tax collection.
</P>
<P>
Nanjing and Suzhou cities in the province also kept files for
high-income people while Wuxi and Nantong set up a computerized
network to collect taxes from resident foreigners.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, the province launched special checks on collection
operations. Statistics show that last year, the province checked
out 380 million-yuan worth of tax evasion, accounting for one
fourth of the total revenue.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Government started to enforce the Personal Income
Tax Law in 1994, with revenues increasing by around 60 percent per
year between 1994 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
Last year China's personal income tax revenue amounted to some
25 billion yuan, according to the latest statistics of the State
Administration of Taxation (SAT). 
</P>
</TEXT>
