<HEADLINE> No Plan to Control Forex Trade in Malaysia: Mahathir </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad said Thursday his government did not have any
plan to impose a control on foreign exchange trade following the
drop of ringgit to its lowest level recently.
</P>
<P>
"If we say we are going to do that, it will result in loss of
confidence. And when there is loss of confidence, it will result
in the ringgit to further deteriorate," he told reporters after
launching an Anti-Corruption Agency (ACA)-initiated campaign to
consolidate integrity in the government machinery here.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, the ringgit kicked off the day at 4.5800 to the
U.S. dollar against the close at 4.5900 Wednesday when the State
Bank intervened in the foreign exchange market to support the
local unit. The ringgit touched an intra-day historical low of
4.8800 to the greenback Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said that as trading of foreign exchange could not be
controlled, Malaysia had to face the effects from foreign exchange
trade.
</P>
<P>
"We do not have the power to determine the value of our
currency. It is the market forces which determine it," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The position has been reversed. Now, market disciplines the
government, not the government disciplines the market. Now,
governments in East Asia are being disciplined," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
