<HEADLINE> Shanghai Residents' Consumption Pattern Changes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The consumption pattern of
residents in China's leading industrial city of Shanghai witnessed
great changes in 1997 in comparison with 1990.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from an urban social and economic investigation
group showed that by November 1997, the per capita monthly
expenditure on foods and garments accounted for 59.35 percent of
the urban residents' total expenditure, down 8 percent in
comparison with the same 1990 period.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Shanghai citizens' per capita monthly
expenditure on housing, medical treatment and health care as well
as communications and telecommunications accounted for 16.21
percent of the total, up 8.4 percent than 1990's same period.
</P>
<P>
Experts here said these changes in consumption structure
indicate a rapid improvement of Shanghai residents' living
standard. 
</P>
</TEXT>
