<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Philippine Peso on Free Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine peso has been
caught in a new round of turmoil together with other regional
currencies since the start of 1998, with its value plunging nearly
16 percent against the U.S. dollar during the past four trading
days.
</P>
<P>
Last Friday, the first trading day this year, the peso fell to
a record low of 41.80 pesos to the greenback from the close of
40.11 pesos on December 29, the last trading day in 1997, in the
Philippine Dealing System, the country's electronic spot foreign
exchange market.
</P>
<P>
The peso continued to slide against the dollar this week, with
the peso-dollar exchange rate breaching the vital psychological
level of 45 pesos to one dollar Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, the peso plunged nearly 6 percent to a scary low of
45.20 pesos to one dollar from the previous low of 42.65 pesos
recorded Monday.
</P>
<P>
The 6-percent fall represented the largest single-day loss
since July 11 last year when the Central Bank was forced to allow
the peso to move in a wider range.
</P>
<P>
The peso plummeted to a new low of 46.50 pesos to the dollar
Wednesday, but managed to strengthen toward the end of trading and
closed at 45.35 pesos to a dollar.
</P>
<P>
The local currency has so far depreciated more than 70 percent
against the greenback since its de facto devaluation in July last
year. The exchange rate prior to the currency crisis was at 26.40
pesos to a dollar.
</P>
<P>
Traders attributed the new round of free fall of the peso to
fears of a further weakening of the currency, a tremendous demand
for the dollar by corporates and the unabated tumble of other
Southeast Asian currencies.
</P>
<P>
Many participants in the Philippine Dealing System were
unwilling to sell dollars in anticipation of a further fall of the
peso and the shortage of dollars in return forced the peso lower,
traders said.
</P>
<P>
"The currency market is being entirely driven by sentiment --
and the fear is that the peso will fall further," said Cora
Guidote, head of Philippine equities at UBS Securities Ltd.
</P>
<P>
"Sentiment is so bad. Volume shows that this is a one-sided
affair. There are no sellers. You have to have a lot of guts to
sell dollars," said one trader.
</P>
<P>
This sentiment was reflected clearly Tuesday, one of the most
remarkable days in the six-month-old peso crisis, when no deals
were made in the first 30 minutes of trading as banks refused to
buy the peso at prices within an initial volatility band designed
to prevent sharp fluctuations.
</P>
<P>
The trading paralysis forced the Bankers Association of the
Philippines to widen the trading band for the peso from 4 percent
to 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
Currency dealers said declines in other Asian currencies also
added to the pressure on the Philippine currency. Many believe
that with the Thai baht falling to as low as 53 baht to the dollar
this week, it is unreasonable for the peso to stand still.
</P>
<P>
But the drastic fall of the Indonesian rupiah early this week
was the direct cause of the current wave of currency turmoil in
the region.
</P>
<P>
Another factor contributing to the peso's sharp decline is the
increasing demand for the dollar by local corporates, which needed
badly dollars to repay their maturing dollar-denominated loans and
to expand business.
</P>
<P>
Some traders said the Central Bank of the Philippines seems to
run out of ammunitions in fighting currency speculators who are
relentlessly attacking the local currency.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank, whose gross international reserves dropped to
as low as 9 billion dollars as of the end of 1997, merely enough
to finance three-month imports, can hardly intervene in the
currency market.
</P>
<P>
Central Bank Governor Gabriel Singson defended the
non-intervention policy, saying attempts to intervene in the
market were futile and would only deplete the country's dwindling
foreign reserves.
</P>
<P>
In fact, the Central Bank did take some measures to prop up the
peso, including the one-percentage-point hike of the overnight
borrowing rate to 12 percent Wednesday to add speculation cost.
But the downtrend of the peso remained.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank and the Bankers Association are now planning
to open a 30-day non-deliverable forward (NDF) facility in dollar
this week.
</P>
<P>
Under the scheme, customers can buy NDF contracts from banks
which in turn will cover their dollar loans with the Central Bank.
As a result, firms with unhedged foreign exchange exposures need
not crowd the spot foreign exchange market and the pressure on the
peso is expected to ease.
</P>
<P>
Traders said that by the end of this week, when people calm
down and the pressure is not too great, things may get better. But
they added that the latest wave of plunge of the peso and other
regional currencies indicated that the currency turmoil plaguing
the region was far from over. 
</P>
</TEXT>
