<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe to Restructure National Railways </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The National Railways of
Zimbabwe (NRZ) is seeking funds to enable it to retrench about
4,000 workers, as the loss-making parastatal embarks on major
restructuring aimed at transforming it into a viable enterprise.
</P>
<P>
NRZ board chairman Sam Geza said yesterday the government is
currently negotiating with the World Bank to provide the fund of
over one billion Zimbabwe Dollars (60 million U.S. Dollars).
</P>
<P>
The parastatal currently employs nearly 11,000 people, a
situation which Geza said is not commensurate with the
organization's capacity.
</P>
<P>
''We have to correct the ratio of salaries and wages to the
gross revenue of the NRZ, which should be 35 percent, and not the
current 70 percent. this present situation is totally
unsustainable,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
Geza said his six-month-old board will move quickly to
commercialize the NRZ in the next six months.
</P>
<P>
Before the retrenchment exercise begins, the parastatal will
first identify those units ''which should be scratched
completely, and those whose services could be out-sourced.''
</P>
<P>
Irrelevant posts will also be identified and abolished. All
the retrenched workers will be given their packages.
</P>
<P>
The commercialization of the NRZ, which has been on the cards
since 1990, will see the separation of the organization's
operations from infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
''In about two months from now we should have a total physical
separation of the two. The aim of the whole restructuring
exercise is to bring down tariffs on both rail and road networks
so that they compete internationally,'' Geza said.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet has already agreed to the separation of
infrastructure from operations, and what was now left was to
translate this into practice, he said.
</P>
<P>
A four-member task force consisting of staff from the NRZ
management was set up last December to steer the restructuring of
the parastatal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
