<HEADLINE> Brazil Wins Water Polo Opener in Swimming Worlds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PERTH, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Brazil opened the women's water polo
action in the world swimming championships with a 9-5 victory over New
Zealand on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Camilla Pedrosa gave Brazil a lead after four minutes of scoreless
action. She and Julia Albuquerque then scored goals less than a
minute apart to put their side 3-0 ahead.
</P>
<P>
New Zealand netted the first goal through Jillaine Heather with
nine minutes left in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
New Zealand outscored Brazil 2-1 in the second quarter when Leah
Wistrand and Emma Jones both found the net as Brazilians slackened
off.
</P>
<P>
Brazil woke up from lethargy in the third quarter as Mariana
Secches scored twice and Danusa Da Silva contributed one goal, putting
the Brazilians 7-3 up.
</P>
<P>
Cristiana Pinciroli completed Brazil's tally one minute into the
fourth quarter. Wistrand scored to pull New Zealand to within four
with just under three minutes remaining in the match, but the team
would get no closer, falling by a final score of 9-5.
</P>
<P>
Brazilian coach Coutinho said that defence was the key to their
victory.
</P>
<P>
"Since we played against New Zealand in December we have been
working really hard on defense which was really strong today," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The Netherlands also tasted victory on Thursday, beating Greece
8-2. 
</P>
