<HEADLINE> Australian Coach Tips Top Diving Action </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PERTH, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The West Australia Institute of
Sports' head diving coach Steve Foley believes the best-ever
diving will be seen at the Perth world swimming championships.
</P>
<P>
"It's certainly the biggest and I think the depth of diving is
twice as good as it was here seven years ago," Foley was quoted by
West Australia Daily as saying.
</P>
<P>
This year, picking a winner in any of the events will not be
easy.
</P>
<P>
Foley said the standard of divers had increased and the
improvement had made it difficult to predict how the events would
unfold.
</P>
<P>
"It is a little bit unpredictable this time, In Rome, and the
last time in Perth, we tended to know who would battle out for the
gold and silver, whereas this time, even though there might be a
few favorites, anything is possible," he told West Australia Daily.
</P>
<P>
Chinese divers dominated the 1991 Perth world championships,
winning four of the six gold medals at stake.
</P>
<P>
It was a similar story in 1994 in Rome when Chinese women again
dominated, with Yu Zhuocheng winning the men's three-meter
sprinborad gold.
</P>
<P>
Although Russian, Canadian, German and American divers will be
among those challenging for top honors, China will again put up a
strong performance.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese are ranked No.1 in the world at the moment so they
will still be the ones to beat," Foley was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The addition of synchronized diving to the championships also
would be a major boost to the sport even though some people have
doubts over its inclusion.
</P>
<P>
"In the diving community it is probably taking a little bit of
time to get going," Foley said.
</P>
<P>
"But what we are finding is the public and media are absolutely
loving it, and when it is done properly it is fantastic," he
added. 
</P>
