<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Gem, Jewelry Export Earnings Down in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's gem and jewelry
export earnings in the first 11 months last year stood at 10
billion rupees (167 million U.S. dollars), a 13.7-percent drop
from a year earlier, according to figures released by the Gem and
Jewelry Authority Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Average monthly earnings were 911 million rupees (15.2 million
dollars) last year, down from about 1.06 billion rupees (17.6
million dollars) in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
In the whole year of 1996, the country earned a total of 12.7
billion rupees (211 million dollars) from gem and jewelry exports.
</P>
<P>
The largest share of the 1997 earnings came from cut diamonds,
which amounted to 7.78 billion rupees (129.7 million dollars),
while gem exports netted 1.36 billion rupees (22.7 million
dollars).
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka's major gem and jewelry markets last year were Japan,
the United States, Germany, Australia, Italy, Switzerland,
Singapore, Thailand and France.
</P>
<P>
The authority is confident that exports this year will show a
certain increase thanks to the implementation of the government's
tax relief measures in favor of the industry.
</P>
<P>
Under the tax exemption package, gold, gem and jewelry industry
will be exempted from income tax as well as the National Security
Levy. Imports of gold and gem are now also duty-free.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Gem and Jewelry Authority has been empowered to
collect a fee of 1 percent from the sale of rough stones and use
the proceeds to provide insurance cover to gem miners.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
