<HEADLINE> Malaysia Works to Boost Government Integrity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad Thursday launched a campaign to consolidate the
integrity of the government machinery.
</P>
<P>
The campaign was initiated by the government's Anti-Corruption
Agency (ACA).
</P>
<P>
At the launch, held at the agency's headquarters here,
Mahathir, who is also home minister, handed over a copy each of
the Anti-Corruption Act 1997 and the Prime Minister's Order 1/98
to eight senior officials representing the government's management
system.
</P>
<P>
The new act provides the ACA with additional powers to deal
with graft perpetrated with growing sophistication.
</P>
<P>
On the occasion, Mahathir reminded leaders and administrators
that perpetrating graft against the have-nots is a form of social
oppression.
</P>
<P>
Left unchecked, corruption may build up public resentment
against the establishment and subsequently undermine national
stability, he said.
</P>
<P>
"If the administration or its members collude with greedy
traders or entrepreneurs, the consequence will be escalating
operating and development costs," he said. "It is the people who
would have to bear these costs whereas most utilities meant for
them did not reach the public or became too expensive and
unaffordable."
</P>
<P>
Integrity and trustworthiness are part of good ethics in any
management system, Mahathir noted.
</P>
<P>
He added that an untrustworthy administration would be
unmanageable and in fact it could only lead to anarchy and erosion
of governance. 
</P>
