<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Why Southeast Asian Currencies Continue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Southeast Asian currencies have
tumbled again and again to breathtaking new depths since the first
trading day of the new year, and these is no sign that they may
regain their strength anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
Southeast Asian currencies started off the new year on the
wrong foot. Last Friday, the first trading day of 1998, the
Malaysian ringgit and the Philippine peso fell to fresh lows,
while the Indonesian rupiah and the Singapore dollar also slumped.
</P>
<P>
This week, the downward trend continued with most of southeast
Asian currencies hitting new historic lows. Most of the currencies
have lost at least 10 percent of their value against the dollar in
the past few days. The Japanese yen also fell to its record low in
six years.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that high demand for dollars by companies to
repay or prepare short-term debt payments is one of many factors
that caused regional currencies to fall to new record lows.
</P>
<P>
The short-term debt payment by corporations will continue to
cause short supply of dollars in the region, they added.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that 62.2 percent of Asia's debt to
international banks was due to mature within this year. As Much of
Southeast Asia's debt is short-term and has to be paid soon,
companies have to buy in dollars to meet future debt payments for
fear that the dollar will be more expensive later.
</P>
<P>
However, while companies scramble for dollars, few
international investors are willing to buy Asian shares and sell
dollars into Asia because slowing economies are expected to hit
profits in the region.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that the big gaps between the demand and the
supply of dollars are making the outlook for regional currencies
bleak in the coming months.
</P>
<P>
Besides, less central bank interventions in the currency
markets recently, due to a drying up of foreign reserves, also
failed to stop falls of regional currencies in the past few days.
</P>
<P>
In the Philippines, the country's foreign exchange reserves
have reduced to 9 billion dollars, just enough for three months of
imports, from 10.9 billion dollars last July, when a Thai currency
crisis began to spread to the rest of Southeast Asia. The
situation in other Southeast Asian countries proved no better.
</P>
<P>
Without enough foreign reserves, the central banks could hardly
succeed in their interventions in the foreign exchange market and
arrest falls of regional currencies. If they do, they most
probably might only suffer big losses, dealers said.
</P>
<P>
But lack of confidence in Southeast Asia's economic health and
political stability is one of the major factors that drive
regional currencies to record lows.
</P>
<P>
The fear of worsening in the debt crisis in South Korea and
Indonesia, political uncertainty and possible social unrest in
some countries have also limited buying interest of investors and
encouraged corporate hedging activities since the beginning of the
new year, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
During the last trading days, Indonesia's rupiah led the crash
of regional currencies as investors showed much concern about the
country's presidential elections in March and its national budget.
</P>
<P>
When the budget was unveiled on Tuesday, it was greeted with
disappointment and the rupiah quickly dived to new lows of 8,450
to the dollar against the opening 7,500/7,900.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that as Singapore is Jakarta's major trading
partner, the continuous drop of the rupiah will make the Singapore
dollar more vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
At present, Southeast Asian countries have entered the period
of economic reforms and re-adjustments to save their economies,
and the full negative effects of the six-month old crisis will
begin to bite the region.
</P>
<P>
The economic adjustments and the impact of the crisis would
lead to more unemployed people, more closures of banks and
corporations in the months ahead. Any bad news will cause jitters
in the region's currency market.
</P>
<P>
Economists said that the downward trend of regional currencies
is unlikely to change in the near term, and the situation might
only change in the later part of the year when the worst period of
the crisis is over.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980108.0265 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
