<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ciorbea Brushes off Minister's Reinstatement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Romanian Prime Minister Victor
Ciorbea categorically rejected Wednesday the Democratic Party's
request for former transport minister Traian Basescu's
reinstatement.
</P>
<P>
Ciorbea said in a statement following talks with coalition
parties: "This is unrealistic from the viewpoint of laws, politics
and morality."
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said the ruling coalition National Peasant's
Party, the National Liberal Party and the Hungarian Democratic
Union disagreed with Basescu's resumption of his post.
</P>
<P>
He also said that during the current period of reform and
transition, the cabinet shake-up was very normal. Even for the
prime minister, he would make no exception.
</P>
<P>
The Democratic Party, which is responsible for the nomination
of a transport minister, exerted pressure on the government,
saying that Basescu was the most appropriate nominee, and the
prime minister should not lose sight of Basescu's achievements
during his term of office.
</P>
<P>
Basescu was dismissed on December 29 following his remarks
that the Romanian government was incompetent. The former transport
minister said in an interview published at the same day that the
"government did not have the strength to take important
decisions." He criticized the "useless 18-hour long sessions" of
Ciorbea's cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Basescu, one of the more competent ministers in the government
and known for his frank talk, is the second minister to be sacked
within a week.
</P>
<P>
On December 23, Romania's foreign minister, Adrian Severin, was
asked to resign by President Emil Constantinescu after accusing
several politicians and newspaper editors of spying on behalf of
foreign powers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
