<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Bans Import of Live Birds From 17 Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka has banned the import
of live birds from 17 countries in an effort to prevent the
transmission of the deadly bird virus 'Avian Influenza", the
official newspaper Daily News said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Director of the Animal Production and Health Department Dr.
Seevali Ranavana was quoted by the paper as saying Wednesday that
live birds imports from 17 countries where the virus has been
reported were banned with immediate effect.
</P>
<P>
All imported birds found sick or dead will be incinerated at
the Colombo airport without any investigation while other imported
birds will be put under quarantine for a month, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, local firms involved in the import of birds have
been informed of the danger of the virus.
</P>
<P>
The virus has been found transmissive to human beings for the
first time in its 25-year history only recently.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
