<HEADLINE> University of Science and Technology Attracts Overseas Scholars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, January 8 (Xinhua) -- In recent years, more and more
overseas scholars have returned to work for the University of
Science and Technology of China (USTC).
</P>
<P>
The USTC, one of China's key universities located in Hefei,
capital of east China's Anhui Province, now has more than 400
professors or research fellows who returned from overseas. About
30 people who obtained doctoral degrees abroad choose USTC a
year. The university also invited nearly 100 overseas scholars to
be its part-time professors or senior scholars.
</P>
<P>
Returned scholars hold two thirds of USTC's positions in charge
of scientific research, teaching, school management, foreign
affairs and postgraduate education.
</P>
<P>
Thirty-four-year-old Ye Xiangdong was appointed vice-director
of USTC's school of engineering after he returned from Russia with
a doctor's degree.
</P>
<P>
Professor Sun Weidong, 36, was assigned to be in charge of the
USTC information center.
</P>
<P>
USTC worked out preferential policies to attract overseas
scholars. Those who decide to join USTC will have priority in
having research funds, labs, assistants as well as
apartments. USTC leaders even take the responsibility to find jobs
for the spouses of the overseas scholars and schools for their
children.
</P>
<P>
Doctor Zheng Yongfei from Germany was invited to work at USTC
in 1993. The university helped him successfully apply for national
research funding for outstanding young scientists the next
year. Zheng was then selected by the Chinese Academy of Sciences
(CAS), China's top natural science research body, as one of the
100 trans-century academic leaders.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
