<HEADLINE> Mexican State Governor Resigns in Wake of Massacre </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, January 7 (Xinhua) -- The governor of Mexico's
Chiapas state resigned on Wednesday in the wake of the December 22
massacre of 45 Indian refugees in this southern state.
</P>
<P>
The Chiapas state congress on Wednesday afternoon accepted
Julio Cesar Ruiz Ferro's resignation and named federal congressman
Robert Albores Guillen as the new governor.
</P>
<P>
Albores Guillen, 54, is an economist and a member of the ruling
Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI).
</P>
<P>
On December 22, 45 Indian refugees, most of them women and
children, were shot dead by gunmen allegedly linked to local
politicians of the ruling PRI, of which Ruiz Ferro is a member.
</P>
<P>
Ruiz Ferro was the second high-ranking official to resign
following the massacre. Federal Interior Minister Emilio Chuayffet
also resigned on Saturday. 
</P>
