<HEADLINE> Former Chinese Star Says China Remains No.1 in Diving </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PERTH, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Former Chinese diving star Li
Kongzheng said China remained the world top diving power despite its
lackluster performance last year.
</P>
<P>
"There is no country able to match China in depth of talents, said
Li, platform silver medalist in the 1984 Olympic Games and now head
coach of the U.S. diving team.
</P>
<P>
"China is certain to dominate the diving events at the Perth world
championships," he added.
</P>
<P>
China's prowess in diving has been affected by retirement of Fu
Mingxia, women's three-time Olympic gold medalist, and semi-retirement
of men's Olympic springborad champion Xiong Ni.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese world championship team is now led by 1992 Olympic
men's platform champion Sun Shuwei, who failed to qualify for the 1996
Games because of injuries, and Yu Zhuocheng, springboard runner-up to
Xiong in the Atlanta Olympics.
</P>
<P>
Threat to China, if any, will come from Russia which boasts two
world-class divers Dimitry Sautin and Vera Ilyina, Li said.
</P>
<P>
Sautin, 1996 Olympic champion in platfrom, fared well in 1997, the
year he concluded with a sweep of the World Cup platform and three-meter
springboard titles in Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
The Russian, who lost only once in his five encounters with Chinese
divers last year, made Chinese officials worried.
</P>
<P>
"Sautin is our top threat and he is nearly invincible," said
Chinese diving team leader Yuan Jianwei.
</P>
<P>
Li Kongzheng said that Yuan was overstating the situation.
</P>
<P>
"Last year, Chinese divers were focusing on the National Games in
Shanghai and it seemed they didn't pay much attention to other
competitions," Li said. "The year of 1998 will be different."
</P>
<P>
Ilyina is Russia's top women diver who triumphed in the U.S. Open,
Rome Grand Prix and European championships last year.
</P>
<P>
Li is one of those Chinese divers-turned-coaches who are coaching
outside of China.
</P>
<P>
"Chinese coaches are everywhere in the world, and in the United
States alone, there are over 40 Chinese coaches," said the world top
coach Xu Yiming, whose students have won nine Olympic and 26 world
championship gold medals for China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
