<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Alligator Thriving in Breeding Center, Languishing in Wild (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Population of Chinese alligator,
once on the verge of extinction, is now multiplying, but not in
the wild.
</P>
<P>
Latest reports from the country's largest alligator breeding
and research center in east China's Anhui Province shows that the
number of alligators there has shot up to more than 7,000, making
their dwelling place, the one-square-kilometer lake, a bit
"overcrowded".
</P>
<P>
The reptile is rare and precious because it is one of the few
species that were originated form the same period as dinosaurs but
have survived to this day.
</P>
<P>
It was listed as the endangered species by the United Nations
as early as in 1973 and has been under the state first-class
protection since then.
</P>
<P>
Alarmed by a field survey which revealed the alligator's
population had shrunk to less than 500, China built up the first
alligator's breeding center in 1979 in Anhui Province, the
reptile's main natural habitat.
</P>
<P>
Now the center boasts expertise from alligator's egg hatching
to baby alligator raising. The survival rate is more than 90
percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980108.0278 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Alligator Thriving in Breeding Center, Languishing in Wild (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
However, that alone cannot make wildlife experts free of
misgives.
</P>
<P>
"I'm afraid the wild alligator population is decreasing," said
Gu Changming, deputy director of the Wildlife Protection Agency in
Anhui. "It's still too early to say that they would not totally
disappear some day."
</P>
<P>
A recent survey convinced zoologists that the alligator could
no longer be found in its former habitat in Zhejiang Province,
also in east China.
</P>
<P>
That means wild Chinese alligators are now living only in
Anhui, in the 13 nature reserves set up in 1983. These reserves
cover a total water area of 433 square kilometers.
</P>
<P>
Gu said the use of farm chemicals and pesticide pollution have
poisoned the environment. "Worse still, some people don't have the
conscious to protect wild animals."
</P>
<P>
Some alligators would dig holes for hibernation in the rice
field or ponds, plus they live on fish and shrimps and eat up
ducks and geese they can find in the water. The angry farmers
often kill alligators within their reach.
</P>
<P>
The animal is actually very docile. They are pretty small, the
biggest one is about two meters and weighes about 20 kilograms, Gu
noted.
</P>
<P>
He said Anhui Province is preparing a field survey to find out
the wild Chinese alligator population and changes of their living
environment. The project will be joined by experts from the
National Wildlife Federation of the United States and the
International Union of Conservation of Natural Resources.
</P>
<P>
To boost wild alligator population, zoologists plan to release
to nature some raised in captive, Gu said.
</P>
<P>
"It's very difficult for alligators brought up in captive to
adapt to natural environment. We must risk that great many of them
should not survive," he said.
</P>
<P>
Experts agree that alligators kept in the breeding center will
ultimately face challenges from gene degeneration.
</P>
<P>
"We will make efforts to protect wild alligators," said Qing
Jianhua, director of Wildlife Protection Department in the
Ministry of Foresty. "That's the only way to retain the rare
species," he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980108.0279 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Baht's Instability Hampers Economic Revival: Banker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Olarn Chaipravat, president of
the Bankers' Association of Thailand, said on Wednesday that the
instability of the foreign exchange market had hampered efforts to
ease tight liquidity and revamp high interest rate policies.
</P>
<P>
He added that currency instability and the confidence crisis
had stalled efforts by policy-makers to revive the economy and
rendered previous economic theories useless, the Bangkok Post
Thursday quotes him as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said made the remarks when commenting on the continued slide
of the baht, which had been falling since the end of the New Year
holiday, creating new lows each day for three straight days.
</P>
<P>
The Thai currency closed at 53.20 to the US dollar on Wednesday
in the local market, compared with 52.20 on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Offshore, the baht dropped to as low as 54.50 to the dollar in
the morning session before gaining ground to trade late at
52.80/53.00.
</P>
<P>
The baht has lost more than 100 percent against the dollar
since it was floated on July 2 last year. The pre-float rate was
25.79 per dollar.
</P>
<P>
Olarn said demand for the dollar in the market was being driven
by a withdrawal of funds by foreign creditors and investors and by
a rush of local firms to hedge future debt obligations.
</P>
<P>
Normal daily trading in the local market totals about 300-400
million US dollars through 31 foreign and Thai commercial banks in
the country, with about 60 percent of transactions in the forward
market.
</P>
<P>
However, during the past few days forward transactions rose to
about 70 percent, reflecting the panic rush by locals for the
dollar, according to Olarn, who is also president of Siam
Commercial Bank.
</P>
<P>
Deeply concerned about the continued plunge of the baht,
Finance Minister Tarrin Nimmanhaeminda said Wednesday that the
government would announce new steps to deter speculation against
the Thai currency, but he refused to reveal details.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
