<HEADLINE> Thai Gold Shops to Contribute Gold to Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Each of the 10,000 gold shops
throughout Thailand have agreed to contribute one kilogram of gold
bullion to the government, according to Deputy Finance Minister
Pichet Trangsithpakdi.
</P>
<P>
The gold will be used to boost the country's reserves which are
drying up because of attacks by currency speculators.
</P>
<P>
Pichet was quoted Thursday by local press as saying that the
government intends to swap the gold for bonds. The new bond issue
is likely to carry an annual interest rate of 5 percent with a
maturity period of three to five years.
</P>
<P>
The Finance Ministry will appoint a committee to decide on
details of the bond issue next week., he said.
</P>
<P>
Under the terms of a 17.2-billion-US-dollar International
Monetary Fund-led economic rescue package, Thailand has to
maintain reserves in gold and hard foreign currencies worth at
least 25 billion dollars this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
