<DOCNO> XIE19980108.0287 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hungary, Poland, Czech Republic Seek U.S. Support </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Foreign ministers of Hungary,
Poland and the Czech Republic are seeking support from the United
States Senate in formally joining the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
The three ministers are expected to go to the U.S. between
February 9 and 11 to press the case with Senate members.
</P>
<P>
Hungarian Foreign Minister Kovacs Laszlo, who revealed this at
a press conference Wednesday, said there are no insuperable
difficulties for the parliaments of NATO members to ratify the
documents for the three nations to join NATO.
</P>
<P>
The alliance signed agreements with Hungary, Poland and the
Czech Republic on December 16, 1997, after it decided to absorb
the three countries as new members at its Madrid Summit last July.
</P>
<P>
However, the agreements still need to be ratified by the
parliaments of the NATO members before they become effective.
</P>
<P>
Currently, only the U.S. Senate has difficulty in approving the
agreements. The number of supporters in the Senate is less than a
half the total, which is necessary for the ratification.
</P>
<P>
The defense ministers of the three countries, who had been to
the United States earlier, hoped to persuade a majority of
senators to support their cause. 
</P>
</TEXT>
