<HEADLINE> Khatami Criticizes U.S. Policy Toward Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Mohammed
Khatami on Wednesday criticized the Iran policy adopted by the
U.S. government, saying that the American politicians still live
"with Cold War mentality."
</P>
<P>
"They continue to live with Cold War mentality and try to
create a perceived enemy," Khatami told Cable News Network
reporter Christiane Amanpour in an interview which is to be
broadcast on Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
Taking Iran as such a kind of perceived enemy, the
U.S. Congress has allocated 20 million U.S. dollars in an attempt
"to topple the Iranian government," the president said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the attitude of the United States toward Iran was
not a "civilized one."
</P>
<P>
He noted that "many progressive countries, including the
Europeans, are far more advanced in their foreign policies than
the United States."
</P>
<P>
The United States adopted a hostile policy against Iran and
tried to inflict economic damage upon it, Khatami said.
</P>
<P>
However, he added that such a policy also had a positive effect.
</P>
<P>
"It made us mainly focus on our domestic capabilities and
resources to advance our objectives."
</P>
<P>
The United States severed ties with Iran in 1979 after its
embassy in Tehran was stormed by a group of Islamic militants and
52 Americans there were held hostage for 444 days.
</P>
<P>
Because of the hostility of the United States toward Iran over
the past two decades, "there is a grave mistrust" between the two
countries, Khatami said.
</P>
<P>
He said if there is a dialogue between the two countries, the
United States "should respect the rights of each individual and
adopt an approach based on communicative rationality." 
</P>
</TEXT>
