<HEADLINE> Indonesian Rupiah Plunges to All-Time low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian rupiah plunged to
a record low of 8,450 against the U.S. dollar in the morning trade
Wednesday as the financial market gave a cool response to the
1998-99 state budget but recovered later to close at 7,900/8,100,
dealers here said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The weakened rupiah also dragged down share prices, pushing
down the Jakarta Stock Exchange's composite index below 400
points.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah hit a low of 8,450 against the greenback in the
morning session before recovering to 8,200/8,300 during the lunch
break.
</P>
<P>
The spot rupiah ended at 7,900/8,100 at the close compared to
an opening of 7,500/7,900.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah has persistently dropped since the financial turmoil
hit the country early July last year. The greenback has
appreciated 235 percent against the rupiah since then.
</P>
<P>
Negative reaction toward the draft state budget unveiled by
President Soeharto Tuesday night fueled the rush for dollars,
currency dealers said.
</P>
<P>
The demand for dollars did not only come from corporate
borrowers to pay maturing debts, but also from jittery individuals
and institutions, one dealer said.
</P>
<P>
Financial analysts said the draft state budget, which called
for a hefty 32.1 percent increase in both revenue and expenditures
to 133.5 trilling rupiah (one U.S. dollar equals 4,000 rupiah),
was too optimistic given the drop in the country's economic
performance.
</P>
<P>
Most people in the financial market think that some figures in
the government's state budget are too optimistic and unrealistic,"
an analyst said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the rupiah's free fall dragged down share prices,
with the benchmark composite index losing 1.99 percent to close at
394.23. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
