<HEADLINE> India, Italy Against Quick-Fix Formula on U.N. Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, January 8 (Xinhua)-- India and Italy have called for
greater democratization of the United Nations and strongly opposed
any quick-fix formula for expansion of the Security Council.
</P>
<P>
Talking to newsmen here Wednesday evening, visiting Italian
Prime Minister Romano Prodi, who arrived here Tuesday on a
three-day visit, said that Italy was not opposed to inclusion of
Germany and Japan in the Security Council, but any decision on the
expansion should be taken by the two-thirds of the total
membership of the world body and not merely by a majority of the
members present and voting.
</P>
<P>
As far as Italy is concerned, Prodi said that his country was
opposed to any increase in the number of permanent members of the
Security Council.
</P>
<P>
When asked about the Indian claim for a permanent seat in the
proposed expansion of the Security Council, he said Italy wished
India well in its endeavour, but it would not be easy for any
non-industrialized nation to get a permanent seat in the Security
Council.
</P>
<P>
He said that Italy and India should share their common
perception on the need for complete democratization of the
U.N. and were opposed to any quick fix formula for expansion of
the Security Council. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
