<HEADLINE> Philippine Government Posts Budget Surplus in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government posted
a budget surplus of 1.15 billion pesos (25.5 million US dollars)
in 1997 despite the tight fiscal scenario brought about by the
peso depreciation.
</P>
<P>
This was the country's fourth consecutive year of surplus since
1994, the Philippine Daily Inquirer Thursday quoted Finance
Secretary Roberto de Ocampo as saying.
</P>
<P>
The finance chief noted that the surplus was a "big turnaround"
from the 22-billion-peso (488.9-million-dollar) deficit expected
by the International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
But it was smaller than the original surplus target of 7
billion pesos (155.6 million dollars) for 1997 and the actual
surplus of 6.3 billion pesos (140 million dollars) in 1996, De
Ocampo said.
</P>
<P>
The surplus was made possible by last minute remittances from
government-owned corporations which had pledged to augment overall
collections by a combined 7.1 billion pesos (157.8 million
dollars) in dividends, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
