<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Police Chiefs Meet in Rome on Kurdish Refugees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, January 7 (Xinhua) -- National police chiefs from seven
European countries and Turkey arrived here Wednesday to discuss
ways to control the westward exodus of Kurdish refugees.
</P>
<P>
Top police officials from Italy, Turkey, Germany, France, the
Netherlands, Austria, Belgium and Greece were scheduled to meet
Thursday for one-day talks on illegal immigration, and better
controls of the European borders.
</P>
<P>
More than 1,200 immigrants, mostly Turkish and Iraqi Kurds,
arrived in southern Italy in recent weeks. They sparked a debate
that has since spread to other European Union countries on how to
deal with the exodus.
</P>
<P>
Italy has been accused of encouraging a further exodus after it
announced in late December that it would consider Kurds -- either
fleeing the war in southeastern Turkey or fighting in northern
Iraq -- eligible for political asylum.
</P>
<P>
Italian Prime Minister Romano Prodi said on Tuesday that his
country would examine favorably requests for political asylum from
Kurds on an individual, not a collective, basis.
</P>
<P>
In Brussels, the European Commission, the executive body of the
EU, said on Wednesday that the Schegen accord, which provides for
passport-free movement among nine EU states, would not in itself
help an influx of Kurdish refugees to spread throughout Europe.
</P>
<P>
But, the commission said: "The EU must speak with one voice and
act after coordinating its actions." If not, "weakness and
difficulties would arise in controlling refugees flows now and in
the future."
</P>
<P>
The Italian prime minister, traveling in India, Wednesday
called on the European countries to coordinate well in their
efforts to regulate the immigration.
</P>
<P>
"There cannot be an Italian policy, a French one and a German
one. We need a common policy," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980108.0295 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
