<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East China's "Dragon Head" of Pudong Gains Weight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Pudong, known as the "dragon
head" of China's dynamic Yangtze River Delta, is expected to
flaunt greater economic amplifying power as a result of an
increasing concentration of many of the most important markets.
</P>
<P>
Once the more backward side of China's leading commercial
metropolis separated from the downtown area by the Huangpu River,
Pudong is now home to the markets in property rights, grain and
edible oil, real estate and securities.
</P>
<P>
The relocation of the Shanghai Stock Exchange, one of China's
two bourses, to Pudong late last year has been widely deemed as a
symbol of the area as a rising financial and trade center.
</P>
<P>
Official sources say that Shanghai will also move the shipping,
technology and metal exchanges to Pudong, making it more matchable
to the role of an engine of economic growth in the Yangtze River
Delta.
</P>
<P>
While more important markets move to Pudong, investment in its
infrastructure has been growing rapidly. A loan of 612 million
yuan has been arranged for the construction of the Century Avenue,
a main line of Pudong.
</P>
<P>
All this indicates that Pudong has entered a new round of
development both in infrastructure and in its role as a financial
and trade center, said Zhao Qizheng, Vice Mayor and Director of
the Pudong New Area.
</P>
<P>
"As it gains weight as a 'dragon head', Pudong will lead
economic growth in Shanghai and the the Yangtze River Valley as a
whole," he said.
</P>
<P>
Improvement in the investment environment has turned Pudong
into a kind of magnet for foreign investors, experts here say.
</P>
<P>
To date 20 overseas banks and insurance companies have moved to
Pudong, with nine of the banks allowed to deal in the Chinese
currency on a trial basis. Pudong is also home to the headquarters
and regional offices of more than 70 multi-national corporations.
</P>
<P>
Currently, there are 4,900 overseas-funded enterprises in
Pudong, with investment totaling more than 23 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Pudong's amplifying power to the Yangtze River
Valley and further to the interior areas is becoming increasingly
apparent.
</P>
<P>
Customs figures show that more than 200 state-owned enterprises
were involved in the processing trade in Pudong at the end of last
November. Government ministries, the Shanghai Municipality and
other provinces and regions of China have set up 86 foreign trade
companies in Pudong.
</P>
<P>
The gross domestic product (GDP) of Pudong grew an estimated 18
percent to 60.8 billion yuan in 1997, with the service industry
accounting for one third of the total. The value of Pudong's GDP
grew 20.2 percent in 1996.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980108.0299 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexican President Names Woman As New Foreign Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Mexican President Ernesto
Zedillo on Wednesday named Rosario Green Macias as foreign
minister, the first woman to ever hold the post in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
The new woman minister was named to replace Jose Angel Gurria
who was reappointed as finance minister on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Macias, born in 1941, was an ambassador to the former
Democratic Republic of Germany in 1989-1990, the United Nations
under-secretary-general in 1994-95, and vice foreign minister of
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
The appointment was part of the cabinet reshuffle. Zedillo also
changed the posts of interior, finance and agriculture ministers
on January 3-5.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party said
the changes would help consolidate the national foreign policy,
help the economy recover, and help provide a more feasible
solution to the political crisis in the southeastern state of
Chiapas where 45 women and children were killed in
December. 
</P>
</TEXT>
