<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, January 8 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK -- Stocks on Wall Street finished only modestly lower
Wednesday after rebounding from a plunge.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average fell just 3.98 points at
7,902.27 after rebounding from an early afternoon deficit of
nearly 130 points.
</P>
<P>
Most broad-market indicators, except Nasdaq, also bounced back
from their lows in the heavily traded session.
</P>
<P>
Decliners outnumbered advancers by a 3-to-2 margin on the New
York Stock Exchange, with its volume totaling 655.88 million
shares, up from 617.61 million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
NEW YORK -- The U.S. dollar dropped more than 2 yen Wednesday
on fears that Japan would join an effort to hold down the surging
U.S. currency.
</P>
<P>
The dollar also fell against the German mark as traders
anxiously awaited details of a meeting between U.S. officials and
Japanese financial officials.
</P>
<P>
In late New York trading, the dollar was quoted at 131.25 yen,
down from 133.65 late Tuesday. It was the sharpest drop since
December 17, when the dollar fell nearly 6 yen after Japan's
central bank launched a surprise intervention to sell dollars for
the first time in more than five years.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- An American who was arrested on charges of spying
in Russia will not have to return to that country to face spying
charges, Senator Richard Bryan said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Bryan was quoted by the Associated Press as saying that
high-level diplomatic negotiations persuaded Russia to lift a
Saturday deadline for Richard Bliss to return.
</P>
<P>
However, Bliss, who works for San Diego-based Qualcomm,
technically remains charged with espionage, but doesn't have to
answer to Russian authorities, the senator said.
</P>
<P>
Bliss was charged with spying on November 25 and was released
December 5, and returned to San Diego Christmas night.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States will monitor Iranian President
Mohammed Khatami's interview with CNN very carefully, the White
House said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"We'll be listening very carefully to the interview," White
House spokesman Mike McCurry told reporters. "We've made it clear
that we would welcome an authorized transparent dialogue."
</P>
<P>
The interview, to be broadcast at 6 p.m. EST on Wednesday, will
be the first with a U.S. television network by an Iranian leader
since Iran sever the diplomatic relations with the United States
in 1980.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Main tasks for Russia this year is to keep the
improving economic situation under control, and to have "major
structural transformations in the country", Russian First Deputy
Prime Minister Boris Nemtsov said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview with the Interfax news agency Nemtsov
said such structural transformations are economic growth, slashed
taxes, and timely pay.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the country should finally abandon "the common stock"
principle of making social benefits available to all but actually
to no one and adopt a social security system, by which benefits
are addressed to those who really need them, Nemtsov said.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
LAGOS -- Nigeria has claimed that foreign governments are
behind the coup plot the government uncovered last December, in
which the head of state was slated to be assassinated.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary investigations of the alleged plot had "indicated
possible foreign involvement, which included the collusions of
their diplomatic missions with the coup plotters in the foiled
coup plot," said Foreign Minister Tom Ikimi, quoted by press
reports Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The actual details of the involvement was being investigated,
Ikimi told the corps of African ambassadors Tuesday in the capital
Abuja.
</P>
<P>
According to Ikimi, the coup suspects, including Chief of
General Staff Lt.-Gen. Oladipo Diya and 11 others, intended to
assassinate Head of State General Sani Abacha, some key military
officers and prominent civilians both in and out of the
government. 
</P>
