<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Evidence of Crimes of Unit "731" Discovered in Northeast China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, January 8 (Xinhua) -- A group of original written
materials which can prove the crimes committed by the Unit "731"
of the war-time Japanese army have been discovered by researchers.
</P>
<P>
Experts here said that these materials, written in Japanese,
are the first group of the kind so far found in China.
</P>
<P>
These materials, in 31 volumes, are all printed with the words
"special transfer", which means people arrested by the Japanese
army were sent to the Unit "731" for germ experiments through
special means.
</P>
<P>
Orders signed between 1940 and 1941 by the commander of the
Japanese Kwantung Army, which first invaded northeast China in
1931, and head of Japanese military police corps in northeast
China were also found in the 31 volumes of evidence materials.
</P>
<P>
All the 31 volumes of materials include complete information on
people who were arrested by the Japanese army, which include their
biographical notes, cause of arrest and trial, degree of education
and instructions on sending them to the Unit "731" for
bacteriological test. Some of the materials also have photos of
the arrested.
</P>
<P>
Unit "731" belongs to the Japanese aggressor troop's Kwantung
Army, with its headquarters based in Harbin, during the World War
II. The unit won an ill reputation for manufacturing germ weapons
based on experiments on living people.
</P>
<P>
Over 3,000 people were used for germ experiments by the Unit
"731", according to an arrested Japanese army official in charge
of germ experiments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980108.0304 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Job Layoffs Loom in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 8 (Xinhua) -- About 10,000 to 20,000 industrial
workers, mostly in the manufacturing sector, will lose their jobs
this year due to production cutbacks by companies hard hit by the
peso depreciation and soaring interest rates.
</P>
<P>
This was revealed by Raul Concepcion, president of the
Federation of Philippine Industries, who warned that the number of
workers who will be laid off will rise if the financial crunch
does not improve.
</P>
<P>
"As I said this is all market forces driven. The government
can't legislate or the executive can't put out rules and
regulations and say, no, don't cut back," local press reports
Thursday quoted Concepcion as saying.
</P>
<P>
In many cases, he said, permanent workers who will be retained
will have reduced working time of only three days a week.
</P>
<P>
Even in the public sector, there is a mass displacement of
personnel due to the severe belt-tightening measures ordered by
President Fidel Ramos, Concepcion said.
</P>
<P>
Ramos admitted on Wednesday that unemployment will unavoidably
rise this year due to the current currency crisis.
</P>
<P>
"We must expect that to happen. The government cannot afford to
say we don't need a cutback. We can't do that; otherwise we will
be subsidizing business," Ramos said.
</P>
<P>
Despite the economic slowdown, however, the government and the
private sector would continue to produce quality jobs for the
labor force, Ramos said.
</P>
<P>
Concepcion said he feared a surge in the number of unemployed
overseas Filipino workers (OFWs) due to cutbacks being implemented
by host countries.
</P>
<P>
However, Ramos remained confident there will be enough jobs for
OFWs particularly in the Middle East.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
