<HEADLINE> Iranian President Calls for Warmer Relations with U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Mohammed
Khatami has called for warmer relations between the American and
Iranian people as a way to ease two decades of hostility between
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
"Nothing should prevent dialogue and understanding between the
two nations, especially between their scholars and thinkers,"
Khatami told Cable News Network reporter Christiane Amanpour in an
interview in Tehran, which was broadcast on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"Right now, I recommend the exchange of professors, writers,
scholars, artists, journalists and tourists," he said.
</P>
<P>
It is the latest in a series of calls made by Khatami since he
won the presidential election in May, 1997.
</P>
<P>
As early as last December, Khatami proposed a "thoughtful
dialogue between the American people and the Iranian people,"
which received a positive response from United States President
Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
The United States severed ties with Iran in 1979 after its
embassy in Tehran was stormed by a group of Islamic militants and
52 Americans there were held hostage for 444 days. 
</P>
