<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 8,000-Year-Old Sites Found </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archeologists have
recently excavated ten ancient sites dating back 8,000 years,
which are expected to provide clues to the origin of Chinese
civilization.
</P>
<P>
These sites, including hundreds of tombs and houses, are the
oldest ones of the Neo-Stone Age found on the lower reaches of the
Yellow River, scattered in a 150-kilometer-wide area in Shandong.
</P>
<P>
Archeologists said that this is the first time for them to find
Neo-Stone Age sites which are so densely located.
</P>
<P>
One of the largest houses occupies a floor space of 50 square
meters, and is distinctly divided into a kitchen, bedrooms and
parlous. Pottery articles of different types as well as animal
bones have been unearthed.
</P>
<P>
In another site, archeologists found that in two tombs 14 and
19 people were buried together, respectively, hinting that there
existed a strange custom at that time, when matriarchy was quite
popular.
</P>
<P>
The Yellow River valley is believed to be the cradle of Chinese
civilization. Since early this century, archeologists have
unearthed thousands of prehistorical sites there, mainly belonging
to the famous Yangshao and Longshan Cultures of the Neo-Stone
Age.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980108.0311 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dengue Fever, Cholera Kill 90 Venezuelans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Dengue fever killed 40 people
last year in Venezuela and cholera claimed another 50, a report of
the Epidemiology Office of the Health Ministry said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A total of 32,391 people were affected by Dengue last year and
2,282 by cholera, the report added.
</P>
<P>
Of the total cases of dengue, 6,109 people, or 19 percent, were
of the hemorrhagic type.
</P>
<P>
Over the first week of this year, another 1,253 people infected
with dengue were registered.
</P>
<P>
Experts attributed the outbreak and spread of the two diseases
to a decline in the budget for the country's health and
epidemic-control programs.
</P>
<P>
Dengue and cholera were declared epidemic respectively in
Venezuela in November and June last year and the authorities have
not yet removed the alert.
</P>
<P>
Experts said that a social re-organization is the only way to
overcome the epidemics of dengue and cholera which stem from
poverty and less health attention. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
