<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northeast China City Finds More Water Resources </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Residents in Changchun,
capital city of northeast China's Jilin Province, are expected to
say goodbye to the days when they are troubled by shortage of
drinking water resources.
</P>
<P>
This is the result of the great efforts the local government
has made in developing water supply projects in urban areas in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
Changchun, a famous cultural city and a center of Chinese film
making and automobile manufacturing industries, is one of the
country's 50 cities which are short of water resources.
</P>
<P>
To resolve the problem, the city government has sped up the
construction of water supply projects by introducing foreign funds.
</P>
<P>
The Changchun Industrial Water Supply Plant, a project
involving Japanese investment, and the Third Water Treatment
Plant, built with a loan from the World Bank, can raise the daily
water supply volume to 1.06 million cubic meters from the former
590,000 cubic meters when they are operational.
</P>
<P>
In the past five years, the city extended the total length of
its running water supply pipes from 99,600 km to 129,840 km, with
the number of people who use running water rising to 1.79 million
from the original 1.6 million.
</P>
<P>
A project to divert water from the Songhua River into Changchun
city is going on smoothly and is expected to become operational
very soon.
</P>
<P>
The project, with an investment of 1.88 billion yuan, will
enable the city to have enough water for daily living and
industrial use.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
