<HEADLINE> Brazil Increases Mine Exploration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Brazil invested 120 million
U.S. dollars in mine exploration last year, becoming second-placed
as the most attractive nation of the region for foreign investors
on mineral exploration after Chile, the Mining Exploration
Company of Brazil reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Its President Carlos Oiti Berbert explained in Rio de Janeiro
that of the total invested, 33 percent was foreign capital.
</P>
<P>
He announced that investment for mine exploration in Brazil
could reach 200 million dollars yearly by 2000, 80 percent expected
to come from foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
Berbert said that Brazil is recovering its rank at mineral
exploration worldwide after it dropped to the 9th rank in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Brazil had invested an average of 150 million dollars per
year, 41 of them being foreign money, until 1988, but fell then
into a declining phase.
</P>
<P>
Berbert said that his country still has brilliant prospects for
mineral development because "Brazil's 50 percent of mineral areas
still remain unexplored, particularly in the Amazonic."
</P>
<P>
Brazil is expected to have directed some 30 billion dollars to
the mining industry by 2000, of which four billion will have come
from foreign investors, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
