<HEADLINE> Re-employment Going Smoothly in South China Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Guangzhou, south China's
biggest industrial center, has been successful in helping laid-off
workers find new jobs and having a re-employment rate above 55
percent.
</P>
<P>
The city has established a system to ensure that laid-off
workers, who mainly come from financially troubled state
enterprises, can rely on help from job agencies and accept
re-training for other posts, according to Jiang Yun, deputy
director of the Labor Department of Guangzhou, capital of
Guangdong Province.
</P>
<P>
For example, the department jointly held a coach
driver-training class for laid-off workers with a public bus
company, which enabled many laid-off workers to find jobs.
</P>
<P>
Guangzhou set aside 25 million yuan (3.12 million U.S. dollars)
in early 1997 to help laid-off workers. The city since has doubled
the allocation.
</P>
<P>
More than 8,000 laid-off workers benefited from the fund last
year, 60 percent of whom have been re-employed, said Jiang.
</P>
</TEXT>
