<HEADLINE> U.S. Urban Students Have Less Skills for College </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Less than 20 percent of high
school teachers in inner city schools in the United States are
confident that their students have the skills to do well in
college, said a report on urban education released on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Urban districts are those in which 75 percent or more of the
households served by a district are in the central city of a
metropolitan area.
</P>
<P>
Urban schools, with 11 million students, account for one-fourth
of the nation's public school population. About 43 percent of the
nation's minority children and 35 percent of the poor children
attend urban public schools.
</P>
<P>
The report by Education Week newspaper found that the low
expectations were coupled with low performance by students on
national measures of reading, math and science.
</P>
<P>
By examining results from national standardized tests of
fourth-grade reading in 1994, it was found that 43 percent of the
inner city school children scored at or above a basic level,
compared with 63 percent elsewhere and 58 percent for the nation
as a whole.
</P>
<P>
In the 1996 test for eighth-grade math, 42 percent of city
children scored at or above the basic level, compared with 63
percent elsewhere and 62 percent nationally.
</P>
<P>
Similarly in the eighth-grade science test, 38 percent of the
students were at or above basic level, compared with 65 percent
elsewhere and 61 percent nationally.
</P>
<P>
Education experts attribute the unsatisfactory performance of
urban students partly to classroom crowding and shortages of
teachers and guidance counselors, in addition to kids from
difficult or poor situations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
