<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Government to Cut Costs in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government has
planned to slash its spending and seek new loans from abroad as
the peso fell to a new low and stocks tumbled.
</P>
<P>
"I think we have some preliminary figures which show about 25
percent cutback in both capital outlay and other expenses," local
press reports Thursday quoted Finance Secretary Robert de Ocampo
as saying.
</P>
<P>
"We have to be selective in terms of which infrastructure
projects we will prioritize," De Ocampo said.
</P>
<P>
He said government agencies had been asked to study areas where
they could cut back expenses.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government is negotiating for up to 600 million
US dollars from the World Bank and the Asian Development Bank to
beef up its international reserves. Last month, the government
said it hoped to get 2 billion dollars from the International
Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
The peso has depreciated by more than 70 percent against the
dollar since the regional currency crisis began in July 1997. The
peso fell to a record low of 46.50 per dollar on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The country's international reserves have fallen to 9 billion
dollars from a record high of 12 billion in March, mainly because
its costly and unsuccessful attempt to prevent the peso from
further plunging.  
</P>
</TEXT>
