<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Twin-hump Camel Is Suited For Cold Desert </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The reason single-hump camels
live in the scorching deserts of Africa and most twin-hump camels
live in the cold deserts of northwestern China has to do with the
ability to adapt, Chinese scientists have said.
</P>
<P>
Most of the 19 million camels in the world have one hump and
live in the deserts of northern and western Africa. There are also
about two million camels with two humps, 400,000 of which inhabit
the regions of Xinjiang, Gansu, and Inner Mongolia in northern and
northwestern China.
</P>
<P>
Wang Jianlin, a professor at Gansu Agricultural University, who
has studied camels for years, said that twin-hump camels have
thick skin that can protect them from cold weather, and hair that
is long in the winter and short in the summer.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the two humps, which store fat and nutrients,
other parts of the animal hold large amounts of fat, allowing it
to adapt to the cold weather in northern and northwestern
China, Wang explained.
</P>
<P>
Single-hump camels contain much less fat in their bodies. But,
Wang said, the two still have a lot in common. Their sweat glands
are not very well developed, something that helps them retain
water, and they can drink as much as 80 kilograms of water at one
time, and can live on what their bodies store for more than 20
days.
</P>
<P>
Gansu Agricultural University started doing research on camels
in the 1950s to look for ways to protect the animal, but, Wang
said: "Research on the physical structure of camels is still
not enough."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
