<HEADLINE> World Bank Project Benefits Northwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YINCHUAN, January 8 (Xinhua) -- A World Bank poverty relief
project in northwest China has greatly benefitted local residents
since its initiation last October.
</P>
<P>
The six-year project, which covers 26 poverty-stricken counties
in Sichuan and Shaanxi provinces, and the Ningxia Hui Autonomous
Region, involves 2.3 million people and a funding of three billion
yuan, including a World Bank loan of 180 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The program in Ningxia was designed to provide assistance to
235,000 farmers in four state-designated poverty-stricken
counties. Construction of the first phase project is almost
finished, and more than 6,000 rural families in 85 villages in the
four aforementioned counties have witnessed substantially improved
standards of living.
</P>
<P>
Offices opened by the autonomous region in related villages,
which bear responsibility for all work, have launched land
development, infrastructure, and village enterprise projects.
</P>
<P>
In addition, other projects involving improvements to terraced
fields, digging wells, breeding livestock and planting both grass
and trees are currently underway.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank project will lead to the development of
approximately 20,000 ha of terraced fields and grain production on
18,000 ha, as well as the plantation of cash crops on 2,800 ha,
26,000 wells, and three potable water processing projects. In
addition, related programs will help increase the average annual
per capita income of farmers to over 500 yuan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
