<HEADLINE> New York Stocks Stabilized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Stocks on Wall Street finished
only modestly lower today after rebounding from a plunge.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average fell just 3.98 points at
7,902.27 after rebounding from an early afternoon deficit of
nearly 130 points.
</P>
<P>
Most broad-market indicators, except Nasdaq, also bounced back
from their lows in the heavily traded session.
</P>
<P>
Decliners outnumbered advancers by a 3-to-2 margin on the New
York Stock Exchange, with its volume totaling 655.88 million
shares, up from 617.61 million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list fell 2.58 to 964.00 after
recovering from a 14-point slide, and the NYSE composite index
fell 1.15 to 506.18.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq composite index fell 18.44 to 1,561.70, and the
American Stock Exchange composite index fell 0.74 to 674.29. The
Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 3.31 to 429.79.
</P>
<P>
Investors continued to worry about greater economic losses,
with more people joining the selling spree.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's main stock market index tumbled nearly 6 percent
today and several other markets in Southeast Asia also fell as
various currencies in that region slipped to new lows.
</P>
<P>
Bonds also struggled today. The yield on the 30-year Treasury
rose to 5.79 percent after settling at a record 5.71 percent on
Tuesday. 
</P>
