<HEADLINE> U.S. Dollar Drops Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, January 7 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar dropped more
than 2 yen Wednesday on fears that Japan would join an effort to
hold down the surging U.S. currency.
</P>
<P>
The dollar also fell against the German mark as traders
anxiously awaited details of a meeting between U.S. officials and
Japanese financial officials.
</P>
<P>
In late New York trading, the dollar was quoted at 131.25 yen,
down from 133.65 late Tuesday. It was the sharpest drop since
December 17, when the dollar fell nearly 6 yen after Japan's
central bank launched a surprise intervention to sell dollars for
the first time in more than five years.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. currency also was changing hands at 1.8223 marks, down
from 1.8314.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of Japan has reportedly intervened three times since
that first action, the latest being a reported 2 billion U.S.
dollar effort on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Despite the yen's rise, other Asian currencies showed no signs
of recovery Wednesday. The Malaysian ringgit, Indonesian rupiah
and the New Taiwan dollar all fell again to record lows.
</P>
<P>
Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Tuesday:
1.4758 Swiss francs, down from 1.4825; 6.0957 French francs, down
from 6.1284; 1,789.25 Italian lire, down from 1,799; and 1.4330
Canadian dollars, up from 1.4317.
</P>
<P>
The British pound was quoted at 1.6273 U.S. dollars, up from
1.6268 U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
