<HEADLINE> American Will not Return to Face Espionage Charges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 6 (Xinhua) -- An American who was arrested
on charges of spying in Russia will not have to return to that
country to face spying charges, Senator Richard Bryan said today.
</P>
<P>
Bryan was quoted by the Associated Press as saying that
high-level diplomatic negotiations persuaded Russia to lift a
Saturday deadline for Richard Bliss to return.
</P>
<P>
However, Bliss, who works for San Diego-based Qualcomm,
technically remains charged with espionage, but doesn't have to
answer to Russian authorities, the senator said.
</P>
<P>
Bliss was charged with spying on November 25 and was released
December 5, and returned to San Diego Christmas night.
</P>
<P>
"That was a pretty good indication that he was not a spy,"
Bryan said. "No country would allow a spy to return to the country
of their origin." 
</P>
