<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Governor, District Attorney Vow to Try Bombing Criminals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Oklahoma Governor Frank
Keating and Oklahoma City District Attorney Robert Macy have vowed
to try convicted bombers Timothy McVeigh and Terry Nichols on
state murder charges.
</P>
<P>
Macy said he is ready to lay fresh charges against the two men.
Nichols today escaped the death penalty for his role in the April
19, 1995 bombing of the Alfred Murrah Federal Building in Oklahoma
City.
</P>
<P>
Judge Richard Matsch dismissed a jury in Denver, Colorado,
today after it could not agree on a punishment. Matsch must now
decide Nichols' fate, following his conviction in December last
year on charges of conspiracy to murder and involuntary
manslaughter.
</P>
<P>
McVeigh already faces the death penalty, having been found
guilty of first degree murder in the deaths of eight federal
employees of the 168 bombing victims.
</P>
<P>
Of a state prosecution, "We're ready to go. It's not over yet.
That's the important message that needs to go out now. Hopefully
we'll have a different verdict," Macy was quoted as saying by
United Press International.
</P>
<P>
Keating condemned the jury's indecision, saying it did not
square with the first Nichols verdict, "I certainly don't agree
with the second decision, essentially throwing up their hands and
walking away. Anybody involved in any way in this crime deserves
the death penalty that will be imposed at an Oklahoma trial,"
according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Many survivors and relatives of victims also want a separate
state prosecution, in which all 168 victims, and not only eight
federal officials, would be named. Some, believing the jury gave
up too easily, want the death penalty for Nichols, the report
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
