<DOCNO> XIE19980108.0340 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Urges Better Child Care </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 7 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
today proposed a 21.7 billion-dollar package of grants and tax
breaks to help working families find affordable care for children.
</P>
<P>
Clinton announced the plan before an audience of parents and
children in the White House.
</P>
<P>
Clinton called his proposal a fiscally responsible attempt to
help American families, and he urged Republicans in Congress to
embrace it.
</P>
<P>
The key element would be a major expansion of the state block
grant program offering subsidies for child care. Clinton's plan
would add 7.5 billion dollars to the program over five years,
administration officials said.
</P>
<P>
The proposal also would expand the reach of the program to
lower-income families, officials said. The program now largely
helps Americans trying to move from welfare to work.
</P>
<P>
Congress would have to approve all the money for Clinton's
proposals, and Republicans have resisted earlier attempts to
expand social spending. The administration expects nearly a third
of the money to come from an expected settlement between the
government and the tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
Another major component would be 5.2 billion dollars over five
years to expand the income tax credit that parents can take for
child care expenses.
</P>
<P>
Clinton also earmarked money to expand an after-school program
run by the Education Department and called the 21st century
community learning center program.
</P>
<P>
Another initiative calls for early-learning fund, grants to
communities and public-private partnerships for early childhood
development.
</P>
<P>
Clinton also proposed tax credits for businesses that build or
expand child care facilities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
