<HEADLINE> European Shares Keep on Declining </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Leading stock markets in Europe
kept on falling and most of them ended lower Wednesday, depressed
by a weaker Wall Street and continued worries over the Asian
currency crisis.
</P>
<P>
Britain's major shares ended sharply down with profit- taking
largely behind the fall on the back of Asian currency turmoil. The
FTSE 100 index finished the session at 5,224.1, lossing 40.3
points on the day.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that a fresh downturn in New York also put
pressure on stocks as Far Eastern woes continued to unsettle
investors.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a sharp reversal on the Hong Kong market upset HSBC
shares.
</P>
<P>
The Frankfurt market, which ends before Wall Street opens,
closed firmer and near the day's highs, helped by a strong dollar
and futures as well as by hopes of a firmer Dow, with the DAX-30
index 38.91 points higher at 4,391.54.
</P>
<P>
But in later screen-based trade, the IBIS DAX index ended down
20.07 points at 4,339.98.
</P>
<P>
The CAC-40 index in Paris finished 31.00 points lower at
3,006.73 as the French market's recovery stalled.
</P>
<P>
Losses on Wall Street and worries over developments in Asia
were key factors in afternoon trading. 
</P>
</TEXT>
