<HEADLINE> U.S to Retain Sanctions against Firms Dealing with Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 7 (Xinhua) -- The United States said on
Wednesday that it is "serious" to impose sanctions on French
energy company Total and its partners for a 2 billion US dollar
gas deal with Iran.
</P>
<P>
The remarks was made by Under Secretary of State Stuart
Eisenstat when he delivered a speech at the National Press Club
in Washington, D.C..
</P>
<P>
"Let me emphasize that we are serious about implementing this
law and have not ruled out any options. Sanctions remain a real,
live option in both cases if these activities and found to be
sanctionable," he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Eisenstat said the sanctions threat will also apply to Canada's
Bo Valley Energy for its 212 million dollar project to develop
Iran's Balal offshore oil field.
</P>
<P>
The undersecretary of state, who is in charge of economic
affairs, disclosed that the State Department is launching a
formal review of the controversial sanction policy, which has
become a major source of tension between the United States and
its European allies and Russia.
</P>
<P>
"The State Department is reviewing the use of this
controversial tool," he said. And the State Department is
establishing a sanctions "team" to find ways to make sanctions
more effective in foreign policy, he added.
</P>
<P>
The United States is involved in negotiations with France and
Russia in an effort to avoid sanctions looming in the case of the
$2 billion gas deal with Iran by the French energy company Total
and over charges that Russian firms and research centers have
aided Tehran ballistic missile program.
</P>
<P>
Undersecretary of State Thomas Pickering is in Paris trying to
work out a deal with French officials for the purpose of avoiding
the looming sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Clinton administration is "very carefully"
listening to Iranian President Mohammed Khatami's interview with
CNN, to be broadcast at 6 p.m. EST so that it could determine
whether there is any possibility for conciliation between the
two countries, which has severed the diplomatic relations in
1980.  
</P>
</TEXT>
