<HEADLINE> Pro-Government Rebel Forces in Sudan Form Union </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of south Sudan's
pro-government rebel forces have agreed on the unification of
their forces under the name of "Sudan Defense Force," a faction
source said here today.
</P>
<P>
An unnamed official source of the United Democratic Salvation
Front said the leaders of those factions held a meeting Tuesday
on this purpose.
</P>
<P>
They charged Riyak Mashar, chairman of the coordination council
of the southern states, with forming a committee that will undertake
the unification process, said the source.
</P>
<P>
Mashar, who is also chairman of the front which comprises all
rebel signatories of the Khartoum peace agreement with the
government last April, was quoted as saying that the unification
will help expand the scope of peace, establish security and
stability in south Sudan.
</P>
<P>
The Khartoum government signed a peace agreement with four
small southern rebel factions last April in a bid to put an end
to the 13-year civil war.
</P>
<P>
The largest anti-government group operating in south Sudan, the
Sudan People's Liberation Army (SPLA) did not sign the accord.
</P>
</TEXT>
