<DOCNO> XIE19980108.0344 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Insists on Open-Border Policy After Refugee Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, January 7 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU)'s
executive body, the European Commission, said today that an
open-border policy between nine EU member countries should be
maintained.
</P>
<P>
The Schengen accord has nothing to do with the recent influx of
Kurdish refugees into Italy, an EU member state, the commission
indicated today.
</P>
<P>
But the EU executive emphasized that "weaknesses and
difficulties" would arise in controlling refugee flows in the
future unless the EU adopted long-overdue draft legislation and
acted in harmony on asylum and immigration matters.
</P>
<P>
More than 1,000 refugees, mostly Kurdish people, arrived in
Italy last week aboard two boats from Turkey. More are said to be
on the route.
</P>
<P>
The arrival has caused fears among EU members, especially
Italy's EU neighbors, of an influx of illegal immigrants from
Italy.
</P>
<P>
Migration experts gathered here today to start preparing an
action plan to prevent influx of refugees into Italy, which is
likely to derail the EU's open-borders project.
</P>
<P>
The commission stressed at the meeting that the Schengen
passport-free zone, which involves a total of nine countries at
present, was not "a sieve," according to a spokesman for the EU
executive.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that Schengen was the achievement of free
movement which was flanked by efficient measures to control
illegality and criminality. "It works," he said.
</P>
<P>
Diplomats said that the action plan would be under preparation
for a few more days before being adopted by EU foreign ministers
later this month. It will reportedly involve more effective border
controls, consular cooperation and police cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the EU needed a comprehensive approach to
not only solve the current problem but also anticipate future
problems.
</P>
<P>
The Schengen agreement now has Belgium, France, Germany,
Luxembourg, the Netherlands, Portugal and Spain as its full
members. Italy and Austria have scrapped passport controls for
inter-Schengen flights but their land control borders are due to
disappear in March. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
