<HEADLINE> EU Opens Inquiry Into Air France Deal With US Airlines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, January 7 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU)'s
executive body, the European Commission, said today that it was
starting an investigation into cooperation accords of Air France
with both Continental Airlines and Delta Airlines.
</P>
<P>
Air France, the French flag carrier, agreed to cooperate with
Continental and Delta, two U.S. airline giants, respectively in
November 1996 and June 1997.
</P>
<P>
The commission's decision will add to a long list of global
aviation pacts which the EU's antitrust watchdog has been
investigating for 18 months and of which the most controversial
one was the alliance between British Airways and American
Airlines.
</P>
<P>
Air France agreed to cooperate with the two airlines giants in
code and revenue-sharing agreements, coordination of routes and
flight frequencies, and joint participation in their frequent
flyer programs.
</P>
<P>
However, the agreements have been implemented only partially
pending negotiations between France and the United States on
liberalizing the air transport market between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The commission maintains that an agreement of this type might
comprise anti-competitive aspects, just like the alliances signed
by other European airlines with their U.S. counterparts for which
proceedings have been opened.
</P>
<P>
It said in a statement that it must analyze the effect of these
agreements on competition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
