<HEADLINE> US Says Algeria Accepts Outside Probe Into Killings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Algeria has agreed to the
idea of an outside investigation into violence in the country, the
U.S. State Department said today.
</P>
<P>
"They told us that they would accept a visit" by a human rights
investigator to look into recent mass killings, spokesman James
Rubin said at a regular briefing.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that outsiders may provide additional information
on the scope and source of these heinous crimes," he added. And he
stressed the international probe was aimed at seeking the facts,
not blaming the Algerian government.
</P>
<P>
The United States called Monday for a inquiry into the recent
massacres in Algeria and Rubin said today the Algerian government
had accepted "in principle" the idea of a visit by a U.N. envoy
for the investigation.
</P>
<P>
But his statement conflicted with word from the Algerian
capital that the Algerian government was rejecting the U.S. call.
And reports said the Algerian government Tuesday summoned U.S.
ambassador Cameron Hume to the Foreign Ministry.
</P>
<P>
"The American diplomat was reminded of Algeria's categorical
rejection of any idea of an international commission," the
official Algerian news agency APS said.
</P>
<P>
But Rubin told reporters that the Algerians told Hume during
the meeting "they would accept a visit by a U.N. human rights
rapporteur."
</P>
<P>
Algerian newspapers said that about 1,000 people had been
killed since the Muslim holy month of Ramadan started on December
30. And Algerian security forces said that 62 people had died in
three new massacres in the Western province of Relizane.
</P>
<P>
The killings have brought concerns from the outside world and
the West has called on the United Nations to send a special envoy
to Algeria to assess the situation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
