<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Belgium Condemns Massacres in Algeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Belgium today denounced
massacres which recently took place in Algeria and blamed the
African country for being reluctant to allow Western countries to
help it curb the violence.
</P>
<P>
Belgian foreign ministry spokesman Andre Querton called the
massacres "blind violence" at a weekly media briefing held
Wednesday in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said Belgium was coordinating its exact position
on the massacres, blamed mainly on Islamist fundamentalists, with
other EU member countries.
</P>
<P>
Robin Cook, British foreign secretary, Wednesday said the EU
wanted to discuss with Algerian authorities how to end the wave of
guerrilla mass killings. More than 65,000 people had been killed
in the country's six-year-long civil war.
</P>
<P>
An international commission of inquiry has been proposed to
cooperate with the Algerian government in order to end the wave of
massacres in the north African country. But Querton said Algerian
authorities had repeatedly said it would not cooperate with such
an organization.
</P>
<P>
Sweden has suggested that Algeria itself establish a
parliamentary commission of inquiry on the civil strife while
Germany has proposed the EU offer help in fighting terrorism and
aiding the victims of violence, according to the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
However, the Algerian government has reportedly turned down all
bids for foreign investigation or mediation with the Muslim
rebels, saying that they were unacceptable interference. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
